<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Obit-Cafritz 1stLd-Writethru   11-30 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Cafritz, 1st Ld-Writethru,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prominent Washington Hostess Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS date in lead; picks up 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``Mrs.
Cafritz...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gwendolyn Cafritz, known as one of Washington's
top hostesses for several decades, died of cancer Tuesday at her
home. She was 78.
   Mrs. Cafritz gave elegant and lavish parties from the end of
World War II until the early 1970s, when failing health curtailed
her social schedule.
   Her husband, millionare Washington real estate developer and
businessman Morris Cafritz, died in 1964. After his death, she
became president of the Cafritz Foundation, which gave about $6
million a year to local organizations devoted to the arts, community
service, health and education.
   The Cafritz party guests ranged from the Duke and Duchess of
Windsor _ who once danced on a transparent dance floor lighted from
below _ to Supreme Court justices. But President Harry Truman
favored Mrs. Cafritz's competitor, Washington ``hostess with the
mostess'' Perle Mesta.
   Mrs. Cafritz, born in Budapest, Hungary, moved to Washington in
the 1920s and began entertaining in post-World War II years. In June
1986 she gave her last large party, which was described as a ``trip
back into Washington social history.''
   In 1969, four masked men broke into her mansion, bound and gagged
Mrs. Cafritz and others, and escaped with more than $1 million in
furs and jewelry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
