<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SweetLiberty     11-30 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweet Liberty,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Humorist Jerry Clower Is Back Home at Route 4, Liberty
^Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIBERTY, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Knock 'em out John'' if Jerry Clower
isn't right back on Route 4 in the very backwoods the country humor
king visits in tall tales of his youth in rural Mississippi.
   Clower's back with the Ledbetters, the Eubanks, the prize hounds
and his raccoon-chasing cousins. It's where his mama cooked chicken
for the preacher and his uncle's prize cows were gunned down in a
bird hunt gone sour.
   His new house in the Eastfork community between Liberty and
McComb in southern Mississippi must share the title ``home'' with
Yazoo City, where he and his wife of 41 years raised ``four head of
children'' and where Clower began his career as a country humorist.
   ``But it was right here at Route 4 Liberty where I first saw the
light of day,'' Clower said of his return to rural Amite County.
``We lived in Yazoo City for 35 years and we have a lot of friends
there. But after we put the last of our kids in college, mama and I
decided to go back home.''
   The Clower home is a two-story structure with large white
columns, a ``great big brick porch, hardwood flooring and a
fireplace,'' Clower said.
   ``My mother lives right here in the old home place, and my
brother Sonny, who choked the rat to death at rat killin' time, is
here too,'' said Clower, a member of the Grand Ole Opry who has
traveled the globe spreading smiles about life growing up in the
country.
   ``It's where we used to take corn to the grist mill and sugar
cane to the molasses mill,'' Clower said. ``Times have changed and
now we go to the store to buy our meal and molasses. But the sun
still comes up in the same place and the Amite River is still
running.''
   Clower said he is considering naming his 20th album with MCA
Records: ``Let There Be Liberty.''
   ``More people have died over that one word, liberty, than any
word in the history of mankind,'' said Clower, who played football
at Mississippi State before joining the Navy in World War II and
earning three battle stars and a unit citation for bravery before
age 19. ``I know what it takes to keep freedom.''
   The move does not mean Clower will be cutting back on a schedule
that includes about 200 concerts a year.
   ``I'm just as surprised about my success as a lot of other
people,'' Clower said. ``I was at the North Carolina State Fair in
Raleigh the other day and the guy who introduced me told me this was
the largest crowd at the fair on a Sunday night in 121 years.
   ``When you keep bringing them in like that, you've got to keep
going out there and doing what you love to do.''
   But the humorist said he was already enjoying his return to Amite
County.
   ``There's a special feeling about this place,'' he said. ``I woke
up the last two mornings and a couple of deer have been standing in
the back yard. There's just no place like home.''
</TEXT>
