<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChristmasScare     11-30 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Christmas Scare,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confusion Raises Fear That Christmas Is Canceled In Bethlehem, Pa.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power outage that shut the lights on the
town's Christmas tree and a name mix-up led Bethlehem residents to
fear someone had stolen their Christmas.
   An hour after the tree-lighting ceremony Sunday in this eastern
Pennsylvania town, the lights went out.
   On Monday, residents heard broadcast reports that Christmas in
Bethlehem was canceled.
   By Tuesday, even though the Christmas lights were again shining
brightly, at least a dozen residents were concerned enough to call
the chamber of commerce to see if, indeed, the town's celebration
was off.
   Vangie Sweitzer, the chamber's assistant director, said she told
the callers, ``Yes, the celebration in Bethlehem is canceled, but
it's the other one.''
   ``The other one'' is Jesus' birthplace, in the West Bank, the
center of a Palestinian uprising against Israel's occupation.
   The deputy mayor, Hanna Nasser, announced Monday the town's
Christmas celebration was being canceled because of the uprising.
   ``No one happened to notice the dateline,'' Ms. Sweitzer said.
``We assured everyone that Christmas is on in Bethlehem,
Pennsylvania.''
   The confusion made some businessmen here nervous, she said,
because the town has a large tourist trade at Christmas time. She
estimated 45,000 people come to the town during December to see the
city's 60,000 Christmas lights.
   ``We haven't had any bus tours cancel,'' she said.
   One call came from a New Jersey woman who said she travels to the
town each year.
   ``I told her not to worry,'' Ms. Sweitzer said, ``Christmas will
come to town same as always.''
</TEXT>
