<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     11-30 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Delays Judgment of Next US President; Extends Nicaraguan
Truce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega, announcing
a one-month truce extension with Contra guerrillas, said he will
take a wait-and-see attitude toward the next president of the United
States.
   ``While the U.S. government doesn't show a changed attitude
toward Nicaragua, we can't change our own readiness, up to and
including the possibility of invasion by American troops. We are in
constant and permanent alert,'' Ortega said Tuesday.
   Other Nicraguan officials have said they expect a more
``pragmatic'' attitude toward Nicaragua from George Bush's
administration. Ortega said he hopes Bush will accept ``as a reality
that we survived all the efforts of a superpower to destroy the
Nicaraguan revolution.''
   Ortega, who is in Mexico City for the inauguration Thursday of
President-elect Carlos Salinas de Gortari, said he had no plans to
meet Secretary of State George Shultz, who will represent the United
States.
   President Reagan has steadfastly supported the Contras since he
took office in 1981, but Congress has refused to provide money for
weapons since March.
   Both the leftist Sandinista government and the Contras have
accused the other of violating the ban on offensive military action,
but Nicaragua has unilaterally extended the March 21 cease-fire on a
month-to-month basis.
   The U.S.-backed rebels, called Contras, say the truce is
indefinite and need not be formally extended every month.
   Ortega, at a news conference at the Nicaraguan ambassador's
house, said the guerrillas have violated the truce and characterized
recent Sandinista army operations as defensive in nature.
   The Nicaraguan president said the inauguration gives Central
American presidents a chance to discuss problems on an informal
basis, and said they should arrange a future meeting ``without
preconditions.''
   Presidents Jose Napoleon Duarte of El Salvador, Jose Azcona Hoyo
of Honduras and Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala also are to attend the
inauguration, but not Oscar Arias of Costa Rica.
   Arias won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for a Central American peace
plan that was agreed upon Aug. 7, 1987, but has stalled.
   The Sandinistas and the Contras signed a cease-fire agreement
March 23 under which the rebels were to stop fighting in exchange
for democratic reforms in Nicaragua. Both sides suspended offensive
military operations and a formal truce took effect April 1.
   Talks on details of the truce agreement broke off and no
negotiations have been held since September. Most Contra fighters
have left Nicaragua for camps in Honduras.
</TEXT>
