<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Credentials     11-30 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Credentials,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Once Overlooked Visa Denials, Now Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-UN-PLO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States often has denied visas to
suspected subversives seeking U.N. credentials, but the United
Nations started protesting strenuously only when President Reagan
began barring Soviet and PLO speakers.
   Under the 1947 Headquarters Agreement between the United States
and the United Nations, Washington must grant visas to diplomats on
U.N. business and let them operate missions in New York.
   The State Department has denied visas to suspected spies and
propagandists seeking U.N. credentials as diplomats and journalists.
   Reagan hardened the U.S. stance in the 1980s, not only refusing
them credentials to work in the U.N. but preventing them from
visiting U.N. headquarters to speak.
   The United States blocked Soviet Foreign Minister Andrei Gromyko
from addressing the United Nations in 1983 after the Soviet Union
downed Korean Airlines Flight 007, in which 269 people died.
   New York and New Jersey refused to allow Gromyko's plane to land
at their commercial airports.
   Soviet diplomats and the United Nations defended Gromyko's right
to speak, but Gromyko canceled his visit.
   On Saturday, the State Department denied a visa to Yasser Arafat,
chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization, saying he
condoned terrorist attacks.
   U.N. legal counsel Carl-August Fleischhauer said Monday that
decision violates the Headquarters Agreement.
   Fleischhauer said that in the past, the United Nations did not
take a position on rejected visa requests ``where the requesting
state itself, for reasons of its own, did not pursue the matter.''
   During the Cold War years, the U.S. regularly rejected visa
applications of suspected spies from the Soviet bloc, and the
requests were withdrawn.
   An Iranian who had been convicted of an attempt to assassinate
the Shah of Iran was denied an entry visa in 1954.
   In 1981, the State Department refused a visa for an Iranian
deputy foreign minister who it said was involved in the 1979
takeover of the U.S. Embassy in Tehran. The request was withdrawn.
   Earlier this year, most U.N. nations accused the United States of
violating the Headquarters Agreement by attempting to evict the
PLO's U.N. mission in Manhattan.
   In June, a judge ruled against the Justice Department's effort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
