<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     11-30 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Sweeps Sweep</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the 1988 November sweep results enter the
record books, there will be a big asterisk next to them because of
the writers' strike that delayed the TV season.
   But the month will most likely be remembered for the last of the
big-event network miniseries.
   According to the A.C. Nielsen Co., with a couple of days left,
NBC had won the November sweeps by about 2 rating points, despite
ABC's ``War and Remembrance,'' an 18-hour megaseries that ended up a
rating of 18.6 and a share of 29.
   Each rating point equals 904,000 households with television. The
share is a percentage of sets in use.
   Even the competing networks expected the ``Winds of War'' sequel
to do somewhere in the mid-30 shares. ABC reportedly guaranteed
advertisers a 20.2 rating and will have to give them free commercial
time to make up the difference. ABC executives had predicted they'd
lose $20 million on the miniseries even if it met the guarantees.
   The poor performance of the first 18 hours of ``War and
Remembrance'' casts doubt on whether the remaining 12-14 hours will
run next May as tentatively planned. It also once again casts doubt
upon the value to networks of such big-budget, time-consuming
programs.
   ABC, meanwhile, will offer the first 18 hours on videocassette
next week.
   As of the end of prime time Sunday, NBC had 2-point lead on ABC
for the sweeps win. November is one of four months a year when
network affiliates' local ratings are measured for purposes of
negotiating advertising rates. The networks usually load up their
schedules with special programming to help affiliates. This
November, however, the first sweeps period of the new season was
dampened by delays caused by the writers' strike. ABC and CBS still
have regular series that have yet to premiere this season, and ABC
rushed ``War and Remembrance'' onto the air to fill gaps.
   NBC won the week that ended Sunday with an average, prime-time
rating of 15.0. ABC had 13.0 and CBS 12.0.
   The week included Thanksgiving on Thursday, NBC's biggest night
for ratings. As a result, ``The Cosby Show'' barely made the top 10.
But two NBC movies, ``In the Line of Duty: The FBI Murders'' and
``Take My Daughters, Please,'' made the top 10.
   An atypical week in news _ due to football pre-emptions _ gave
NBC its first victory in the news race since Sept. 14, 1987. ``NBC
Nightly News'' had a rating of 10.5 and a 20 share. The ``CBS
Evening News'' had a 10.2 and 20, and ``ABC World News Tonight'' had
a 10.0 and 20.
   The top-rated prime-time shows last week were: ``Golden Girls,''
NBC; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS; ``In the Line of Duty: The FBI Murders,''
NBC; ``Empty Nest,'' NBC; ``Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS tied with
``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``Take My Daughters, Please,'' NBC; ``Who's the
Boss?'' ABC; ``ALF,'' NBC; ``Amen'' tied ``The Cosby Show,'' both
NBC.
   The next-to-the-last installment of ``War and Remembrance''
ranked 12th. The final installment was ranked 16th.
   The only new series last week was CBS' critically praised
``Almost Grown,'' which had a two-hour movie preview on Sunday and
came in 30th. It moved to its regular time period on Monday.
   Fox's ``Married With Children'' had its highest rating and share
ever, a 10.5 and 15, better than 14 network shows.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
