<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChelseaSchools 1stLd-Writethru a0766 11-30 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chelsea Schools, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0766,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Won't Block Proposed BU Takeover of Troubled School District</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 3-4 with four grafs to UPDATE with School Committee
voting to tentatively approve contract. Picks up 5th graf pvs,
``Rather than.' Recasts 11th graf pvs, `School Committee' to
conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Tuesday turned aside a challenge to Boston
University's proposal to take over Chelsea's troubled public
schools, ruling against teachers concerned that local officials were
abdicating their responsibilities.
   Suffolk Superior Court Judge Walter Steele without comment denied
the Massachusetts Federation of Teachers' request for an injunction
blocking any agreement between the university and the school
district, which has 3,300 students.
   Later Tuesday, the Chelsea School Committee voted 5-2 to
tentatively agree to accept a contract with the university.
   ``They (university officials) have to be given a chance,'' said
Morris Seigal, a committee member who voted in favor of the
contract. ``We do not have any other alternative.''
   The contract could be made final in two weeks, university
officials said.
   Union lawyer Bruce Miller said he was disappointed by the judge's
ruling and predicted it would not be the last legal battle.
   ``Rather than dealing with the question of education, we're going
to be dealing with the question of litigation,'' he said.
   In what would be a groundbreaking arrangement, the private
university is proposing to run the public school district for 10
years. Chelsea, a town of 26,000 just north of Boston, has the
lowest per-capita income and the highest school dropout rate in the
state.
   University educators are proposing to revamp the curriculum,
supervise the building of new schools and create special programs
such as counseling for pregnant teen-agers.
   Chelsea School Committee Chairman Bruce Robinson said Chelsea's
deteriorating finances make the proposal a necessity. ``It's an
ambitious plan,'' he said. ``We're going to have to give BU some
slack.''
   The union had argued that the proposal should be stopped, saying
state law forbids putting a tax-funded institution into private
hands. Miller said allowing school officials to sign a contract with
the university while the constitutional issue is debated would give
BU a strong foothold in the school system.
   But Walter Greenspan, representing school officials, said it was
not possible for a judge to rule on the legality of the proposed
agreement until it had been signed.
   After the judge's ruling but before the School Committee meeting,
member Liz McBride argued against an immediate vote on the proposed
agreement. She said negotiations with the university are not
finished and describing BU's offer of help as ``fine if they want to
come in as a partnership but not as a dictatorship.''
   Committee member Lydia Walata said she didn't believe a consensus
existed on the issue since some members were unhappy at the way BU
has made its proposals.
   ``It's sort of like a bull in a china shop,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0204EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ManImpaled     11-30 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Man Impaled,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impaling May Have Saved Worker's Life</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Jakie cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 6-foot steel rod that impaled a
construction worker after a three-story fall may prevented him from
plunging six more floors to a certain death, doctors said.
   The bar, which measured 1.8 inches, pierced Jakie Dale Klaber's
belly and groin Monday, but it probably kept him from plummeting to
the ground outside a parking garage, said Drs. Tom Harris and Brian
Zachariah.
   ``The rod basically arrested his fall,'' said Harris, a
third-year resident in emergency medicine, who treated Klaber at the
scene.
   Zachariah, another third-year resident, said that without the
rod, the 50- year-old crane operator would definitely have died in
the accident at the Whittenberg Engineering and Construction Co.
site.
   Klaber was reported in serious condition after the rod was
removed during an operation at Humana Hospital-University of
Louisville, officials said.
   Klaber was hoisting a half-ton wooden concrete-form panel from
inside a control cab on top of the nine-story garage when a gust
apparently blew the 8-by-12-foot panel into the wooden cab, knocking
it and Klaber over the building's edge, according to witnesses and a
Whittenberg vice president.
   Klaber, still inside the control cab, fell headfirst 36 feet to
the sixth-floor parking deck, which juts out farther than the top
three floors. He fell almost vertically onto the steel rod, located
within 2 feet of the garage's edge.
   Firefighters rescuing Klaber cut through the bar with a torch
and, with the rod still imbedded in his body, lowered Klaber to the
ground in a basket.
</TEXT>
