<2ND_LINE>AM-El Rukn Raid, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0811,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Street Gang Headquarters Raided, Founder's Son Held</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after the 2nd graf to UPDATE with police
saying no murder charge against Anthony Fort; picking up 3rd graf
pvs `The headquarters'; DELETES penultimate graf, `Anthony Fort' as
outdated.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used a battering ram to break through the
fortresslike doors of a Chicago gang's headquarters, seized four
guns and 69 grams of cocaine and arrested a man wanted on a murder
warrant.
   The police raid Monday was sparked by a manhunt for Anthony Fort,
22, the eldest son of imprisoned El Rukn founder and leader Jeff
Fort.
   Anthony Fort, wanted on a murder warrant, was taken into custody
later that day, but police Tuesday found his alibi was legitimate
and he was not charged with the Thanksgiving death of a woman, Lt.
Philip Cline said.
   Cline said Fort, however, also was carrying a gun illegally at
the time of his arrest and was named in several bond forfeiture
warrants, so other charges are pending.
   The headquarters, known as the El Rukn Grand Major Mosque, was
raided by police and Chicago Fire Department personnel who tore
apart walls and flooring in a search for weapons, ammunition and
drugs.
   Investigators found the guns, drugs and three or four gallons of
a codeine-based medication, commonly known on the street as
``syrup,'' police Captain Frank Radke said Tuesday.
   ``We confiscated all their records also,'' Radke said.
   Reputed El Rukn members Arthur Proctor, 47, Charles Green, 46,
and Duane Price, 30, were arrested and charged with weapons
violations and illegal possession of narcotics, police said.
   Police were followed by officials from the gas and electric
companies, who shut off the utilities for nonpayment of bills,
police said. The water was also shut off to the building, which once
was a South Side movie palace.
   Anthony Fort is wanted in the slaying of Katie Vines, 27, who was
shot in the head early Thanksgiving Day, police said.
   Two reputed El Rukn members, Christopher Brooks, 22, and Darryl
Howard, 26, were arrested Thursday in the woman's slaying and
charged with armed robbery and murder.
   The El Rukns, formerly known as the Blackstone Rangers and the
Black P Stone Nation, maintain they are a Moslem religious group and
that the raided building is a mosque.
</TEXT>
