<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mozambique     11-30 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mozambique,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Delivers Military Items to Protect Power Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW TORCHIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRA, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa is sending tons of
nonlethal aid to Mozambique to protect and help repair a
hydroelectric project damaged by rebels who have received covert
military support from Pretoria.
   The supply ship Drakensberg unloaded 139 tons of equipment
Monday, including tents, radios, underwear and 21 trucks. Two more
voyages are to bring the total deliveries by early 1989 to $4
million.
   South African officials said it was the first visit by one of
their navy vessels to Mozambique in its 13 years of independence.
They said the aid represented one of the largest foreign grants ever
made by South Africa.
   The equipment is for a Mozambican military force to be formed to
protect the 560 miles of power lines from the Cahora Bassa dam on
the Zambezi River in western Mozambique to the South Africa border.
Work on nearly 600 electrical pylons damaged by Mozambican rebels is
to begin in four months and take 18 months to complete.
   Mozambican Energy Minister Antonio Branco declared at a dockside
ceremony that restoration of Cahora Bassa could contribute to ``a
climate of stability and development'' in southern Africa.
   He refused to discuss Mozambican allegations that some South
African aid still reaches Mozambique guerrillas. Mozambican
officials believe that mutual undertakings like the Cahora Bassa
agreement will pressure sections of the South African military
suspected of supplying arms to the rebels.
   Relations between the neighboring countries worsened in the early
1980s, when South African soldiers raided Mozambican targets housing
members of the African National Congress, the main guerrilla group
fighting the Pretoria government.
   At the same time, Mozambican National Resistance guerrillas,
fighting their Marxist government, covertly received South African
miltary supplies.
   The 1984 Nkomati Accord, pledging South Africa to end support for
the rebels if Mozambique expelled ANC guerrillas, faltered amid
accusations that South Africa broke the pact.
   South Africa's desire to mend fences and Mozambique's need for
economic help led the two countries to try again through new
agreements on trade, employment and technical assistance.
   Cahora Bassa, one of the world's largest hydroelectric projects,
has been severely affected by guerrilla activity since it opened 13
years ago. The dam was built by Portugal, once Mozambique's colonial
ruler.
   If it reached full operation, the dam could supply power to a
large part of southern Africa.
   South Africa, which generates 60 percent of Africa's electricity,
presently has a power surplus. But Deputy Economic Affairs Minister
George Bartlett said Cahora Bassa electricty could enable South
Africa to defer construction of costly coal-fired power stations
until the 21st century.
   He said Mozambique could receive $5.5 million a year in fees for
the electricity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0236EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     11-30 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert and Judy Linkenberg started with
1,200 cans of shaving cream and finished with a house filled 2 feet
deep with minty-smelling cream and $10,000.
   The Kentucky couple lathered up radio station WLRS-FM for the
five-digit shave by fulfilling the station's contest challenge _
``What would you do for $10,000?''
   A committee chose the shaving-cream idea because it created an
atmosphere that was fun but safe, said Toney Brooks, president of
Radio One, which owns WLRS.
   If the Linkenbergs were unsuccessful, the station would have let
the runner-up try his stunt _ swimming across the Ohio River with a
bottle of wine and glasses cemented to a card table on his back,
Brooks said.
   Before the Linkenbergs began their stunt Monday, the carpet and
the furniture in their two-bedroom, one-story bungalow were covered
with plastic.
   ``This was Judy's idea,'' Linkenberg declared at one point.
   The Linkenbergs, with help from friends and relatives, emptied
the last can more than five hours later.
   The Linkenbergs, though thousands of dollars richer, will have to
subtract taxes, cleanup costs and $880 for the 1,200 cans of Colgate
regular, menthol and aloe shaving cream.
   They hope to use the money to refinance their home's 30-year
mortgage or buy a car to replace their 1962 Chevy Nova.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pee-Wee Herman, Elvis Presley and
Mickey Mouse were among the many non-candidates who received
write-in votes for president in Broward County, an election official
says.
   But the top vote-getter in write-in ballots unsealed Monday was
the more serious figure of Democrat Jesse Jackson, who got 90 votes,
said county Supervisor of Elections Jane Carroll.
   Voters also tapped Richard Nixon, Gary Hart and Oliver North for
the White House, but less serious figures dominated.
   Cartoon characters Garfield, Bullwinkle the Moose, Goofy, Bill
the Cat, Roger Rabbit, musicians Frank Zappa and John Denver, actor
Robert Redford, talk show host Morton Downey Jr., journalist Hunter
S. Thompson and movie hero Indiana Jones also garnered votes.
   Ms. Carroll said the county does not officially count write-in
votes for president.
   However, she did say that four disgruntled voters opted for
``none of the above.''
</TEXT>
