<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SavageJob Bjt   11-30 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Savage Job, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman's Son Swore He Was a Chicagoan While on Washington
Payroll</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the son of a Chicago congressman was
living and running for political office there, he was on the payroll
of the District of Columbia's delegate to Congress _ an arrangement
in apparent conflict with both House rules and Illinois election
laws.
   According to records of the House of Representatives, Walter E.
Fauntroy, the district's non-voting delegate to the House, hired
Thomas John Savage, the son of Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., on Sept. 8,
1987, and kept him on the payroll through June 30, 1988, except for
a six-week unpaid leave in February and March.
   Records show that, on Dec. 13, 1987, while he was an employee of
Fauntroy, Savage filed a petition with the Illinois Board of
Elections to run in the March 15, 1988, primary for state
representative. In the petition, he swore ``that I reside at 10846
South Halsted St., Chicago'' and that he was ``legally qualified to
hold such office.''
   Illinois election laws say a candidate ``for two (2) years
preceding election, must be a resident of the district he is to
represent.''
   Savage also was paid $5,600 during this period for working on his
father's re-election campaign, federal records show.
   If Savage were working in Chicago at the time he was on
Fauntroy's payroll, he would stand in apparent contradiction of
House rules.
   A House Ethics Committee guide for congressmen stipulates that
House staff assistants can be paid ``only for services performed in
Washington, D.C., or in the state or district that the member
represents.''
   In an interview, Savage denied that he held a no-show
congressional job.
   ``I was in Washington full-time, except maybe for a couple of
weekends, from September (1987) on,'' he said. ``It was impossible
that I was there (in Chicago) weekdays.''
   But a former worker in Rep. Savage's Chicago office said Thomas
Savage was doing work for his father there while he supposedly was
in Washington.
   The Illinois residency law is strictly enforced. For example, Tim
Wright, a candidate for the state legislature, was removed from the
primary ballot last spring. He owned a house in the district he
wanted to represent but had not lived in it for two full years.
   House payroll records show that except for the six-week unpaid
leave in February and March 1988, Savage was paid as a legislative
assistant to Fauntroy until June 30, 1988, earning $21,398 for the
10-month period.
   Savage said he spent most of the fall of 1987 in Washington,
lived in Chicago while on the leave, returned to Washington after
the March 15 primary and stayed here until he left Fauntroy's
payroll.
   He claimed his job was to enlist support among House members for
a Fauntroy bill that would grant statehood status to the District of
Columbia. However, he could not name any members he had lobbied.
   Fauntroy did not return a reporter's repeated phone messages left
at his office last week and Monday and Tuesday. Rep. Savage also did
not return several phone calls.
   Thomas Savage maintained that a Chicago apartment he shares with
his wife, Drella, fulfilled the state election board's residency
requirement. He said that while working in Washington, he stayed at
his father's apartment and his wife remained in Chicago.
   Among those who place the younger Savage in Chicago during the
time he was on Fauntroy's payroll is Nelson Rice, who defeated him
in the primary.
   ``He was here every damn day _ he was available, accessible,''
said Rice. ``Unless he had free airplane flights back and forth,
there was no way he could have been in Washington.''
   Juanita Bratcher, a reporter for the Chicago Daily Defender who
covered Thomas Savage's campaign, said she frequently saw him around
Chicago during the period he was on Fauntroy's congressional payroll.
   In addition, a former worker in Rep. Savage's Chicago office said
Thomas Savage made almost-daily appearances during the time he was
supposedly working in Washington.
   ``I saw him there five or six days a week during the fall,'' said
the former worker, who spoke only on condition of anonymity. ``In
December, he was there every day.''
   Campaign spending records filed by Rep. Savage with the Federal
Elections Commission say his son was owed $9,200 by the campaign,
and had received $5,600 between Sept. 4, 1987, and when he left
Fauntroy's payroll last June. The younger Savage said the money was
for work done in prior elections.
   The FEC records list only amounts paid and owed campaign workers
and do not detail when the work was performed.
   The younger Savage is also not listed in the official 1988 House
telephone directory, which includes all congressional staff
assistants. The directory is issued each March and includes anyone
on the congressional payroll at the end of the preceding year.
   Savage was hired by Fauntroy just a month after his father hired
Lezli Baskerville, a Fauntroy aide. Ms. Baskerville was given a job
with a subcommittee Rep. Savage chairs, according to House records
and committee officials.
   But Baskerville was removed from the Public Works and
Transportation Committee job after it was learned she was not
showing up for work, committee officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
