<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmWorkers-Deadline     11-30 0141</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Workers-Deadline,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Midnight Marks Deadline For Alien Amnesty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1.2 million undocumented farm workers
are expected to have applied for amnesty to live legally in the
United States under a program that ends midnight tonight.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service had estimated that
more than 1 million people had applied for resident alien status
under the program by late November and as many as 200,000 more might
apply before tonight's deadline.
   Legalization offices will stay open until the deadline to allow
last-minute filing, the INS said in a statement.
   Aliens who can prove that they worked for at least 90 days in
agricultural field work between May 1, 1985, and May 1, 1986, are
eligible to apply, the INS said. People whose applications are
turned down cannot be deported on the basis of their applications.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0237EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     11-30 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Foresee Higher U.S. Farm Exports Although Volumes Decline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bolstered by higher world prices, U.S. farm
exports are expected to continue to grow in value in 1989, rising
about $1 billion to $36.5 billion, according to the latest
Agriculture Department projections.
   However, export volumes are forecast to shrink by 8 percent in
fiscal year 1989 in response to declines for some farm products hard
hit by last summer's drought.
   The projected increase in export values would mark the third
straight year of growth. American farm exports rose from $26.3
billion in fiscal year 1986 to $27.9 billion in 1987 to $35.5
billion in 1988.
   The volume of sales probably will fall to 136 million metric tons
in 1989, down from a six-year high of nearly 148 million metric tons
in the year ended Sept. 30, according to Richard W. Goldberg, acting
undersecretary of agriculture for international affairs and
commodity programs.
   Goldberg delivered what he described as a ``bright'' agricultural
trade forecast at Tuesday's opening session of USDA's Agricultural
Outlook Conference, an annual event in which government analysts
outline prospects for the coming year for farmers and agribusiness.
   ``Export volume is forecast smaller as the U.S. share of world
trade shrinks for drought-affected products,'' Goldberg said.
   Overall, the United States is expected to account for 48 percent
of world total grain trade in 1989, down from 50 percent.
   One of the hardest hit commodities is soybeans, with the U.S.
share of world soybean trade forecast to drop to 35 percent in 1989
from 49 percent.
   Rice, corn and horticultural products are among the few
commodities expected to see increases in 1989 export volumes, with
wheat and wheat flour falling about 2 percent to 40.2 million metric
tons.
   But with global grain stocks drawn down largely because of the
drought in North America, Goldberg said that world prices for wheat,
corn and soybeans should be their highest since 1985.
   Goldberg said a $2.6 billion increase in the value of U.S. grain
and feed exports will offset declines for cotton and oilseeds in
1989.
   ``For U.S. agriculture, the challenge in the coming year will be
to sustain the momentum in overseas sales which has been regained
over the past few years,'' said Goldberg. ``This will require more
competitive prices, aggressive market development, persistent trade
policy efforts and a market-oriented trade philosophy.''
   Imports of agricultural products into the United States are
expected to remain about the same as 1988's record $21 billion. That
means that the U.S. agricultural trade surplus should rise about $1
billion in 1989, reaching about $15.5 billion. In contrast, the
surplus stood at only $5.4 billion in 1985.
   Goldberg said projected production increases in 1989 probably
will not prevent further drains on global farm product stocks and he
pointed out that the European Community is offering ``a tremendous
incentive'' to its farmers to produce through its system of export
subsidies.
   ``The United States will have a problem competing with such
subsidized competition unless we have the supply to be competitive.
If U.S. prices aren't competitive, other nations _ especially the
subsidizing ones _ will expand their production to fill the gap,''
said Goldberg.
   He forecast that Japan and South Korea would continue to buy more
U.S. farm products in 1989 and that sales to Taiwan would remain
about the same as record amounts this year.
   Goldberg projected ``continued large imports'' of U.S. corn and
oilseeds by the Soviet Union in 1989 but said that wheat sales
probably would not match 1988's record 9 million tons. He said a
drop in crop production in China should ``strengthen the demand for
food grain exports'' and that higher wheat prices could push the
value of wheat sales to more than $800 million in 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers and agribusiness should expect to see
continued growth in the U.S. economy in the year ahead, with a
potential for falling inflation, according to a member of the board
of governors of the Federal Reserve System.
   Wayne Angell, an economist and partner in a Kansas farm before
joining the Federal Reserve in 1986, said Tuesday he was
``relatively optimistic about the prospects for the economy.''
   In remarks to the USDA's Agricultural Outlook Conference, Angell
said ``a reasonable goal over the medium term would be to reduce
inflation by about one-half to 1 percentage point a year and I
believe this can be done while unemployment remains in the 5 to 6
percent range.''
   Among the biggest questions about the economic future are the
chances for reducing the U.S. trade and budget deficits, but Angell
said he didn't think the imbalances would ``derail'' the current
six-year economic expansion.
</TEXT>
