<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NimitzFire     11-30 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nimitz Fire,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Killed, One Injured in Nimitz Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One Navy serviceman was killed and another was
seriously injured on the USS Nimitz in the north Arabian Sea early
Wednesday when a fire apparently was started by an accidental firing
of an aircraft gun, a Defense Department spokesman said.
   Six aircraft on the nuclear-powered carrier were damaged by the
blaze, said Army Maj. John Smith. The incident occurred at 2:48 a.m.
(7:48 p.m. Tuesday EST).
   The identities of the two men were not immediately released
pending notification of next of kin, Smith said.
   The fire apparently started when a gun on an A-7E aircraft
accidentally fired during routine maintenance, Smith said. The round
of ammunition struck an A-6 aircraft, which ignited, and the blaze
spread to other nearby planes, he said.
   Smith said it was not immediately known whether the death and
injury were caused by the gunshot or by the blaze, which was brought
under control within 20 minutes.
   The spokesman said he did not know how badly the planes were
damaged. An investigation into the incident has begun, he said.
   The 95,000-ton carrier, based at the Puget Sound Naval Shipyard
in Bremerton, Wash., is the flagship of a carrier battle group in
the Indian Ocean operating area. Smith said the carrier would
continue on its current mission.
   The 1,092-foot-long carrier normally carries a crew of more than
6,000 and more than 80 aircraft, according to the Navy.
   Named for Fleet Admiral Chester W. Nimitz, commander of the U.S.
Pacific fleet during World War II, the USS Nimitz was commissioned
in 1975.
   On Aug. 19, 1981, Nimitz jets downed two Libyan jet fighters
following an attack on Nimitz aircraft in the Gulf of Sidra.
   The Nimitz is to be based at Puget Sound until facilities can be
completed for a planned permanent homeport in Everett, Wash., north
of Seattle.
</TEXT>
