<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Senate     11-30 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Senate,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Senators Honor Departing President</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's Republican friends in the
Senate bid him farewell with a pledge to carry on his conservative
legacy and praise for a politician they described as ``larger than
life.''
   The president and his wife Nancy were honored Tuesday evening at
an elaborate dinner in the Great Hall of the Library of Congress,
attended by President-elect George Bush, his vice president-elect
Dan Quayle, and GOP senators and their spouses.
   ``Soon you will leave and we will remain behind,'' said Sen. Bob
Dole, R-Kan. ``We stay on to do the nation's work and also to
protect your legacy, and extend it to the future.''
   The Senate minority leader had effusive praise for the
president's eight years in office _ including the first four when
the GOP ran his chamber.
   ``We will always be ready to win one for the Gipper _ and we know
... there will be times when we will have to call on you to win one
more for us,'' Dole said. ``And when we do, you will ride down out
of the hills again, larger than life, ready to save the day one more
time.''
   Reagan, in his remarks, voiced regret that the Republican Party
was unable to regain control of the Senate in the past election.
   But he asked the GOP members on Tuesday to give Bush ``the same
friendship, support and solidarity that you gave me.''
   After the dinner, Reagan was presented with a gift from the
senators _ a large ``weed whacker'' for his Santa Barbara ranch.
   ``It's a high-tech, top secret device that can be used to clear
out weeds, brush, trees, rattlesnakes, desperadoes and Democrats,''
said Dole, who presented the device to Reagan.
   The president also lavished praise on Dole, Bush's one-time
political adversary, calling him a great leader who ``has never let
me down.''
</TEXT>
