<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CatRescue     11-30 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cat Rescue,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cat Rescue Ends Family's Five-Day Ordeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family's cat was put into the bag near the
top of a 100-foot-high tree to end a five-day ordeal during which a
would-be rescuer landed in jail on disorderly conduct charges.
   John Wilson, stepfather of the cat's owner, climbed the pine tree
Tuesday, captured the animal and put it in a duffle bag. The cat, a
2-year-old white Persian named Spooky, was home in good condition
Tuesday night, though a little thinner, Tuesday night.
   ``He wasn't walking too straight, but he dashed straight for the
kitchen to get something to eat,'' Wilson said.
   Wilson's 25-year-old stepson, James M. Otts, was arrested Monday
night after he climbed 90 feet up the tree in an unsuccessful rescue.
   Family members said police and fire officials had refused several
calls for help, so Otts decided to try to save his sister's cat
Monday, when temperatures dipped into the 30s.
   Otts, who suffers from asthma and ``a small fright of heights,''
said he climbed about 90 feet before he grew too cold and tired to
continue. And as he climbed higher, Spooky scaled higher.
   ``He went up a little further, and then I went up a little
further, and then I went up a little further to where I couldn't get
down,'' he said. ``I've never been that high before.''
   It took firefighters 45 minutes to get Otts down, and when he was
back on the ground, he cursed at police officers, Police Chief
Everett Little said.
   Otts said officers ``started telling me how much (the rescue
effort) was costing the city. And I said, `Well that's what I pay
taxes for.'''
   He was arrested and taken to police headquarters, where he
received a summons alleging disorderly conduct and was released on
$50 bond. He is scheduled to appear in court Dec. 15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
