<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0327EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Extradition     11-30 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Extradition,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules To Extradite American Wanted in California Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former U.S. Marine charged in a string
of sex murders in California was ordered extradited to the United
States, where he could face the death penalty if convicted.
   The lawyer for 27-year-old Charles Ng said he will appeal the
ruling, issued Tuesday after a six-week hearing.
   Justice Marguerite Trussler of Alberta Court of Queen's Bench
said Ng should be extradited on 19 of the 25 offenses he is charged
with in California.
   Ng is charged with murder, kidnapping and burglary in connection
with the deaths of 12 men, women and children.
   Eleven of the deaths involved sex slayings at a rural cabin in
Calaveras County, 120 miles east of San Francisco. The 12th involved
the death of a San Francisco disc jockey.
   In her decision, Ms. Tussler cited evidence from Ng's alleged
partner in the crimes, Leonrd Lake.
   Ng came to Canada after Lake was picked up for shoplifting in San
Francisco and committed suicide. Lake later was linked to the deaths
or disappearances of several people. That investigation led to the
charges against Ng.
   ``I am satisfied beyond a reasonable doubt based on all the
evidence ... that there was a general conspiracy that related to
weapons, money and sexual gratification,'' the judge said.
   Defense attorney Don MacLeod has said appeal arguments could take
the case all the way to the Supreme Court of Canada, which could
take up to five years.
   The defense is seeking to invoke a provision in the Canada-U.S.
extradition treaty that says extradition may be refused unless the
requesting state guarantees the fugitive will not be executed if
convicted. Canada does not have the death penalty.
   Ng, who was born in Hong Kong and educated in British private
schools, is serving a 4{-year sentence at a maximum-security federal
penitentiary in Prince Albert, Saskatchewan, for shooting a security
guard in the hand in December 1985 during a shoplifting attempt at a
department store in Calgary.
   Ms. Trussler told a hushed courtroom she was satisfied, on
evidence filed during a six-week extradition hearing, ``that the
offenses charged in the state of California are extraditable with
one exception.''
   The exception was a charge of accessory to murder.
   The judge dismissed five other charges of kidnapping and
conspiracy to kidnap because no evidence was shown of transportation
of the three people involved, as required under Canadian law.
   The judge said she would issue a warrant keeping Ng in prison in
Canada until he is turned over to U.S. authorities.
   In Sacramento, Calif., Gov. George Deukmejian urged Canadian
officials to act quickly on the court ruling.
   Deukmeijian said delays would make the prosecution of Ng in the
United States more difficult. ``There are few crimes in modern times
that are more heinous as the atrocities attributed to Charles Ng,''
Deukmejian said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
