<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0326EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AgOutlook-Glance     11-30 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ag Outlook-Glance,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Farm Scene</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of the outlook for U.S.
agriculture in in 1989, according to newly released Agriculture
Department reports.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EXPORTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   U.S. export values should rise by about $1 billion to $36.5
billion in fiscal year 1989, while volumes are forecast to decline
by 8 percent to 136 million metric tons. The U.S. share of world
grain trade is expected to slip to 48 percent from 50 percent this
year.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PRICES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   World prices for wheat, corn and soybeans are expected to be at
their highest point since 1985. Food prices are forecast to climb 3
percent to 5 percent, which compares with a 4 percent rise this year
that included the effects of the drought.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FARM INCOME</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Net farm income, which includes rising values of inventories of
commodities, will increase by about 20 percent to between $44
billion and $48 billion in 1989. Cash farm income is expected to
fall about 10 percent to $48 billion to $52 billion. Higher
production costs and lower direct government payments will draw down
cash gains from rising farm prices.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PRODUCTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   U.S. production of wheat, corn and soybeans is expected to
rebound in 1989 in response to higher prices from drought-reduced
harvests this year. For some crops, the government also has eased
its land-idling requirements for subsidy programs. In general,
global grain and soybean stocks are down about one-third this year,
with reserves good for about two months of use for grains and 1{
months for soybeans.
</TEXT>
