<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Sikhs     11-30 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Leader Critically Injured After Trying To Unite Political
Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sikh leader was shot and critically
injured after initiating moves to unite the main Sikh political
party, and militant Sikhs were believed responsible for the attack,
news reports said.
   Jagdev Singh Talwandi was shot Tuesday in the village of Talwandi
in northern Punjab state, the Press Trust of India reported.
   Two of his bodyguards were killed and at least one other person
was injured in the attack, according to the report.
   Talwandi is leader of one faction of the Akali Dal, the Sikhs'
splintered political party.
   On Monday, he met with other Sikh leaders to unite the party,
newspapers said. At least one faction agreed to unite, the
newspapers said.
   Sikh militants, fighting for an independent homeland since 1982
in Punjab, have been generally opposed to the moderate Akali Dal.
   The party has split into three major groups _ Talwandi's own
faction, the United Akali Dal and the Akali Dal of former Punjab
Chief Minister Surjit Singh Barnala.
   The United Akali Dal and Talwandi's group agreed to unite, but
there was no word on the talks with Barnala's representatives.
   Sikh form 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are a
majority in Punjab.
   The militants claim they are discriminated against by the
majority Hindus, who make up 80 percent of the population.
   In other violence in Punjab, militants killed at least six people
Monday night, news reports said.
   The deaths raise to 2,323, the number of civilians killed by the
militants in the state this year. At least half of the victims have
been Sikhs who were accused by the militants of being traitors.
</TEXT>
