<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan     11-30 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Soviet Official And Afghan Guerrilla Leaders To Meet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrilla leaders will meet
with the Soviet deputy foreign minister, Yuli Vorontsov, in Saudi
Arabia this weekend, an insurgent spokesman said.
   ``The meeting signifies that they recognize us as a legitimate
force in Afghanistan,'' Hamed Karzai, spokesman for the Liberation
Front of Afghanistan guerrilla group, said Tuesday.
   The leader of the front, Sibghatullah Mojaddedi, will attend the
meeting along with Burhanuddin Rabbani, leader of the
Jamiat-e-Islami group and chairman of the seven-party guerrilla
alliance based in Pakistan, Karzai said.
   Moscow's decision to send Vorontsov, who also became Soviet
ambassador to Afghanistan last month, ``shows they are willing to
reach a political understanding,'' Karzai said.
   Moslem guerrillas, backed by the United States, began fighting in
Afghanistan after a communist coup in April 1978. Soviet military
forces entered the country in December 1979.
   Under a U.N.-mediated agreement, the Soviets began withdrawing
their estimated 115,000 soldiers May 15. Half were confirmed to be
out by Aug. 15, and the agreement requires the rest to be gone by
Feb. 15, 1989.
   The insurgents were not parties to the negotiations or the
withdrawal agreement and have asked repeatedly for direct talks with
the Soviet Union.
   Karzai said the agenda of the meeting in Saudi Arabia is
flexible, but he and several other guerrilla representatives said
the form of a postwar government was not on it.
   Determining the form of government ``is the right of the people
of Afghanistan and it will not be compromised,'' Karzai said.
   He said the willingness to meet with the insurgents indicates a
decline in Kremlin support for the Afghan government of President
Najib.
   ``They realize they have no alternative; they have to abandon
Najib,'' he said.
   Guerrilla leaders have refused Najib's offers of a power-sharing
arrangement.
</TEXT>
