<DOCNO> AP881130-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0517EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ConstructionExplosion-Scene     11-30 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Construction Explosion-Scene,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resident Near Blast Site: `I Thought It Was Nuclear War'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Construction Explosion, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY NACHTIGAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norman Collins was speeding toward the
construction site when he heard the blast he had feared and felt his
car shake.
   Collins, the president of Mountain Plains Construction Inc., of
Kansas City, Kan., had been awakened minutes earlier by a security
guard at the highway construction site where his company was doing
work. A storage trailer was burning, and Collins, knowing it
contained the explosive ammonium nitrate, made sure the fire
department was called and raced to the scene.
   Halfway there, he felt the blast.
   ``I was afraid of what it was,'' he said.
   In the early-morning darkness Tuesday, six firefighters died when
30,000 pounds of the chemical, used as a dynamite additive in
construction, exploded at the site in south Kansas City.
   The firefighters were extinguishing an arson fire in a pickup
truck when they noticed the blaze in the trailer. Two pumper trucks
drove up an access road to the blaze, and the firefighters were
killed instantly when the trailer containing the chemicals exploded.
   A few miles away, when the flash of light brightened her bedroom,
Cindy Denning thought the worst.
   ``I woke up and my first reaction was it's nuclear war, or else a
gas explosion in my building. I thought the building probably was on
fire,'' she said.
   When Ms. Denning looked out the window, she saw what resembled
``something out of a war movie'' _ people in nightclothes, some
carrying children and possessions, shouting and scrambling to get
into cars in the cold.
   Police cars with loudspeakers drove through another apartment
complex a half-mile away from the construction site across a heavily
wooded ridge, warning residents to evacuate for fear of a second
explosion.
   The second blast was not as loud as the first. But it still
sounded ``like a volcano erupted,'' said apartment resident Tamara
Taylor. She and her husband, Kerry, grabbed their 9-year-old
daughter and fled.
   ``All the glass in the apartment broke. Everything exploded in
midair,'' Mrs. Taylor said. ``I heard the police say the word
`evacuate,' and that was all I needed to hear. It scared the living
daylights out of me.''
   The explosions, which created two huge craters at the
construction site, knocked out electricity for blocks in the
surrounding area. Many people in the metropolitan area thought they
had felt an earthquake or a natural gas explosion.
   Neighborhoods just to the north of the blast site looked as
though they had been ravaged by riots. Thousands of windows were
blown out of businesses, homes, schools, banks and hospitals up to
10 miles away. Property damage was expected to total in the hundreds
of thousands of dollars.
   At the 4-Acre Motel three-quarters of a mile from the blast site,
doors were blown off hinges, scores of windows were broken and the
explosion blew a lock out of a door.
   ``It's just like a bomb, really,'' said motel clerk Dee
Cornelius. ``Property you can fix up, but those poor firemen.''
   Flags flew at half-staff around the city and fire bells tolled at
9 p.m. to mark the worst loss of life in the history of the Kansas
City Fire Department.
   Firefighter John Seise, who was manning an emergency shelter at a
nearby apartment complex for people who had to evacuate their homes,
knew all six of the dead firefighters.
   ``I tell you what, I haven't come to grips with it,'' Seise said.
``I just can't get it off my mind. You never realize how vulnerable
you are in this business until something like this happens.''
</TEXT>
