<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Jews 1stLd-Writethru   11-30 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Jews, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0482,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Jewish Delegation Lobbies Against New Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf, `The delegation...' to restore time element.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of 25 major U.S. Jewish groups urged
Israeli leaders to oppose a proposal to grant Orthodox rabbis sole
power over conversions to Judaism.
   The delegation met with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres on Tuesday, the first day of a two-day visit
to Israel, to protest the so-called ``Who is a Jew'' legislation.
   Four religious parties emerged as power brokers in the Nov. 1
election. They won a promise from Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc
that a Likud-led government will pass the measure.
   Such legislation has been proposed in various forms, including as
an amendment to the Law of Return, which defines who may become an
Israeli.
   The law now defines Jews as those born to a Jewish mother or
converted to Judaism. The amendment would add the phrase ``converted
according to Orthodox regulations.''
   Most affiliated American Jews belong to the Reform and
Conservative streams of Judaism, and many consider such legislation
a symbolic repudiation. It would prevent Reform and Conservative
converts from emigrating to Israel under the Law of Return.
   Rabbi Daniel Syme of Stamford, Conn., vice president of the
Reform movement's Union of American Hebrew Congregations, said the
delegates told Shamir and Peres of the ``tremendous anger,
frustration and disillusionment'' felt by American Jews over the
proposed changes.
   Syme called Shamir's reaction a ``non-response, a lack of
recognition of the significance of the issue.'' He said Shamir made
no promises.
   Shamir later met with Orthodox rabbis from the United States who
backed the proposed legislation.
   Shamir has said he would keep his promise to the religious
parties even if Peres' left-of-center Labor Party joined a Likud-led
coalition and rendered the religious parties superfluous.
   Before the religious parties struck a deal with the Likud, they
engaged in negotiations with Labor, which offered wide-ranging
concessions on the ``Who is a Jew'' issue.
   In his meeting with the American delegation, Peres ``acknowledged
his error in seeking an accommodation with the religious parties,''
Syme said.
   ``He indicated he was prepared to remove the religious agenda
from the table of negotiations and in effect challenge the prime
minister to join him in that commitment,'' Syme said.
   Peres said later on Israel radio: ``I explained to them that we
shall vote against the change in the Law of Return.''
   The American delegates said they proposed to Shamir and Peres a
three- to five-year moratorium on religious legislation to give
Orthodox rabbis and diaspora Jews a chance to work out a compromise.
   The delegates represent most major American Jewish groups,
including Reform, Conservative, Orthodox and secular organizations.
More than 30 meetings with Israeli politicians and religious leaders
were scheduled during the two-day visit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0049 </DOCNO>
