<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0609EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BookAwards     11-30 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Book Awards,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winners of National Book Awards Are Named</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A journalist won the 1988 National Book Award for
non-fiction with a book about the Vietnam War, and a newspaper
columnist took the fiction prize for a novel about the murder of a
girl in Georgia.
   Neil Sheehan, 52, author of ``A Bright Shining Lie: John Paul
Vann and America in Vietnam,'' and Peter Dexter, 45, who wrote
``Paris Trout,'' were honored Tuesday night at an awards ceremony
attended by 500 people.
   The authors each received $10,000 and a Louise Nevelson sculpture.
   ``I feel like a man who was on a long voyage of discovery ...
who's finally come home,'' said Sheehan, his eyes damp with tears as
he accepted the award for his book, which took him 16 years to write.
   Sheehan was United Press International's Vietnam bureau chief in
1962 and worked for The New York Times from 1964 to 1972. He
obtained the Pentagon Papers in 1971 while working for the
newspaper. Sheehan is the author of ``The Arnheiter Affair.''
   ``A Bright Shining Lie'' tells the story of the Vietnam War
through the eyes of Lt. Col. John Paul Vann, a troubled but
dedicated career officer who spoke out against the brutality and
ineffectiveness of the early U.S. strategy in Southeast Asia.
   Sheehan, a resident of Washington, said he wrote the book hoping
that ``it would help my country ... come to grips with the war.
   ``The most moving reactions I get are from Vietnam veterans who
write or call and say, `You put me back there. That's what it was
like. For the first time I know what it was all about. I know why it
happened the way it happened,''' he said.
   ``That's very moving. That's what I wanted to achieve.''
   Dexter's novel is about the murder of a 14-year-old black girl by
a white man in a small Georgia town just after World War II.
   The book was inspired by a shooting that took place when he was a
child in Milledgeville, Ga. ``I just started putting that together
and remembering things and that sort of became the spine of the
novel,'' he said.
   Dexter, a columnist for The Sacramento (Calif.) Bee and a
frequent contributor to national magazines, said the novel's success
would not lead him to give up his column, which he writes three
times a week.
   ``I'm not someone to hole up in the woods and produce a novel
every two years. I like being on the street and hearing different
voices,'' said Dexter, who has written two other novels.
   The books honored Tuesday were published by Random House, whose
editorial director, Jason Epstein, also was honored. Epstein was the
first winner of the National Book Awards Medal for Distinguished
Contribution to American Letters.
   ``This is really a happenstance,'' Robert Loomis, executive
editor of the publishing house, said of the awards sweep.
   Other fiction nominees were:
   Don DeLillo for ``Libra''; J.F. Powers for ``Wheat That Springeth
Green''; Mary McGarry Morris for her first novel, ``Vanished''; and
Anne Tyler for ``Breathing Lessons.''
   The other non-fiction nominees were:
   Peter Gay for his biography, ``Freud: A Life For Our Time''; Eric
Foner for ``Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution,
1863-1877''; Brenda Maddox for ``Nora,'' a biography of James
Joyce's lifelong companion and muse; and Jack McLaughlin's
``Jefferson and Monticello.''
   The National Book Awards, established 38 years ago, are awarded
by a panel of judges chosen by the National Book Awards Inc., a
non-profit institution dedicated to creating a wider audience for
American literature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0612EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Tornadoes     11-30 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tornadoes,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>N.C. Residents Pick Up Pieces, Plan For Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His house was a crumbling shell and most of
his belongings were broken or gone, but tornado victim Robert D.
Keys managed some humor as he surveyed what had been his bedroom.
   ``Get a load of this,'' he said Tuesday, holding up a sopping
paperback book entitled ``How to Survive the '80s.''
   ``I guess it taught us something.''
   Survival was uppermost in the minds of Keys and hundreds of
others who began putting their lives back together after rampaging
tornadoes cut a destructive swath through heavily populated northern
Raleigh early Monday.
   Two Raleigh residents were among the four killed in the state;
157 were injured in the night of terror that state officials said
caused an estimated $100 million in damage.
   Survivors voiced gratitude for life and health as they salvaged
what property they could and looked to the future.
   ``You've got to joke a little bit, cry a little bit, grunt and
grumble ... but then move on,'' said Keys, associate professor of
crop science at North Carolina State University.
   Affected neighborhoods were beehives of activity on the sunny,
cool day Tuesday. Sightseers gawked, police watched abandoned houses
for looters, and crews replaced lost road signs. The buzz of chain
saws, pounding of hammers and roar of heavy machinery at times
drowned out conversations of residents who traded stories of their
brush with death as they worked.
   Keys said he, his wife and two daughters jumped out of bed and
dashed ``like frightened jackrabbits'' to the small, first-floor
hallway seconds before a twister tore into their split-foyer house.
No one was hurt; the roof and second-floor walls were blown away,
but the first floor was left standing despite heavy interior damage.
   When Keys ventured upstairs, he saw that a sturdy, 50-foot oak
had tumbled across his bed. ``If we'd still been there, it would
have been goodbye,'' he said.
   Nearly unrecognizable under limbs and debris in Keys' back yard
was wreckage of a 34-foot motor home that had been parked on the
street in front of his next-door neighbors' house. Lee DiMond and
her family were trying to attach a tow truck to a twisted car
blocking access to the motor home.
   ``We only moved in two weeks ago,'' said Ms. DiMond, 23, an
employee of GE Mortgage Insurance Co. Soon she and her sister,
Daisy, will move into an apartment with their three dogs _ a fourth
died in the tornado _ and a few salvaged belongings.
   ``It didn't get my closet, so I've got some clothes,'' she said.
``But just about all the furniture's gone. We're going to try to get
my washer and dryer started.''
   Several miles to the southwest, residents of the Cooper's Pond
apartment complex gingerly climbed over piles of rubble. Four
buildings were destroyed and four others may have to be razed and
rebuilt, manager Deidre Kauder said.
   Residents streamed into the manager's office seeking advice, some
unhappy that they weren't allowed to enter rickety buildings.
``Anything you've got in there, consider it lost,'' an assistant
manager told one disenchanted tenent.
   Jennifer Rogers' parents helped her search the pile. Her husband,
Ed, was hospitalized with back injuries after the couple, who were
in bed when the tornado hit, were tossed down a 60-foot embankment
as their apartment disintegrated.
   ``We're alive, thank God,'' the 24-year-old schoolteacher said.
Later came another miracle: a neighbor discovered her wedding ring
embedded in a tree stump.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
