<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Marcos-Health     11-30 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos-Health,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical Report Says Marcos Can Travel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court-appointed physician decided Ferdinand
Marcos is healthy enough to face criminal racketeering charges in
New York, but Marcos' attorney refused to say whether the exiled
Philippine president would seek a second opinion.
   ``We received word that Dr. (Francis) Weld decided the president
was healthy enough to travel to New York,'' said spokesman Gemmo
Trinidad. ``But we have received no official report on the matter
and I'm going to have to refer all other questions to our lawyers.
   ``I'm with the president, I see him every day, and it's clear he
is not well, not healthy enough to travel, no matter what the
doctors say,'' he added.
   Trinidad said he did not know when the 71-year-old Marcos was
expected to appear and would not disclose his reaction to the news.
   Defense lawyers contend Marcos is too frail to make the 10-hour
flight and a hearing is scheduled Monday before Judge John Keenan in
New York.
   Marcos' attorneys have said they would seek medical tests by
``neutral'' physicians if their client was judged fit to travel, but
San Francisco attorney John Bartko said Tuesday the defense team
would read the full report before making its next move.
   ``We'd advised him that there would undoubtedly be various
opinions about the state of his health,'' Bartko said. ``Until we
read the full report, we'll reserve judgment about what we should do
next.''
   Marcos has been using a wheelchair since he and his wife, Imelda,
were indicted Oct. 21 on criminal racketeering charges accusing them
of plundering the Philippines' treasury and stashing much of the
money in the United States.
   He has been treated in the past for eye ailments, chest pains,
severe headaches and calcium deposits near the knees. In recent
appearances, Marcos has also worn a neck brace.
   Mrs. Marcos pleaded innocent to the charges Oct. 31 in New York
and was released on $5 million bail provided by tobacco heiress
Doris Duke, a close friend who owns a home here.
   The same day as his wife's court appearance, Marcos was examined
for about three hours at Tripler Army Medical Center here. Weld, a
cardiologist at New York's Columbia Presbyterian Hospital, refused
then to comment on his findings.
   Marcos fled to Hawaii in February 1986 after a military-civilian
revolt ended his 20-year rule and catapulted Corazon Aquino to the
presidency.
   In an interview with the Associated Press early this month,
Marcos said he doubted whether he would live through a criminal
trial, raising the health issue that his attorneys have frequently
said would play a major role in the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
