<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SovietMusician 1stLd-Writethru a0494 11-30 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Musician, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0494,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Pianist Permitted To Live in U.S. with Family</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf `Viardo said...' and 10th graf `Viardo said...'
to CORRECT name of university to University of North Texas, sted
North Texas State University.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet pianist Vladimir Viardo says his
government has granted him permission to live and work in the United
States for two years with his family.
   ``I must say when people ask me where I live, I would say I live
in Moscow. My workplace is all the world,'' Viardo, 39, told a news
conference Tuesday at Steinway Hall.
   Viardo's wife, Natalia, was scheduled to leave for Moscow today
so she could bring their children, 11-year-old Philip and 4-year-old
Alexander, to America.
   Travel restrictions on Soviet citizens have eased under Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev's reforms. Previously, many of the
relatively few Soviets allowed to go abroad had to leave their
families behind to ensure their return.
   Viardo won the Van Cliburn International Piano Competition in
Fort Worth, Texas, in 1973, and gave concerts in the United States
in 1974 and 1975.
   But he was not permitted to return to this country until this
year, when he came to play a concert last summer. After a trip to
Buenos Aires, he returned to the United States in September to play
in several concerts and teach master classes. Earlier in the year,
he played in European music festivals.
   Viardo said Tuesday that he would teach at University of North
Texas in Denton, which has promised him all the time he wants to
travel and give concerts.
   Why Texas?
   ``I'm a Texas winner (the Cliburn competition) and a Texas
citizen,'' Viardo said. ``Friends were made first in this area. They
were very supportive and they are.''
   Viardo said he was invited to stay at University of North Texas
as an artist in residence after giving a master class at the school.
   He said he and his wife then sought advice from Cliburn and
others before writing a letter to the Soviet ambassador in
Washington seeking permission for the Texas stay.
</TEXT>
