<DOCNO> AP881130-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0637EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CatLaw     11-30 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cat Law,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leash Law Applies to Cats, City Council Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPERVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cats are leading a dog's life here as
City Council has ruled that leash laws pertaining to Rover also
apply to Fluff and Mittens.
   Under a law that effective Friday, all cats in Naperville must be
inoculated and wear identifying collars. In addition, if the cats go
outdoors and set foot on any street, alley or other public place,
they must be on leash.
   The same rules, adopted on a 5-1 vote late Monday, apply to dogs,
but the leash requirement was already part of the existing animal
control ordinance.
   Violators face fines of $35 to $200 and the threat of
confiscation of cats. Authorities will attempt to contact the owners
of any seized cats through registered letter, but after seven days
the animals could be put to death.
   ``It's absurd,'' said James Vandendorpe, who spoke out against
the proposal at the meeting. ``My family has had our cat for eight
years, and he's always worn a collar, but there's no way he's going
to become used to a leash at his age.''
   The new cat laws were supported by members of the Naperville
Humane Society, and by village Animal Control Officer Kim Johnson,
who said she needed it to combat various cat nuisances.
   ``It's pretty hard to get people to understand that dogs can't
run at large and poop in your garden, but cats can,'' said Police
Chief James Teal.
</TEXT>
