<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     11-30 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Cheer At Anti-U.S. Rally, Burn Flag</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 12,000 people cheered today when
demonstrators burned an American flag and shouted slogans to protest
U.S. military bases and an alleged government crackdown on militant
labor unions.
   Also today, the military reported eight people were killed in
three separate shootings on southern Mindanao island.
   The rally was sponsored by the militant May First Movement on the
125th birthday of Andres Bonifacio, a 19th-century leader of the
struggle against Spanish colonialists.
   A smaller rally was held in Cebu, the country's second-largest
metropolitan area about 350 miles southeast of Manila.
   In Manila, police said the protesters, many carrying red banners,
totaled about 12,000. They burned a U.S. flag in front of the main
post office.
   Before the march, speakers called for the release of jailed union
leaders and the crowd shouted slogans such as ``U.S. bases, a
plague!'' and waved banners calling for dismantling the six American
installations here.
   Leto Villar, vice chairman of the Movement, told the crowd the
government was mounting an anti-communist propaganda campaign, but
``we know that communism is not the cause of poverty.''
   Leftists have accused the police and military of cracking down on
legal left-wing organizations, including the May First Movement. Two
leaders of a Movement-affiliated transport workers union were
arrested last week and charged with inciting sedition after leading
a strike of passenger jeep operators.
   The military says the Movement is a communist front, but union
officials deny the charge.
   During one speech, about 10 youths wearing handkerchiefs over
their faces walked to the middle of the podium carrying a sign
supporting the Kabataan Makabayan, or Nationalist Youth, the youth
wing of the banned Communist Party of the Philippines.
   Earlier, about 200 hooded youths shouted ``Revolution!
Revolution!'' and threatened Manila's police chief during a rally
marking the 24th anniversary of the founding of the Nationalist
Youth.
   Protesters scattered after the brief rally, and police made no
arrests.
   The military said unidentified gunmen fired Tuesday on a
passenger jeep in Mindanao's Lanao del Norte province, killing five
women. The military said the slaying may have stemmed from a family
feud.
   Also Tuesday, a woman was killed in Lanao del Norte when two men
believed to be Moslem rebels fired on a truck carrying about 20
hitchhikers.
   In a third incident, suspected Communist rebels shot to death a
soldier and a civilian riding a motorcycle Tuesday in Surigao del
Sur province in eastern Mindanao, the military said.
</TEXT>
