<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Demjanjuk     11-30 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Demjanjuk,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demjanjuk's Appeal Delayed Until May After Attorney Commits Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today delayed for six months
the appeal of Nazi war criminal John Demjanjuk after his defense
attorney committed suicide, Israel radio reported.
   An employee of the court confirmed a delay in the hearing,
originally scheduled Monday, but would not give the new date.
   Demjanjuk, a retired U.S. autoworker, was sentenced in April to
death for committing crimes against humanity and against the Jewish
people.
   He was accused of being ``Ivan the Terrible,'' a guard who
operated gas chambers in the Treblinka death camp where 850,000 Jews
were killed during World War II.
   The 68-year-old Demjanjuk, who lived in the Cleveland suburb of
Seven Hills before being extradited to Israel in 1986, claims he is
the victim of mistaken identity.
   Demjanjuk's attorney, Dov Eitan, died after throwing himself from
the 15th floor of an office building in downtown Jerusalem on
Tuesday. Eitan, a 53-year-old former judge, had joined the defense
team in August.
   Police ruled his death a suicide but said Eitan left no note
explaining his motives.
   Eitan was to have presented 60 percent of Demjanjuk's appeal,
according to Demjanjuk's son-in-law, Ed Nishnic.
</TEXT>
