<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthKorea 1stLd-Writethru a0518 11-30 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0518,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Clash With Anti-Chun Protesters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with police breaking up
anti-Chun march. Pickup 2nd graf pvs, ``Government leaders...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police hurling tear gas broke up a
march today by hundreds of students and workers who tried to reach
the presidential palace to demand the arrest of former president
Chun Doo-hwan.
   Also today, political leaders considered a recommendation by a
presidential panel that drastic curbs be placed on the national and
military intelligence agencies to end their domestic spying and keep
them out of politics.
   Thousands of riot troopers in green combat fatigues and visored
helmets blocked the protesters with shields as they tried to march
towards the palace. ``Arrest Chun Doo-hwan! Punish (President) Roh
Tae-woo!'' protesters yelled.
   Police scuffled with protesters after they marched out of a city
center subway station where they first held an evening rally to
demand Roh be removed from office and Chun be put on trial for human
rights abuses.
   Unable to break through the police lines, 1,500 protesters then
marched through the main shopping district, yelling slogans and
scattering leaflets.
   A few firebombs were hurled at a government office but did not
cause any damage. Riot police moved in to disperse the marchers with
tear gas grenades.
   Dozens of protesters hurled firebombs and rocks at police in a
brief clash as other marchers fled.
   There were no reports of arrests or injuries.
   The protest was smaller than major protests Nov. 19 and 26 when
thousands of people demanding Chun's arrested clashed with police in
Seoul.
   About 200 students demanding Chun's arrest battled police with
firebombs in a separate protest Wednesday in Songnam on Seoul's
southern outskirts.
   Chun, a former general who took power with military backing, went
into internal exile last week after apologizing to the nation for
alleged corruption and human rights abuses under his rule.
   Roh appealed for mercy for Chun, but opposition and dissident
groups insist the former president answer questions about the
alleged corruption.
   Several of Chun's close associates and relatives have been
convicted of or charged with corruption and other offenses. The
former president has denied he was involved in any corruption.
   Government officials had no immediate response to recommendations
made Tuesday by the Public Administration Reform Commission, which
was set up by Roh to recommend government changes.
   The commission said the Agency for National Security Planning,
formerly known as the Korean Central Intelligence Agency, should
confine its domestic activities to fighting espionage and
subversion. It should not be used for political purposes and should
operate under the law, the agency said.
   ``The agency has been criticized harshly by the people because of
its political maneuvers and abuse of power which resulted in human
rights violations,'' said Shin Hyun-hwack, chairman of the
commission.
   The commission also recommended confining the military's Defense
Security Command to gathering and analyzing military intelligence.
   The national security agency, which would still conduct overseas
intelligence operations, is a large, shadowy organization that often
has played a major role in enforcing the rule of past authoritarian
governments.
   Both intelligence agencies have traditionally play major roles in
domestic politics.
   Roh in a speech to the nation Saturday pledged to revise the
tough national security laws often used by the agencies.
   Roh, a former general who won presidential elections in December,
has pledged to remove authoritarian controls.
   Other recommendations included limiting the number of domestic
offices of the national security agency; reducing its authority
within the government; and subjecting the agency to government
auditing.
   Government sources, meanwhile, indicated a new Cabinet and other
major changes would be announced by early next week. Up to 11
ministers could be removed because of their ties with Chun,
according to press reports.
</TEXT>
