<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SniperAttack     11-30 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sniper Attack,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Two Suspects in Sniper Attack on Rio Grande Boaters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARFA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested two Mexican teen-agers
and were seeking two others in a sniper attack that killed one
person and wounded two others rafting down the Rio Grande.
   Presidio County Sheriff Rick Thompson said the assailants
apparently began shooting at the victims on a whim.
   ``We have no motive for the shootings,'' he said. ``They saw them
coming down the river and decided to shoot at them.''
   Both suspects gave statements, but Thompson declined to discuss
their statements further.
   Police arrested Eduardo Pineda Rodriguez, 17, on Tuesday at his
parents home near Redford, Thompson said. Rodriguez is a Mexican
citizen but a legal resident of the United States.
   Rodriguez and a 16-year-old boy, whose name was withheld because
of his age, were charged in the Nov. 19 shooting death of Michael
Heffley, 40, of Eastland. They also were suspected of wounding
Heffley's wife, Jamie, 32, and rafting guide, Jim Burr, Thompson
said.
   The 16-year-old was arrested by Chihuahua state judicial police
in Ojinaga, Mexico, Thompson said. Police were seeking two other
teen-age suspects, both of whom were believed to be in Mexico.
   Under international law, a person standing in one country who
fatally shoots a person in another country can be tried in either
nation.
   The attackers opened fire on the trio as they floated on the Rio
Grande through the Colorado Canyon, about 22 miles east of Redford.
   Mrs. Heffley and Burr said their assailants stalked them from a
300-foot-high canyon rim on the Mexican side of the river, which is
about 75 feet wide, as they abandoned their bullet-riddled raft and
scrambled up the river bank.
   Shortly after the attack, Mrs. Heffley recalled that her husband
``threw me out of the line of fire so he took the bullet.''
   Mrs. Heffley was shot in the left side and left shoulder. Burr,
36, suffered a shotgun wound to the right thigh. Heffley was killed
after he was shot in the back with a .30-30 rifle, police said.
   ``I really consider him to be a hero,'' Burr said. ``He was
shielding her in a very exposed area. He gave up his life for her.''
   Mrs. Heffley said she was pleased to hear of the arrests.
   ``I'm glad that they are being caught and I think this incident
should be made a public example,'' she said. ``I think they should
be executed, because if they are not, relations will never get
better across the border. Nobody should have to go through this kind
of torture.''
</TEXT>
