<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Military     11-30 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Military,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Doctor Released To Appeal Sentence For Refusing Army Duty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A physician sentenced to 21 months
in jail for refusing to serve in the army was released on bail today
so he can appeal his sentence.
   Ivan Toms, who ran a health clinic for blacks, was imprisoned in
March for refusing to report for military service.
   Magistrate A.P. Kotze released Toms on $420 bail today so he can
file for a review of his sentence at the Appeal Court in
Bloemfontein. No date has been set for the hearing.
   Toms' lawyers argued that he should not have received the maximum
prison sentence of 1{ times the length of the required military
service.
   Toms completed the mandatory two years of military service in
1979 and reached the rank of lieutenant in the medical corps. But he
has refused to attend the periodic follow-up service also required
of all white males.
   Prior to his imprisonment, Toms ran a clinic in the black
squatter camp of Crossroads outside Cape Town. Local residents
called him the ``angel of Crossroads.''
   Toms described the military as ``the ultimate upholder of
apartheid.''
   The government will not say how many white men refuse to serve in
the military. The last time a figure was disclosed, in 1985, 7,589
men declined to serve. Military duty is required of all South
African white males, but service by non-whites is voluntary.
   Under South Africa's policy of apartheid, the 26 million blacks
have no voice in national affairs, which are controlled by the 5
million whites.
</TEXT>
