<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0507,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Furor Over Right-Wing Segregation Moves Intensifies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with second council removing
portait. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``In one...'' Inserts 2 grafs after
11th pvs, ``Exactly the...'' to ADD Botha comment. Pickup 12th graf,
``A presidential...'' TRIMS thereafter.
^By DAVID CRARY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide furor over
segregation intensified today after one right-wing town council
voted to consider a curfew for blacks and two removed portraits of
the president from their chambers.
   The Conservative Party, which depicts President P.W. Botha's
limited reforms as capitulation to the black majority, provoked the
controversy by implementing strict segregationist policies this week
in some of the dozens of municipalities it won in local elections
Oct. 26.
   Three towns in Transvaal Province _ Carletonville, Boksburg and
Brakpan _ voted in recent days to ban blacks from public facilities
that were integrated in recent years. Such facilities include public
parks, toilets and sports centers.
   The Carletonville council went a step further Tuesday night,
ordering a study of whether a curfew should be imposed barring
blacks from the mining town at night.
   Conservative Party officials said curfews would be reintroduced
in any towns where its councils felt the security of whites was
threatened.
   In Carletonville and Springs, a small industrial city 25 miles
east of Johannesburg, the Conservative-controlled councils voted
Tuesday to remove photographic portraits of Botha from their
chambers. They replaced them with the municipal coat of arms.
   In one ward in Boksburg, voters cast ballots today for a town
council vacancy in a by-election viewed as a referendum on the
segregation issue.
   A Conservative Party candidate was competing with an independent
backed by Botha's National Party, which has denounced the
restoration of ``petty apartheid'' even though it has made no moves
to repeal the legislation allowing segregation of local amenities.
   The Conservatives' resegregation campaign has drawn criticism
from business leaders and sports officials, as well from
anti-apartheid leaders. In Boksburg, blacks have begun a consumer
boycott of white-owned businesses and some have withdrawn accounts
from local banks.
   Liberal politicians, while joining in denunciations of the
Conservative Party decisions, have noted that many public facilities
are segregated in municipalities controlled by the National Party.
   ``Exactly the same bigotry and selfishness is tolerated and
condoned by Nat leadership,'' said Douglas Gibson, Transvaal leader
of the liberal Progressive Federal Party.
   Foreign Minister Pik Botha acknowledged some whites-only signs
remain on public facilities in Nationalist-controlled cities, but
said: ``We are in a process of removing them.''
   ``The Conservative Party knows very well it is endangering white
security,'' said Botha, who is not related to the president. ``Their
own supporters will in the near future have to pay the price for
their unnecessary emotional outburst of racism.''
   A presidential council Tuesday rejected a bill proposing to
enforce residential segregation laws and recommended it be redrafted
to ease penalties and decriminalize some offenses.
   The bill was referred after a deadlock in Parliament, where it
was passed by the National Party-dominated white chamber but
rejected by the Asian and mixed-race chambers.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's majority 26 million blacks have
no representatives in Parliament and no vote in national affairs.
</TEXT>
