<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FactoryFire 1stLd-Writethru a0477 11-30 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Factory Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0477,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Sends Firefighters To Hospitals, Evacuates Hundreds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with 66 firefighters being treated, new
details on firefighting effort; No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FLINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 60 firefighters were treated early
today after inhaling noxious fumes as they battled a factory blaze
that prompted evacuations of up to 500 people, officials said.
   Tuesday night's fire at Diverse Plastics Inc., which makes
auto-related plastic products, burned some of the 700, 50-gallon
stacked drums of isocyanate, said Flint Township Supervisor Rod
Shumaker.
   ``It's not so much flammable but it emits this noxious smoke,''
he said of the chemical. ``It's not fatal but it does affect
breathing.''
   At least 66 firefighters were being treated for fume inhalation
at several hospitals, said Don Rowley, fire chief in the Genesee
County community.
   ``They've inhaled enough of it that they need to be monitored.
They've gone to every hospital in the area,'' said Randy Strong,
Shumaker's assistant.
   Shumaker said officials feared more firefighters would need
medical help, as ``residual symptoms might take 72 hours to show
up.''
   One other firefighter was treated for a dislocated shoulder,
officials said.
   Between 400 and 500 residents were evacuated after the flames
were reported about 8 p.m., and most were sent to the township hall
or a church in nearby Swartz Creek, Shumaker said. They were allowed
to return to their homes at 3 a.m.
   More than 200 firefighters from 28 departments in Genesee,
Shiawassee and Saginaw counties responded to the blaze as chemical
drums exploded, Rowley said.
   The fire, which damaged half the plant, was doused by 11:15 p.m.,
but firefighters remained at the scene to mop up, he said.
   The cause of the fire and the amount of damage was not determined.
</TEXT>
