<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-List 2ndLd-Writethru a0480 11-30 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-List, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0480,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tower Selection Appointment Hits Snag</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 12th graf pvs, Sources, speaking, to CORRECT that
Skinner, not Bush, was state campaign director. Restores dropped
words, last graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search by President-elect George Bush and
his top aides for a person to fill the No. 2 slot at the Pentagon
appears to be hindering the selection of John Tower as Defense
secretary, sources close to the transition say.
   Tower, former chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, is
known to want to head the Pentagon, and Bush could name him as early
as today, according to the sources.
   But Bush has pulled a few surprises since his election Nov. 8 so
there's a chance he could find someone else for defense. Among those
mentioned are Paul O'Oneill, chairman of Alcoa, and Norman Augustine
of Martin Marietta.
   Bush may also make his decision on the CIA public this week.
There is some talk that William Webster, the current CIA director,
may be asked to stay on for a while.
   Here are some other departments and agencies:
   _ Several published reports indicate Rep. Willis Gradison, an
eight-term congressman from Ohio, is a leading candidate to become
secretary of Health and Human Services. Gradison, 59, says the
reports are a mystery to him.
   ``Nothing has happened, no one has phoned me,'' he said.
   _ At Energy, word is that Charles Imbrecht, chairman of the
California Energy Commission and a big booster of alternate fuels,
is a strong candidate. For the record, Energy Secretary John
Herrington says he's packing his bags to head back to California.
   _ Former Michigan Gov. William Milliken is still being spoken of
for the Environmental Protection Agency, or maybe the Interior.
Other EPA candidates still strong are Mike Deland, regional
administrator in Boston, and Francis Blake, former general counsel
to the regulatory relief task force and also formerly EPA's general
counsel.
   Rep. Claudine Schneider's name has come up for Interior, but she
says she's pretty sure she doesn't want the job. Still being
mentioned is Sen. Dan Evans of Washington for Interior.
   _ Samuel K. Skinner, a longtime Bush supporter in Illinois and
now the chairman of the Regional Transportation Authority in the
Chicago area, is a strong candidate for transportation secretary.
   Sources, speaking on condition they not be named, say members of
the Bush transition team have contacted Skinner, 50, a former U.S.
attorney and close associate of Illinois Gov. James Thompson.
Skinner was state campaign director during the presidential campaign.
   Others are also under consideration for the job. Among the names
that have surfaced are Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., and Craig Fuller,
co-director of the Bush transition office and his vice presidential
chief of staff.
   Martin, however, says she really wants to become chairman of the
House Republican Conference. House GOP members will vote on that job
Dec. 5.
</TEXT>
