<HEAD>Griffin O'Neal to Return To Face Charges Of Probation Violation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Griffin O'Neal, who received a
suspended sentence and 1{ years probation for reckless boating that
caused the death of a friend, has been accused of violating his
probation.
   O'Neal, the son of actor Ryan O'Neal, has failed to perform the
400 hours of community service that was a condition of his
probation, Deputy State's Attorney Gerald Anders said Tuesday.
   O'Neal, a California resident, could face 30 days in the Anne
Arundel County Detention Center.
   He was sentenced in the 1986 Memorial Day accident that killed
Gian-Carlo Coppola, the 23-year-old son of director Francis Ford
Coppola.
   O'Neal and Coppola were in a rented powerboat on the South River
when the boat piloted by O'Neal crossed a towline, killing Coppola.
   Joseph Touhey, O'Neal's Maryland attorney, said his client admits
violating his probation terms. Touhey declined to say whether O'Neal
would plead guilty.
   O'Neal will return in January to face the charge, Anders said. No
court date has been set.
