<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0914EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Environment     11-30 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Environment,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Warns Of Environmental Disaster In Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report by the Polish Academy of Sciences
has warned of ``a complete breakdown'' of the environment in 27
areas of Poland inhabited by more than 12 million people, officials
said today.
   The report, summarized in the leading newspapers, was called ``A
Judgment of Effectiveness and Directions of Action in the Field of
Shaping and Protecting the Environment.'' The party daily Trybuna
Ludu said, ``It should be called `Judgment of Uneffectiveness'.''
   According to the report, Poland ranks second in Europe in sulfur
dioxide emission, most Polish rivers lack drinkable water, most
beaches on the Baltic Sea have been closed, and the amount of
industrial wastes in the country has increased by nearly half in the
past five years.
   A spokeswoman at the academy, the country's foremost research
institution, said the report was prepared by a committee of the
academy earlier this year and was now being made public.
   ``There has been a complete breakdown of the state of natural
balance in 27 areas'' inhabited by one-third of Poland's 38 million
people, the newspaper Zycie Warszawy said in its summary of the
report.
   ``It shows in a degradation of the natural order, incapability
(by the environment) for self-cleansing and an increase of diseases
resulting from the state of the environment.''
   The report said that economic losses stemming from environmental
problems were also huge, amounting to 10 percent of the country's
annual national revenue.
   It said industrial dust in the air of the southern Silesia
region, the center of Poland's mining and metal industries, had a
carcinogenic influence on living tissue, causing cancer or genetic
deformations.
   The government newspaper Rzeczpospolita suggested that increased
enforcement of environmental laws and other legal remedies should be
used to improve the environment.
   In recent weeks, government officials have expressed increasing
concern about the environment, and the newly appointed government of
Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski has said that addressing
environmental problems will be one of his top priorities.
   In one of its first acts, the government permitted the closing of
a chromium-producing factory near Wroclaw, in Silesia, for
environmental reasons.
   There is also a budding independent environmental movement, with
at least two groups of activists _ Freedom and Peace and the Polish
Ecological Party _ devoted to pointing out environmental problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
