<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MultipleTransplant 1stLd-Writethru a0478 11-30 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Multiple Transplant, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0478,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toddler Gets Five New Organs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with girl awake, being weaned
today from respirator, recast, include hospital's liver transplant
success rate; picks up 14th graf, `Rolandrea, who...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A toddler's five-organ transplant was
``smoother and much easier'' than the only other time such surgery
was performed, and she should do as well as a liver recipient,
doctors say.
   Rolandrea Dodge, 3, of Fruitland, N.M., was awake today and was
being weaned from the respirator, said Children's Hospital of
Pittsburgh spokeswoman Sue Cardillo. ``She's a very bright little
girl. I'm sure if she could she'd be asking what's going on.''
   Rolandrea was in the hospital's intensive care unit in critical
condition, which is considered normal after multiple transplants.
   She received a liver, pancreas, stomach, small intestine and part
of a large intestine during a 16{-hour operation that ended Tuesday
afternoon. Her spleen also was removed in the experimental surgery.
   Rolandrea's heart was functioning normally after the operation
and her new liver was producing bile, said Dr. Satoru Todo, who
headed the surgical team at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh. She
also was moving her hands and legs to the delight of her parents,
Branden and Cyndi Dodge.
   ``The prognosis is very difficult to say, but I'm expecting it to
go well,'' Todo said Tuesday.
   ``At this point, you don't know where you are other than that you
got through the surgery very successfully,'' said Dr. William
Donaldson, the hospital's medical director.
   The operation went smoothly except for one episode when the
chilled organs, which came from an unidentified young victim, were
inserted into Rolandrea's 30-pound body, Todo said. Her body
temperature dropped dramatically and her heart stopped beating for
about a minute.
   Surgeons restarted her heart with cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
   The only other five-organ recipient, Tabatha Foster, 3{, of
Madisonville, Ky., underwent the operation at Children's Hospital
last November. She died six months later of a blood infection, but
survived longer than any of the three Americans who had had
abdominal transplants involving two or more organs.
   ``This time, it went smoother and much easier. This baby doesn't
have any previous surgery'' as Tabatha did, Todo said.
   Doctors plan to give Rolandrea less anti-rejection medication
than they gave Tabatha so her immune system is stronger and she is
less susceptible to infection, Todo said.
   There is no reason why she should not fare as well as liver
transplant patients, he said. ``We have to be very careful.''
   About 80 percent of the hospital's liver transplant children
survive the first year.
   Rolandrea, who is known as Rolly, arrived at Children's Hospital
in mid-October to be evaluated for a multiple organ transplant.
   Rolly was born with an incurable disease called intractable
secretory diarrhea, which prevented her intestines from absorbing
food and liquids. She had to be fed intravenously, although she was
allowed occasional nibbles of candy, potatoes and other solid food.
   Aside from brief outings, Rolly has spent her entire life in
hospitals. Doctors in New Mexico said she wouldn't survive long
unless she underwent a multiple organ transplant.
   The girl's liver began failing about three months ago as a result
of her high-protein intravenous feedings, and her skin became
jaundiced because of bile pigments in the blood.
   Doctors began administering an experimental drug on Nov. 9 in
hopes of allowing her intestines to absorb food and liquids, but it
was unsuccessful, said hospital spokeswoman Sue Cardillo.
   Doctors decided a week ago to proceed with a multiple organ
transplant as soon as a suitable donor was found.
   Dodge, 27, a coal miner, said shortly after arriving in
Pittsburgh that it was difficult deciding whether to allow Rolly to
undergo the operation. But, he said, ``It's the only hope that we've
got left.''
</TEXT>
