<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gandhi-Clemency     11-30 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gandhi-Clemency,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>India Rejects Mercy Petition; Clears Way For Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President R. Venkataraman has turned down
a plea for mercy by a Sikh condemned to die for the 1984
assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, a government official
said today.
   The president's rejection clears the way for Satwant Singh and
Kehar Singh to be hanged Friday morning, according to a Home
Ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Venkataraman denied Kehar Singh's mercy petition on Thursday, the
official said. The Cabinet had urged the president to deny the
request.
   Satwant Singh, 30, refused to appeal for clemency.
   United News of India said preparations for the execution were
under way at the maximum-security Tihar Central Jail.
   Mrs. Gandhi was gunned down in the garden of her residence on
Oct. 31, 1984, by two Sikh bodyguards _ Satwant Singh and Beant
Singh. Beant Singh was killed in a shootout with other security
guards.
   The two men are not related. All Sikh males, according to
doctrine of their faith, take the name Singh, which means ``lion.''
   Kehar Singh, Beant Singh's maternal uncle, was arrested a month
after the assassination and accused of helping plot Mrs. Gandhi's
murder.
   After an eight-month trial, Satwant Singh and Kehar Singh were
convicted and sentenced to death by hanging. An appellate court and
the Supreme Court rejected numerous appeals.
   Mrs. Gandhi was apparently murdered in revenge for an army raid
she ordered on Golden Temple, the Sikhs' holiest shrine. More than
1,200 people, most of them Sikhs, died.
   The shrine, in the northern state of Punjab, was being used as a
base by militant Sikhs fighting for an independent homeland. More
than 1,200 people died in the raid, most of them Siksh.
   Sikhs form only 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are
in a majority in Punjab.
   Radical Sikhs have been campaigning for a separate state since
1982, claiming discrimination by Hindus, who make up 80 percent of
the population.
   This year, more than 2,300 people have been killed.
</TEXT>
