<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Australia-Yugoslavia     11-30 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Australia-Yugoslavia,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australia Threatens To Shut Yugloslav Consulate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today threatened to close
the Yugoslav Consulate following a four-day diplomatic row over the
shooting of a Croatian teen-ager during a demonstration.
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke demanded ``full cooperation'' from
Yugoslav authorities after 16-year-old Joseph Tokic was wounded in
the throat Sunday when a security guard inside the consulate fired
on hundreds of demonstrators.
   ``It is appropriate we put directly to the Yugoslav authorities
what the implications of non-cooperation are,'' he said. Hawke said
there was no question of the guard being allowed to return to
Yugoslavia and if any charges were to be filed, they would be made
in Australia.
   Foreign Minister Gareth Evans threatened to close the consulate
following a vigorous diplomatic wrangle over police access to the
guard accused of shooting the protester. Police were allowed to
interview the guard Tuesday.
   Evans said closing the consulate was ``under serious
consideration'' and warned of adverse consequences between Australia
and Yugoslavia if the guard did not surrender to police to face
criminal charges.
   He called the incident ``intolerable'' and warned any plea for
diplomatic immunity would be rejected.
   Hawke earlier made a stern plea to new immigrants to leave their
racial problems behind. He said ``do not turn Australia into a
battleground.''
   Australia, with a population of 16.5 million, has a large
Yugoslav community.
   Yugoslavia lodged a strong protest over what it called a lack of
police protection during the incident and has not issued a formal
apology for the shooting, leading to criticism from Australian
newspapers and politicians.
   The statements by the prime minister and his foreign minister
follow a four-day standoff over access to the security guard,
identified as Matijas Zoran. Yugoslav consul-general Stanojlo Glisic
defended the shooting on grounds he was at risk when demonstrators
jumped the walls.
   ``I would like you to face that mob with four people outside and
rest inside,'' he said. ``One (demonstrator) took a rubber hose and
struck me on the face ... so the security guard realized it was
dangerous. I was almost half-blinded by the chaos.''
   Police upgraded their presence at the consulate following a bomb
scare they linked to Sunday's demonstration. A police official said
all cars in and out of the consulate were being searched in case
Yugoslav authorities tried to spirit Zoran, the security guard, out
of the country.
   Tokic remained in stable condition at St. Vincent's Hospital.
Doctors said they were contemplating a second operation to remove
the bullet from his throat. The boy's parents said they expected
their son to regain use if his voice in about one week and called
him a ``very, very good boy.''
</TEXT>
