<HEAD>Man Sets Himself Afire; He And Two Relatives Die In Blaze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man doused himself with gasoline in his
family's living room and struck a lighter, igniting a fire that
killed him, his mother and a stepbrother, authorities said.
   Another stepbrother suffered second-degree burns over 12 percent
of his body, and five other relatives were injured in the blaze
Tuesday night at the home in the Astoria section of Queens,
officials said.
   Anthony Dyke, 27, apparently was despondent ``over a broken
romance,'' said John Mulligan, a fire department spokesman.
   The blaze spread to the rest of the house when Dyke ran upstairs
``in a ball of fire, possibly to get into the shower, maybe to
extinguish the flames,'' Mulligan said.
   Firefighters found Dyke's body in the bathroom. His mother,
Marlena Newberry, 53, was found behind the front door, and his
stepbrother, Kyle, 19, was found in the first floor living room.
   All three apparently died of burns and smoke inhalation, said
another fire department spokesman, Al Brown.
   The fire was under control shortly after firefighters arrived but
the structure was heavily damaged.
   ``There's nothing left,'' said neighbor Barbara Perricone, who
described the building as a brick, one-family row house.
