<DOCNO> AP881130-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1007EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thailand-Floods     11-30 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Floods,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clearing Of Forests Blamed For Floods That Killed 370 In Thailand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prime minister indefinitely
suspended government concessions to lumber companies today after
uncontrolled logging was blamed was for many of the 367 deaths
caused by recent floods.
   In two districts of Nakhon Sri Thammarat province _ where 267 of
the 367 bodies were found _ mud, logs and trees cascaded down
denuded hills, slamming into houses and burying villages. The
disaster affecting 12 southern provinces occurred during a week of
heavy rains starting Nov. 19.
   Officials say 385 people remained missing and 2,057 were injured
in the worst natural disaster in Thailand in recent decades.
   ``We will reduce or revoke the concessions as much as the Thai
law permits and punish poachers and violators severely,'' government
spokesman Suvit Yodmani quoted Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan
as saying.
   He said lumber imports from Burma, Laos, Malaysia and Brunei
should supply all of Thailand's needs. ``From now on, the ministry
will not give concessions'' to lumber companies, said the
agriculture and cooperatives minister, Sanan Kachornprasat, after a
Cabinet meeting.
   Sanan said permits already given were immediately suspended. A
total of 301 concessions are affected, according to the Forestry
Department. Sanan said firms involved in illegal logging will have
their contracts terminated.
   The search for survivors extended into remote areas today and 21
more bodies were retrieved. With some roads and communications lines
repaired, soldiers and other rescuers reached previously cut off
areas, said Col. Bunchorn Chavarnsil, a military spokesman. Ethnic
Chinese clairvoyants tried to help find bodies buried in mud, said
Bunchorn.
   He said the 25 clairvoyants in long robes meditated to call out
to the dead in the single most devastated area, hilly Phipoon
district of Nakhon Sri Thammarat. Two ethnic Chinese-funded charity
groups which help retrieve bodies in disasters invited the
clairvoyants there, he said.
   ``We appreciate all the help we can get, in any form,'' he said.
``The sooner we account for everybody, the sooner we can rebuild
from this tragedy.''
   Bunchorn said the clairvoyants on Thursday will conduct funeral
services.
</TEXT>
