<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran     11-30 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Denies Holding Mass Executions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Iranian official has denied
allegations that Iranian authorities recently executed thousands of
political prisoners, Tehran radio reported today.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Deputy Foreign Minister
Mohammad Javad Larijani as saying that ``only those who have taken
arms against the Islamic revolution or tried to kill people have
been tried and executed.''
   Speaking at a news conference in the Iranian capital Tuesday,
Larijani said that allegations of executions of anti-government
elements in Iran were propaganda statements from world imperialist
powers, the radio said.
   Larijani's remarks followed an Islamic Republic News Agency
report Monday that six clerics and three other men were executed
earlier this month after a religious court found them guilty of
being ``implicated in various offenses.''
   Iran's main opposition group, the Mujahedeen Khalq, or Peoples'
Holy Warriors, claimed Tuesday that 5,000 political prisoners have
been executed in Iran since August.
   The Iraqi-based group said in a statement that the executions
were carried out on orders from Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini.
   The Mujahedeen claim, made in a statement telexed to The
Associated Press in Nicosia from the group's headquarters in
Baghdad, Iraq, could not be independently confirmed. But it followed
a U.N. report issued earlier this month condemning Iran for ``a wave
of executions'' of opposition leaders after accepting a cease-fire
in its war with Iraq.
   Dissident Iranian sources have claimed that the executions are
part of a continuing power struggle within the government. They
claim infighting has intensified since the Aug. 20 cease-fire
between Iran and Iraq.
</TEXT>
