<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Kuwait-Terrorists     11-30 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kuwait-Terrorists,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Of 17 Convicted Terrorists Finishing Prison Term Shortly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the 17 terrorists convicted in the 1983 car
bombings of the U.S. and French embassies are expected to be
released quietly when their prison terms end shortly, informed
sources said today.
   Officials at the Interior and Information ministries had no
comment.
   Members of the pro-Iranian Islamic Jihad organization of Beirut
have demanded the release of the 17 from Kuwaiti jails in return for
the freedom of American and other foreign hostages held in Lebanon.
   The embassy bombings left five dead and 86 injured.
   The two terrorists the sources referred to were 25-year-old Iraqi
national Abdul-Mohsen Rashash Abbas and 30-year-old Nasser Matar
Dahash, whose family lives in Kuwait without official citizenship.
   In March 1984, the two were sentenced to five-year prison terms
with hard labor by the state security court after being found guilty
of possessing arms and explosives without a license. The sentence
also called for their deportation when the prison term ends.
   Other officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, confirmed
that the two were to be released after fulfilling their jail term.
They said that Kuwait does not want to discuss this publicly.
   The sentences were the most lenient meted out for the bombings.
   Three of the others who faced the more serious charges of
masterminding and carrying out the attacks were condemned to death,
although the executions have not been carried out. The rest were
given sentences ranging from life to 10-15 years hard labor.
   According to legal sources, the two will be deported to a country
of their choice once released. Their prison terms would be
calculated from the time of their arrest in December 1983, the
sources said.
   All the defendants were believed to be members of the underground
Islamic ``Al-Daawa party,'' a pro-Iranian group that was operating
underground in Iraq, Kuwait, Lebanon and elsewhere in the Middle
East.
   Nine Americans are among the 14 hostages believed held in
Lebanon. Peter Winkler, 32, a Swiss Red Cross employee, was abducted
by three unidentified gunmen Nov. 17. No group has claimed
responsibility for the kidnapping.
   The longest held foreign hostage is Terry Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was abducted March
16, 1985.
   Kuwait has refused to bow to the demand to release the 17
terrorists, despite threats by Islamic Jihad and a series of other
terrorist acts that included a 1985 car bombing attack on the
motorcade of the Emir, Sheik Jaber Ahmed Sabah. The ruler escaped
with minor injuries.
   The hijackers of a Kuwaiti Airways plane in April also demanded
the release of the 17 terrorists, but Kuwait refused. The plane was
hijacked April 5. Two Kuwaiti passengers were killed in the 16-day
ordeal, which ended when the hijackers surrendered in Algeria and
were given safe conduct.
   Since August, when Iran and Iraq began a cease-fire in their
8-year-old war, ties between Iran and Kuwait have been improving.
Iran had accused Kuwait of aiding Iraq in the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
