<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ByrneMayoralBid     11-30 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Byrne Mayoral Bid,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Switch Possible for Former Mayor, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Jane Byrne, a lifelong Democrat,
might switch political parties to run for mayor, a newspaper
reported today.
   The Chicago Sun-Times, citing unnamed sources, said Byrne is
considering a run for mayor as a Republican. The sources said Byrne
has nominating petitions ready to go, and will announce her
candidacy shortly.
   In 1983, Byrne was denied renomination for mayor when she lost
the Democratic primary to Harold Washington, who later became the
city's first black mayor.
   ``I have no political comment,'' Byrne said Tuesday when asked if
she would become a Republican to run for mayor.
   The Sun-Times reported that Byrne, a former member of the
Democratic National Committee, discussed her possible mayoral
candidacy with Cook County Republican Chairman James E. Dvorak.
   ``I'd rather not comment on any of my discussions with potential
candidates at this time,'' Dvorak said.
   Republican officials said Byrne would likely win the party's
primary election against a lesser-known candidate.
   The filing period for the Feb. 28 primary is Dec. 12-19 for
regular party candidates. Nominating petitions for Republicans must
have 454 valid signatures. Democrats need 4,434 names.
   Six Democratic candidates have announced plans to run for mayor
to serve out the term of Washington, who died of a heart attack last
year. Cook County State's Attorney Richard Daley is expected to
announce his candidacy for the Democratic nomination Monday.
   Eugene Sawyer, who was selected by the City Council as acting
mayor, has not announced his candidacy.
</TEXT>
