<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0539 11-30 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0539,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settler Convicted in Slaying Of Arab; Curfews Confine 150,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 9th pvs pvs, ``The district...'' to ADD
maximum sentence for manslaughter is 20 years. Pickup 10th pvs,
``The incident ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court today found a U.S.-born immigrant guilty
of manslaughter in the shooting of a Palestinian shepherd near a
Jewish settlement in the occupied West Bank, Israeli radio said.
   It was the first time since the start of the Palestinian uprising
nearly a year ago that a Jewish settler was convicted of killing a
Palestinian. The defendant, Israel Zeev, claimed he fired in
self-defense.
   Leaders of the settlement movement, meanwhile, called on the army
to take harsher steps against Arab rioters, deporting those who
throw stones and barring anyone arrested for protesting from ever
holding a job in Israel.
   ``It seems to me we have a war going on here, but it is being
treated like a demonstration,'' said Haim Granit, a brigadier
general in the reserve army who lives in the West Bank settlement of
Elkana. ``The army must be given orders so they can handle this as
they should.''
   The 1.5 million Palestinians living in Israeli-occupied areas
have been rebelling against Israeli rule for almost a year. Since
the uprising began Dec. 8, 316 Palestinians and 11 Israelis have
been killed.
   Troops shot and wounded five Palestinians in stone-throwing
clashes in the occupied areas today, hospital officials said on
condition of anonymity.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   More than 150,000 Palestinians in the occupied Gaza Strip, most
living in refugee camps, were confined to their homes by military
curfews.
   The district court found Zeev guilty in the May 5 slaying of a
28-year-old Palestinian shepherd, Jude Abdallah Awad. Another
Palestinian was wounded in the eye when he came to Awad's aid. Zeev,
originally from Philadelphia, will be sentenced on Sunday, Israeli
radio said.
   The maximum sentence for manslaughter in Israel is 20 years.
   The incident began when a Jewish woman spotted several
Palestinian shepherds in a field between the West Bank village of
Turmus Aiya, 15 miles northeast of Jerusalem, and the nearby Jewish
settlement of Shillo.
   She called Zeev, who came and fired at the shepherds.
   In other developments, police released three Israelis suspected
of setting a fire that burned three Palestinians day laborers to
death as they slept in a shack near the Tel Aviv suburb of Or Yehuda
in August.
   The victims were all residents of the Gaza Strip.
   Police freed the suspects after holding them for 90 days. Israeli
radio said police did not have enough evidence to bring charges
against the men.
</TEXT>
