<HEAD>$350,000 Stolen From Bank Cash Machines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thieves used automated teller machines to
steal nearly $350,000 from about 300 customers at California's
second-largest bank, officials said.
   Authorities are investigating whether special cards given to
employees of Security Pacific National Bank were used to gain access
to accounts, override the daily limit on cash withdrawals and take
cash without being detected.
   Security Pacific spokeswoman Deborah K. Lewis said the bank has
referred the case to authorities. An FBI agent confirmed his agency
is investigating.
   The bank reimbursed depositors after discovering the thefts,
which occurred Nov. 11-13, Ms. Lewis said. She declined to say how
many branches were hit.
   Security Pacific, the state's second-largest bank after Bank of
America, has new security procedures to prevent similar thefts, Ms.
Lewis said.
