<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0846</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the courts.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 28
   San Antonio Express-News on worthwhile tasks for Dan Quayle:
   One of the biggest problems every vice president faces is simply
finding something worthwhile to do.
   Britain's Prince Charles faces a similar dilemma. The heir
apparent to the throne recently celebrated his 40th birthday. Since
his mother, Queen Elizabeth II, is only 62, currently in good
health, and not particularly inclined to abdicate, Charles may have
to wait a decade or two to become king.
   While he is waiting, the prince _ who is a year younger than Vice
President-elect Dan Quayle _ has found some meaningful and
worthwhile work to occupy his time.
   Charles regularly visits inner-city slums, schools and factories.
He organized Project Fullemploy to prepare young, urban blacks for
jobs, persuaded some London companies to offer jobs to people who
have dropped out of school, and plays an active role in helping the
poor gain title to their own homes through ``sweat equity.''
   If Bush means what he says, and if Quayle runs out of meaningful
work to do, Bush might suggest that his vice president look to
Charles' example. It should be an eye-opening experience for Quayle,
who is a son of wealth and privilege, and it might do some good for
the country.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 23
   The Mail Tribune, Medford, Ore., on the B-1B bomber:
   Former President Jimmy Carter ... deserves credit for being on
target when it came to the B-1B bomber program. ...
   (Recently) ...a B-1B bomber crashed and burned while trying to
land. ...
   The crash came two days after the Air Force said it had cleared
63 of the nation's 98 B-1B bombers to return to service. The entire
fleet had been grounded since Nov. 8 when a B-1B crashed and burned
at Dyess Air Force Base in Texas.
   The B-1B was ... intended to modernize the long-range bomber
fleet until the recently unveiled B-2 Stealth bomber could become
fully operational. ...
   Critics say the bomber cannot fulfill its assigned mission of
flying deep into Soviet territory with a payload of nuclear bombs.
They say it is too slow, it consumes too much fuel ... and it is too
heavy for pilots to handle safely.
   Today the nation is paying _ and paying _ for (President)
Reagan's decision to overrule Carter's veto of funds for the B-1B
dud.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 28
   Los Angeles Times on the thaw in Sino-Soviet relations:
   The world may be about to witness the sort of fundamental
strategic realignment that happens only once or twice in a
generation.
   Without fanfare, relations between the Soviet Union and China
have warmed to the point where the world's two great communist
powers are ready to undertake their first high-level exchanges in
decades.
   If Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen's trip this week to
Moscow turns out as well as expected, it will lay the groundwork for
a historic summit (in 1989) between Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and Deng Ziaoping, China's senior statesman, ... the first
since Nikita S. Khrushchev traveled to Beijing in 1959. ...
   As relations between Moscow and Washington have warmed, the
Chinese have felt left out of deliberations over intermediate
nuclear missiles and other matters important to them. ...
   U.S. strategists believe that reduced tensions between China and
the Soviet Union may eventually make the whole region more secure.
But the Sino-Soviet split has been such a fixture for so long that,
once it disappears, other readjustments may be in store.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 24
   The Capital Times, Madison, Wis., on delinquent farm loans:
   Imagine if your holiday mail included a 200-page packet from the
federal government with this grim choice _ fill out this material or
lose your farm. ...
   The Farmers Home Administration sent out the packets the week
after the election to farmers who were delinquent on their loans.
   It took the FmHA five months to put together all this material in
response to a 1987 law. Now it wants farmers to respond in 45 days _
45 days that coincide with the holiday season.
   While the cold and calculating may say that those who can't hack
it ought to get off the farm, that attitude ignores both the
vagaries of the farm economy and the wider threat to rural America
in the steady demise of small farms.
   It also ignores the human pain involved when the farmer not only
loses a job, but a home and land often passed on from generation to
generation.
   A group of 14 members of Congress ... is seeking to extend the
45-day response period so that beleaguered farmers at least have
more time to search out their options under the new federal rules.
   The extra time could help some farmers cope with the complexity
of the law and perhaps could give them a chance to survive
economically through 1989.
</TEXT>
