<TEXT>
   Nov. 25
   The Duluth (Minn.) News-Tribune on President Reagan's veto of the
ethics bill:
   Maybe President Reagan didn't like the nickname of the ethics
bill he killed (last) week with a pocket veto.
   It was informally called the ``Never Again Mike Deaver'' bill,
taking on the name of Reagan's former aide and close friend who was
convicted of illegal influence peddling (lobbying) after he left the
White House.
   Whatever his reason, Reagan refused to sign the bill that would
have imposed tougher curbs on lobbying by both former administration
officials and _ for the first time _ imposed the same restrictions
on former members of Congress.
   The Reagan administration has a dismal record when it comes to
conflicts of interest, and this would have been one final
opportunity for the president to say: ``Enough. It stops here.''
Instead, he said, ``Business as usual.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 28
   The Honolulu Star-Bulletin on the U.S. denial of a visa to Yassir
Arafat:
   Secretary of State (George) Shultz's decision to deny a visa to
the Palestine Liberation Organization's Yasser Arafat to visit
United Nations has raised the hackles of many Arab leaders.
   But it also sends a useful message concerning the United States'
resolve to combat terrorism.
   Shultz has done the right thing, in our opinion, by underscoring
his and the nation's policy of repelling terrorists and those who
abet their aims.
   Organizations which take part in or foster acts of terrorism are
simply going to have to do more for peace and cooperation before
they reach the U.N. bargaining table.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 29
   Topeka (Kan.) Capital-Journal on the U.S. denial of a visa to
Arafat:
   (Secretary of State George) Shultz made the wrong decision.
   The United Nations is an international organization; its forum
should be accessible to international leaders without interference
from the U.S. government.
   Imagine the uproar if Daniel Ortega denied U.S. representatives
access to an international forum on Western hemisphere issues in
Nicaragua because of (U.S.) sponsorship of the Contras.
   It is not a whole lot different, except that Ortega does not
subscribe in practice to the principles of free speech. The United
States does.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 28
   The West Palm Beach (Fla.) Post on U.S.-Canadian trade:
   Canada has voted for free trade with the United States. Now it's
up to leaders on both sides of the border to see that this concept
is not distorted for ends that are political rather than economic.
   The overriding issue in last week's national elections was the
treaty signed in January by Prime Minister Brian Mulroney and
President Reagan, under which all remaining tariffs on trade between
the two nations will be phased out over a 10-year period beginning
Jan. 1. ...
   Properly implemented, the treaty can open up new opportunities
for both nations, removing the economic barriers from what already
is the world's longest border free of military barriers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 25
   The Wenatchee (Wash.) World on the English-only movement:
   It is time to put the brakes on the English-only bandwagon. A new
idea branded ``English-plus'' has a lot more to recommend it.
   Concern about this issue arises because three more states ...
passed English-only amendments to their state constitutions earlier
this month during the big national election. They joined 13 other
states that had already passed English-only laws of their own. ...
   While much of the nation has perceived these laws as relatively
harmless in the past, ... there is a growing sense that there's more
to this legislation than just promoting English.
   Racist comments are surfacing which make it clear some backers of
English-only laws are more worried about keeping certain segments of
the population down than they are about lifting language skills up.
...
   In response to this negative approach taken by English-only
groups, opponents have coined the new slogan ``English-plus'' to
demonstrate their commitment to teaching English while preserving
minority languages.
   We should even go beyond that by encouraging more Americans to
learn other languages, especially Japanese, Chinese and Spanish, to
deal most effectively with the entire Pacific Rim over the next few
decades.
</TEXT>
