<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--SpaceParts     11-30 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Space Parts,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manufacturer Pleads Guilty To Falsifying Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parts manufacturer has pleaded guilty to
charges he falsified safety test documents for nuts and bolts
installed in a space laboratory, forcing the government to spend $1
million for replacements.
   Arthur O. Sammons, 76, entered the plea last week in U.S.
District Court to 43 counts of fraud and making false statements to
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   Sammons faces up to 215 years in prison and a $7.8 million fine
when he is sentenced Dec. 5.
   NASA has said the bolts could have posed a safety threat to
astronauts.
   Workers at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida have been taking
apart the space laboratory, called Astro I, since late summer.
   It is costing NASA about $1 million to replace all the bolts that
Sammons supplied.
   Sammons refused to comment.
   Federal investigators said Sammons operated his one-man company,
A.O. Sammons, out of a condominium garage.
</TEXT>
