<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--ChemicalSpill     11-30 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Chemical Spill,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ammonia Gas Forces Evacuations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ammonia gas spread through a four-story
industrial building today, injuring four workers and forcing the
evacuation of 200 others, a fire official said.
   Three of the injured workers were taken to St. James Hospital of
Newark where they were treated for ammonia inhalation and nausea.
They were released after treatment, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Chemicals used by Plating City Corp. caused the problem, said
Larry Krieger, fire department spokesman.
   ``Before closing yesterday, workers at the plating company added
ammonia to a plating solution and left it overnight,'' Krieger said.
``It's a routine operation, but because of the cold weather the
windows were closed and the fumes built up and seeped into the upper
floors.''
   Carbel Fashions and FCP Fashions occupy the floors above the
plating company and when employees arrived at work, several
complained of headaches.
   After four workers became ill, the fire department ordered about
200 people from the building, Krieger said.
</TEXT>
