<DOCNO> AP881130-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1208EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SkagwayLead     11-30 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Skagway Lead,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blood Tests Show Lead At Port Not An Immediate Health Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blood tests given residents of the
mining port of Skagway, where soil with among the nation's highest
lead contaminations was found, indicate there is no immediate health
threat, state officials say.
   But the state Department of Environmental Conservation said
Tuesday it will require cleanup of the contaminated soil to make
sure there are no problems in the future.
   Dick Stokes, the agency's regional supervisor, called the results
encouraging.
   But, he added, ``Regardless of the blood results so far, there
still is a lot of lead and zinc in the soil. We're very lucky that
no more has been ingested than it has, but it's still there and we
still think cleanup is going to be necessary.''
   For decades, trucks and trains carrying ore from lead and zinc
mines have rumbled into Skagway, a town of 700 people north of
Juneau in the Alaska Panhandle. Most recently, the huge mine at Faro
in Canada's Yukon Territory has been moving ore trucks through
Skagway every half-hour, 24 hours a day, 362 days a year.
   Lead contamination in soil at the ore-loading terminal on the
edge of town reached about 57,000 parts per million, making it one
of the worst known sites of lead contamination in the nation, state
environmental officials have said.
   In town, lead was tested at about 28,000 ppm at one site and
about 20,000 ppm at another. The federal government generally
requires cleanup of sites with more than 1,000 ppm of lead.
   Lead poisoning can cause high blood pressure and neurological
problems. Children and pregnant women are particularly susceptible
to health damage.
   The state offered voluntary blood and urine tests to the town's
residents. The report released Tuesday said that of the 161 blood
samples and 40 urine samples taken, only five showed lead levels
greater than normal.
   The report said those five were from people who worked at the
ore-loading terminal, and that they already undergo regular
monitoring for lead levels.
   It also said there was no need for additional tests or routine
monitoring of Skagway visitors or residents, other than those who
work at the terminal.
   Environmentalists said such one-time blood tests are not
definitive.
   ``I'm glad that most of the results aren't high enough that
immediate intervention is required, but I don't think it's
appropriate for the health department to say no further tests are
warranted,'' said Kristine Benson of the Alaska Center for the
Environment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
