<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AdolphHitlerClark     11-30 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Adolph Hitler Clark,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Pleads Guilty To Third-Degree Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man who blamed his life of
crime on his name _ Adolph Hitler Clark _ has pleaded guilty to a
charge of third-degree murder and also learned his middle name is
Hilbert.
   Clark, 18, pleaded guilty Tuesday in the slaying of a man who was
trying to buy cocaine. He faces up to 12 years in prison.
   Meanwhile, Chief Assistant Public Defender Bill White presented
Circuit Judge John D. Southwood with a copy of Clark's birth
certificate showing the young man's middle name is actually Hilbert
and not Hitler.
   Clark said in an interview last year that he used his middle name
as an excuse for his criminal activity.
   ``After I learned who Hitler really was, I decided people
expected me to live up to his name,'' he said.
   His father, Theodore Clark, said he named his son Adolph after
the boy's uncle and thought Hitler would be a good middle name.
   After seeing the document, Southwood ordered the criminal
information changed to reflect Clark's correct name.
   White said after the hearing that the combination of the
mispronunciation of Hilbert and the familiarity of the Nazi leader's
name apparently led to Clark being called Adolph Hitler Clark.
   Clark pleaded guilty to being one of two gunmen who shot Terry
Lamar Combs, 35, on Aug. 2 as the man was negotiating to buy cocaine.
   Prosecutors dropped a second-degree murder charge against Clark
on the condition that he plead guilty to the lesser offense and
testify against co-defendant Anthony Michael Cobb, 18.
</TEXT>
