<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Chappell 1stLd-Writethru a0540 11-30 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chappell, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0540,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Court Rejects Chappell's Election Challenge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6, `Messages were ...' with 3 grafs with James
comment; Picks up 7th graf, `Chappell's lawsuit ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Florida Supreme Court today rejected
Democratic U.S. Rep. Bill Chappell's lawsuit seeking to reverse his
failed re-election bid by throwing out ballots cast by nearly 11,000
voters.
   The high court, facing a self-imposed noon deadline before the
state's Elections Canvassing Commission could certify Republican
newcomer Craig James as the winner, issued its ruling in a brief
order shortly after 8 a.m. It planned to issue an opinion explaining
its reasoning later.
   The commission had been scheduled Monday to tell federal
elections officials that James, a DeLand lawyer, had won the 4th
Congressional District race, but the court delayed the meeting for
two days because of Chappell's lawsuit.
   A veteran of 20 years in Congress, Chappell lost to James by 732
votes in a recount of the Nov. 8 general election.
   Messages were left for Chappell today, but the telephone calls
were not immediately returned.
   ``We are delighted we had a victory for the people of the 4th
District,'' James said, adding that he had 11 lawyers research the
law. ``To attempt to disenfranchise the voters of the 4th District
is tantamount to being un-American.''
   James said in a telephone interview from Washington that he hopes
Chappell will concede and help ``with an easy transition.''
   Chappell's lawsuit sought to have Flagler County's election
results invalidated, claiming the county elections supervisor's
office missed a seven-day deadline after the election to file
returns with state officials.
   State law requires that returns be ignored if they arrive after 5
p.m. on the seventh day after an election, but the canvassing
commission said it would be unjust to disqualify voters because of a
technicality.
   Without the county's 10,907 votes, Chappell would have won by 288
votes.
</TEXT>
