<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Oliver-Antitrust     11-30 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oliver-Antitrust,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurance, Ag Co-ops Should Be Under Antitrust Laws, FTC Head Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurance companies and agricultural
cooperatives should be subject to the same antitrust laws as other
businesses, the head of the Federal Trade Commission said Wednesday.
   ``There is no good reason to continue the antitrust exemption for
agricultural cooperatives,'' Daniel Oliver told reporters at one of
his occasional briefings for the media.
   ``They are huge agribusinesses now, and whatever reason there was
for having an exemption 50 years ago, when perhaps they were smaller
... those reasons don't seem to exist today,'' he said.
   Repeating a call he has made often, he said he hoped Congress,
which moved toward ending the insurance industry exemption this
year, will complete action next year.
   Discussing directions that should be taken by the new
administration, Oliver also suggested a review of ``the unfair
competition faced by for-profit firms from the commercial arms of
not-for-profit entities.''
   Asked for an example, he cited pharmacies operated by hospitals
competing with privately owned pharmacies.
   ``Why should not all commercial enterprises be subject to the
same antitrust, tax and other legal obligations?'' Oliver said.
   Oliver's term as chairman of the agency, which supervises the
antitrust laws jointly with the Justice Department, has expired.
However, he remains in office until a successor is named or he is
reappointed. He has said he is available to retain the post, should
President-elect George Bush want him to do so.
</TEXT>
