<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Earthquake 1stLd-Writethru a0532 11-30 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Earthquake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0532,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING TO REPLACE GRAF MARKER AFTER EDS NOTE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Strong Aftershock Hits Yunnan Province</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with some injuries, communications
lines cut.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful aftershock today shook remote southwest
China and collapsed buildings damaged in an earlier earthquake that
killed 730 people.
   The official Xinhua News Agency quoted local officials as saying
an unspecified number of people were injured by the aftershock,
which registered 6.7 on the Richter scale. It did not mention any
deaths but said communications lines were cut.
   On Nov. 6, an earthquake in the region, China's worst in more
than a decade, injured more than 4,000 people. It measured 7.6 on
the Richter scale, making it nearly 10 times more powerful than the
aftershock.
   Xinhua said the aftershock hit the Lancang area of Yunnan
province near China's border with Burma. The news agency said one
person was injured on Sunday when an aftershock of 5.9 hit the same
place.
   Li Muxun of the State Seismology Bureau in Beijing said some
buildings damaged in the Nov. 6 quake collapsed after today's
aftershock.
   Since Nov. 6, there have been more than 1,000 aftershocks.
   No one answered telephones at Yunnan provincial government
offices.
   The area contains mountainous, heavily forested terrain that has
slowed rescue efforts and made it difficult to ascertain the extent
of damage.
   The report said the latest tremor was felt in the provincial
capital of Kunming, 240 miles to the northeast.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seimographs.
   An earthquake with a reading of 6 is capable of causing
substantial damage in a populated area.
</TEXT>
