<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Nancy-Raisa 1stLd-Writethru a0453 11-30 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nancy-Raisa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Ladies To Have Final Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Desk: Top 6 grafs new with meeting announcement, picks up 7th graf
pvs, The testy relationship.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan and Raisa Gorbachev, who have had
a testy relationship in the past, will attend a luncheon next week
while their husbands meet elsewhere in New York, it was announced
today.
   The meeting would occur at the same time as the session
tentatively set for Governor's Island, where President Reagan,
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Vice President George Bush
are to confer over lunch next Wednesday.
   The two women, whose frosty relationship has become a sideshow in
superpower gatherings, will attend a gathering hosted by Marcella
Perez de Cuellar, the wife of the U.N. Secretary General, Javier
Perez de Cuellar.
   Mrs. Reagan's spokeswoman, Elaine Crispen, said that other
Americans and Soviets will be invited to the lunch, including
Barbara Bush and Helena Shultz. It will be held at Mrs. Perez de
Cuellar's residence in New York City, Mrs. Crispen said.
   Mrs. Reagan's spokeswoman said the first lady planned to travel
to New York for a private dinner with friends on Tuesday evening and
that she did not expect to change that schedule.
   She plans to return to Washington Wednesday evening with the
president, Mrs. Crispen said.
   The testy relationship between Mrs. Reagan and Mrs. Gorbachev was
apparent during their last meeting in Moscow during the spring
summit between Reagan and Gorbachev, as they openly competed for the
spotlight during their tours of Moscow and Leningrad.
   Mrs. Reagan has said she found the Soviet first lady to be
somewhat abrupt during their past encounters.
   In an interview published Nov. 13 in the Los Angeles Times, Mrs.
Reagan was asked whether she found Mrs. Gorbachev to be rude.
   ``By our standards, I suppose, yes,'' she replied. ``Now, by her
standards, it might not be.
   ``It's just coming from two completely different cultures and
trying to get together for the first time and maybe one not
understanding how the other works,'' she said.
   Mrs. Reagan also said she believes that ``there was way too much
attention paid about that whole thing.''
   Ever since the two women first met over tea at the first
Superpower summit in Geneva in November 1985, there have been
persistent reports that they did not get along.
   Mrs. Reagan did not accompany her husband to the hurry-up summit
held in Reykjavik, Iceland, in October 1986, but Mrs. Gorbachev did,
a move that reportedly irked the first lady.
   Their differing styles clashed during the Washington summit last
December, when Mrs. Gorbachev repeatedly interrupted a White House
tour to talk with reporters about subjects ranging from U.S. history
to sociology.
   In Moscow, Mrs. Gorbachev again spoke at length to reporters,
while cutting off Mrs. Reagan's attempts to do so.
   Mrs. Reagan, insisting, ``I want to say something, I want to say
something now, OK?'' finally got her chance to chat with reporters
after the Soviet first lady backed away.
</TEXT>
