<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cookbook     11-30 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cookbook,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Help Nuns Stuck With 94,000 Cookbooks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICOPEE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Money has been rolling in since word got
out that a small Catholic college was stuck with 94,000 cookbooks
and a printer's bill for $400,000 after a fund-raising project went
awry.
   ``I call it `felix culpa.' It's a latin expression meaning happy
fault that is used frequently in monastic circles,'' said Sister
Judith O'Connell, assistant development director for Our Lady of the
Elms College.
   Sister Judith said Wednesday hundreds of mail orders have been
arriving daily at the women's college since, to the sisters'
chagrin, their plight was publicized in mid-November.
   ``People do care,'' she said. ``Those in Topeka, Kan., and
Houston, Texas, have been particularly kind, but we've gotten orders
from 20 states.''
   Although too swamped to give an exact number, she said more than
5,000 orders have already been filled, and some companies have
approached the sisters about distributing the book.
   ``If it keeps up we could sell all the cookbooks.'' she said.
``We really do believe in miracles. And the response to that story
has become part of our miracle.''
   The Sisters of St. Joseph, who run the 750-student college, had
hoped to raise $1 million for scholarships through sales of the
350-recipe book, ``In Good Taste'' at $10 a copy. But a year later
they had sold only 6,000 copies.
   Sister Mary Dooley, college president, acknowledged that the
100,000-copy printing may have been ``over optimistic.''
   ``We've gotten such lovely letters from all sorts of people,''
said Sister Judith.
   One man sent a check for $500 for 25 books. ``He said that he had
been educated by one of the sisters that is now working at the
college,'' she said. Another tried to cheer the sisters by tucking a
book of poetry into his order.
   ``Some said they were touched by a small school committed to
providing an education for people who wouldn't otherwise be able to
afford college,'' Sister Judith said. ``Others said they just
believed in religious education or were cookbook collectors. But in
large part, it is really a tribute to sisters all over the country
and the way these women have touched people's lives.''
</TEXT>
