<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1320EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SuicidePact     11-30 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Suicide Pact,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comatose Man Who Sued `Judas Priest' Pronounced Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 23-year-old man who sued the heavy-metal rock
group Judas Priest after his 1985 suicide attempt has died six days
after lapsing into a coma, a hospital spokesman said today.
   James Vance was pronounced dead at 10:48 p.m. Tuesday, Washoe
Medical Center spokesman David Stipech said. He had been in a coma
and on life support since Thanksgiving Day.
   An autopsy was scheduled to determine the cause of Vance's death.
   Vance and his parents are suing Judas Priest, claiming subliminal
messages in the British group's music caused Vance and Raymond
Belknap, 19, to make a suicide pact after listening to the group's
``Stained Class'' album for several hours.
   The two took a shotgun to a church playground in nearby Sparks
two days before Christmas 1985 and shot themselves in the head.
Belknap died instantly and Vance was disfigured after shooting away
part of his face.
   The 1986 lawsuit filed by the Vance and Belknap families is
pending in Washoe District Court.
   Vance was admitted to the hospital Nov. 15 for treatment of
depression and was scheduled to be released last Thursday, the day
he went into a coma.
   Phyllis Vance said doctors told her a short time later that her
son was 99.9 percent brain dead.
   Vance's attorney, Timothy Post, said he has ``a strong, strong
hunch'' that a drug overdose sent his client into a coma. Before
Vance died, Post said his death would have no effect on the lawsuit.
   He added that Vance already has given lengthy depositions which
could be read in a court proceeding.
   Mrs. Vance said doctors told her only that they were uncertain
what caused the coma.
</TEXT>
