<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MissingIranians Bjt   11-30 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Iranians, Bjt,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Missing Iranians Becoming Key Element in Hostage Drama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Iranians seized in Lebanon by
Christian militiaman six years ago are becoming an important element
in efforts to free Western hostages held by Lebanese kidnappers
loyal to Iran.
   Senior officials in Tehran have offered in recent months to use
their influence with the Lebanese Shiite Moslems holding Westerners
if the hostages' governments helped locate and free the Iranians.
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, Iran's military commander and parliament
speaker, addressed this remark to Washington last week: ``If you are
interested in having your people held hostage in Lebanon released,
then tell the Phalangists (Christian militia) to release our people
who have been in their hands for years.''
   Mohammad Javad Larijani, Iranian deputy foreign minister, told
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany on Tuesday:
``There aren't just American hostages in Lebanon. There are also
Iranian hostages who are in the hands of Christian militiamen.''
   Informed Lebanese sources have said the Iranians were believed
killed soon after their abductions, like hundreds of other Moslems
and Christians seized by the other side in Lebanon's 13-year-old
civil war.
   One purpose of Genscher's trip to Tehran was to mediate the
release of Western captives. His good contacts in Iranian leaders
were a key factor in the release of three West Germans held in
Lebanon.
   Nine Americans are among the 14 Western captives in Lebanon.
Peter Winkler, a Swiss employee of the Red Cross employee, was
abducted by three unidentified gunmen Nov. 17 but there has been no
claim of responsibility.
   Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Christian militiamen seized the three Iranians and their Lebanese
Shiite driver, who had an Iranian passport, in July 1982 at a
checkpoint 25 miles north of Beirut during the Israeli invasion of
Lebanon.
   They were identified as Ahmad Motevaselian, commander of the
Iranian Revolutionary Guards based in the Bekaa Valley of eastern
Lebanon; Charge d'Affaires Hussein Musavi, and Kazem Akhavan, a
correspondent for Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   The checkpoint at the extreme norh of Lebanon's Christian
enclave, was controlled at the time by the Lebanese Forces, the main
Christian amilitia.
   Nothing was heard of the Iranians until Aug. 31, when Samir
Geagea, now commander of the Lebanese Forces, confirmed the militia
had seized them.
   Geagea added that he could find no trace of the missing men when
he took over the 6,000-member militia in 1986 after a bloody
factional battle.
   He accused his predecessor, Elie Hobeika, of kidnapping the
Iranians and taking them to his Beirut headquarters for
interrogation ``because they were foreigners.''
   Their car was found abandoned in Tripoli, a predominantly Moslem
port 50 miles north of Beirut, several days after they disappeared,
Geagea said. He did not explain how it got there.
   Hobeika, ousted as Lebanese Forces commander in January 1986, was
widely believed to have led pro-Israeli Christian militiamen who
massacred hundreds of men, women and children in Beirut's Sabra and
Chatilla refugee camps in September 1982.
   The slaughter apparently was in revenge for the bomb
assassination several days earlier of President-elect Bashir
Gemayel, a Maronite Catholic, which the Lebanese Forces blamed on
Palestinian guerrillas.
   After two visits to Beirut in August seeking word of the
Iranians, the Right Rev. John Brown said their fate remains a
mystery.
   ``I haven't found any concrete evidence that will suggest to me
beyond doubt that they are alive or dead,'' said Brown, the Anglican
bishop of the Persian Gulf and Cyprus.
   He was sent to Lebanon by Archbishop Robert Runcie, spiritual
head of the Church of England, ``to show the Iranian government that
the Christian Church has a compassionate interest in Moslem victims
of the war in Lebanon as it has ... in the fate of Christian people
who've been taken.''
   The bishop had visited Tehran earlier seeking help in freeing
Britons held in Lebanon. They include Runcie's personal envoy, Terry
Waite, who disappeared Jan. 20, 1987, after leaving his hotel in
Moslem west Beirut to negotiate with kidnappers holding Americans.
   Brown said senior officials in Tehran made clear they would use
their influence with the kidnappers after the fate of the Iranians
was determined.
</TEXT>
