<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DogAbuse     11-30 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dog Abuse,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unopened Dog Food Bags Found At Kennel With Starving Dogs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OCALA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigator who discovered two dead and 23
starving greyhounds at a kennel said Wednesday that four unopened
50-pound bags of dog food also were found.
   Jaye Perrett, chief investigator with the Marion County Humane
Society cruelty division, described the dogs as ``covered with ticks
and fleas and extremely emaciated.''
   The dogs were living at the Sandy Run Acres boarding and training
kennel in Sparr, north of Ocala. Kennel owner Sandra Borcheller, 25,
was arrested Tuesday on 25 counts each of animal abandonment and
animal cruelty.
   Ms. Borcheller was held Wednesday in the Marion County Jail on
$25,000 cash bond.
   She owned 12 of the dogs, including two that were found dead, Ms.
Perrett said. Ms. Borcheller said financial difficulties, including
the failure of some owners to pay kennel bills, kept her from
feeding the dogs, according to Ms. Perrett.
   ``The people I talked to from out of state said they had been
paying their board bills faithfully,'' Ms. Perrett said.
   Out-of-state owners tipped investigators to abuses at the kennel,
Ms. Perrett said. ``They had gone there to check on their dogs and
were told that their dogs had died.''
   Fifteen of the dogs have been destroyed, Ms. Perrett said.
   The surviving dogs are being cared for by the Humane Society
until their owners can arrange to pick them up.
   ``They're eating like little piglets, just as hungry as they can
be,'' Ms. Perrett said.
</TEXT>
