<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--NuclearSecurity     11-30 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Nuclear Security,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mock Terrorist Attack On Reactor Prompts Better Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PETTEN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said Wednesday they will
improve security at a nuclear reactor after marines posing as
terrorists staged a mock attack last week.
   The 20 marines needed only seven minutes to get to the Petten
reactor vault, which houses uranium suitable for making nuclear
bombs, news reports said.
   The research reactor near this northwestern village is operated
by the European Economic Community.
   Economic Affairs Ministry spokeswoman Jane Zuidema said the time
it took to stage the mock attack ``was too short for an outside
(security) unit to come to the scene,'' adding that private security
guards in the building were unarmed. The exercise was part of a
program to check responses to ``new terrorist techniques'' that
might be used against the nation's four nuclear reactors, Ms.
Zuidema said. She did not say what new security measures were
adopted.
</TEXT>
