<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Shuttle-Spectators     11-30 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Spectators,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tourist, Media Attention Drops For Atlantis Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pentagon secrecy, ominous weather and
a general feeling of anti-climax have discouraged tourists and
journalists from flocking here for the Atlantis shuttle launch.
   ``I think it's really a combination,'' Dick Young, head of the
NASA News Bureau at the Kennedy Space Center, said Wednesday. ``STS
26 (the Sept. 29 Discovery launch) was the first post-Challenger
flight and a lot of people were out here just to see if the shuttle
could fly, and we've proved that it could.''
   Because the Atlantis is carrying a military cargo, the Department
of Defense sharply restricts information, another reason for fewer
journalists, Young said. NASA expected fewer than 500 journalists,
in contrast with the nearly 2,500 who covered the Discovery launch,
the first shuttle flight since the Jan. 28, 1986, Challenger
disaster.
   ABC, NBC, CBS and CNN planned live coverage of the launch, but
their morning and evening news shows won't be anchored from the
space center as they were for the Discovery mission.
   ``Dan Rather is staying in New York and we're covering here with
about one-fourth the number of people,'' said Mark Kramer, CBS News
producer for special events. ``I believe the edge is off the story.''
   However, Kramer said he couldn't foresee any shuttle launch in
the near future that won't be carried live on network television.
Only CNN was on live when the Challenger exploded after liftoff,
killing the seven astronauts aboard.
   About 250,000 spectators lined roads and beaches to watch
Discovery lift off, but far fewer people were expected this time _
even before an approaching storm front threatened to postpone the
launch by a day or more.
   Hotels along the ``Space Coast'' that were packed for Discovery
had plenty of vacancies, and local authorities, not worrying about
traffic jams or crowd control, said only a few extra deputies would
be on duty at launch time.
   Because of the secrecy, NASA was not setting up its customary VIP
viewing site for celebrities and other special guests.
   Left moot for now was a dispute between journalists and NASA over
the post-Challenger decision to restrict the number of news media at
the launch site. NASA, citing safety concerns in case of a launch
accident, allowed 1,800 journalists at the complex less than four
miles from the launchpad. The others had to watch from a secondary
press site about seven miles from the pad.
   Young said the restriction policy will be reviewed if such a
large contingent of journalists turns out for a future launch.
</TEXT>
