<HEAD>Governor Pardons Former Leftist Terrorist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state governor on Wednesday pardoned
a former member of the Red Army Faction terrorist gang sentenced to
life in prison for shooting and killing a police officer,
authorities said.
   Manfred Grashof will be released because he has rejected his
militant views, said Hanns Schreiner, a spokesman for Gov. Bernhard
Vogel of the southern state of Rhineland-Palatinate.
   Grashof, 42, who has been in prison for nearly 17 years, was held
in investigative custody before a Rhineland-Palatinate state court
covicted and sentenced him in 1977. He is to be released on March 2,
1989, Schreiner said.
   Vogel, a member of the conservative Christian Democrat Union,
pardoned former Red Army Faction member Klaus Juenschke in June,
saying he also had given up his terrorist views.
   The group, which claimed responsibility for the attempted
assassination of a Finance Ministry official in September, evolved
from the Baader-Meinhof terrorist gang active in the 1960s.
</TEXT>
