<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietNuclear     11-30 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Nuclear,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Nuclear Weapons Plant in Contaminated Zone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A satellite company said Wednesday the
Soviet Union appears to be making nuclear weapons fuel again in an
area east of the Urals that was contaminated and abandoned after a
nuclear accident 30 years ago.
   ``The Soviets apparently think it is a logical step to have
activity that is contaminating in a contaminated area ... and they
seem to have the means to get people to work there,'' said Christer
Larsson, head of the Swedish-based Space of Media Network.
   Larsson said satellite photos taken by the Spot and Landsat
satellites in 1987 and last summer showed the Kysthym complex is
back in operation and a new facility is being expanded nearby.
   In a 100-square-mile area around it, all villages were abandoned,
there was no farming and many were overgrown with vegetation, he
said.
   The satellite images also showed the flow of water through Lake
Kyzyltash was cut off to keep contaminated water out of the Tech
River system, Larsson said.
   The Soviet Union started its nuclear weapons program in the 1940s
at the Kysthym complex to produce plutonium, a main component of
nuclear arms.
   It is widely believed there was a massive release of radiation at
Kysthum during the winter of 1957-58. The cause of the accident is
unknown and the Soviet authorities have refused to confirm it ever
happened.
   The company quoted Zhores Medvedev, an emigre Soviet biologist
who 21 years ago reported the accident to the West, as saying his
countrymen dumped nuclear waste into small lakes in the area,
filling them up almost completely.
   Medvedev, who lives in London, also was quoted as saying he heard
from Soviet nuclear safety officials that a second major accident
occurred in the area in 1967. This could not, however, be confirmed
by the satellite photos, Larsson said.
   The satellite company said the new nuclear facility lies three
miles northeast of the Kysthym complex. It is believed to be part of
a new set of military reactors constructed after 1977. It is not
listed in any official publication. The satellite photos showed that
it was expanded in 1987 and 1988 but was not in operation when the
photos were taken.
   But a major flow of hot water into Lake Kyzyltash showed the
Kysthym complex was operational, the company said. The hot water
would indicate it was being used for cooling reactors.
   The company showed photographs of the area to journalists but did
not make prints immediately available, saying they were for sale
only.
</TEXT>
