<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-GasTax     11-30 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Gas Tax,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Taxes On Oil, Gas From Reservations Argued</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   States do not trample on Indian rights by
taxing companies that produce oil and gas from tribal reservations,
New Mexico officials told the Supreme Court Wednesday.
   Attorney General Harold D. Stratton of New Mexico said the state
taxes do not discourage production or prompt producers to look off
the reservations for deposits.
   ``The taxes in no way hindered economic development,'' he said.
   But Daniel H. Israel, a lawyer for Cotton Petroleum Corp., said
the state taxes have ``a chilling effect'' on the ability of the
tribes to lease their land to private businesses.
   ``Inevitably, off-reservation development is more attractive
because of the lighter tax burden,'' he said.
   The justices, who heard 60 minutes of arguments, are expected to
announce a ruling in the case by July. The outcome is likely to be
important to Western states seeking guidance on what power they have
over tribal resources.
   Cotton Petroleum challenged taxes on oil and gas taken from some
15,000 acres of land on the Jicarilla Apache reservation in New
Mexico.
   The company pays taxes to the tribe amounting to about 6 percent
of its production and New Mexico levies five taxes on the company
amounting to 8 percent of its production.
   Cotton Petroleum challenged the two biggest state taxes on ground
they unlawfully overlap the tribal levies, violating constitutional
interstate commerce protections. The company noted that oil and gas
producers in the state with deposits taken from non-Indian land only
are taxed 8 percent of production.
   The company also said the state taxes are pre-empted by the
Constitution, because they conflict with federal laws aimed at
promoting Indian self-determination.
   The company said it paid $2.3 million in taxes to New Mexico from
1981 through 1985 but only received $89,000 in services from the
state.
   The New Mexico Court of Appeals upheld the state taxes last year.
   Stratton has said the case ``may very well set the course of
Indian-state jurisdiction in the future.'' He said there are more
than 250 cases nationwide that could be affected by the outcome.
   One issue the justices could decide is whether a tribe is
entitled to be treated in some instances as a state.
   Israel said Wednesday the court should afford that treatment to
Indian reservations ``in a limited sense only.''
   He argued, for example, that the Jicarilla tribe should have
``primary power with regard to its resources,'' thus limiting New
Mexico's authority.
   But Stratton said that approach could open the way to widespread
confusion.
   ``How we could treat tribes as states troubles me,'' he said,
noting there are some 250 reservations nationwide.
   The Jicarilla tribe is not a direct participant in the case,
although it has filed a so-called friend-of-the-court brief
expressing its views.
   The case is Cotton Petroleum Corp vs. New Mexico, 87-1327.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0127 </DOCNO>
