<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pell-Cuba     11-30 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pell-Cuba,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Urges Move Toward `Normalized' U.S.-Cuban Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, said Wednesday the time is ripe for
Cuba and the United States to take ``small steps'' aimed at moving
them toward ``more rational and normalized relations.''
   Pell also said Radio Marti, which beams news and entertainment
broadcasts to Cuba, ``exacerbates'' relations between the two
countries and should be curtailed.
   The Rhode Island Democrat commented after a trip to Cuba, which
included a private, three-hour meeting with President Fidel Castro.
   When apprised of Pell's comments, Sen.-elect Connie Mack, R-Fla.,
told reporters that normalizing relations with Cuba or cutting back
on Radio Marti was a bad idea.
   ``Absolutely not,'' said Mack, whose state has a large
Cuban-American population. ``This is not a time to show concessions.
We've got to keep the pressure on Castro.''
   But Pell said he believes the international climate favors moves
toward warming relations with the communist island state 90 miles
from U.S. shores.
   ``Peace is busting out all over the world,'' he said. ``We are on
the verge of a settlement in Angola with the withdrawal of Cuban
troops, the Soviets are committed to withdrawing from Afghanistan,
and U.S.-Soviet relations are vastly improved.''
   ``I return from this trip believing ... it is an appropriate time
to attempt to move toward more rational and normalized relations
with Cuba,'' Pell said. ``The policies of both governments have
become sterile; it is time to break the log jam.''
   He proposed opening talks between the two countries to discuss
the many issues that divide them.
   ``The Cubans expressed sincere interest in my suggestion that
relations can be improved by each country taking small steps to
demonstrate good will and upon which other, progressively more
difficult but mutually beneficial steps can be taken.''
   Pell said he is considering introducing legislation to lift the
current embargo on the delivery of medicines and medical supplies to
Cuba ``as a step in this spirit of moving toward a normalized and
rational relationship.''
   He said Cuba might respond by releasing the remaining long-held
political prisoners in that country and by cooperating with the U.S.
Coast Guard against narcotics trafficking.
   He also suggested that restrictions be eased on telephone calls
between Cuba and the United States and that more Cubans, especially
doctors and technicians, be permitted to visit the United States.
   ``We should begin with the little things while working toward the
more difficult issues like (Cuban involvement in) Central America
and the full embargo, so that, hopefully, the climate could be
created making possible a relationship that would better serve U.S.
foreign policy interests,'' Pell said.
   He said Castro ``got really excited'' when the issue of Radio
Marti was raised in the talks and denounced the broadcasts as an
infringement of Cuban sovereignty.
   Pell said Castro did not explicity state that he wanted better
relations with the United States and emphasized the problems and
irritants in the relationship.
   But he said Castro did say ``that they were interested in going
from one small step to another.''
   In another development Wednesday, President Reagan met with
Ricardo Bofill, founder and former head of the Cuban Human Rights
Committee, in a meeting his spokesman said ``underscores the
president's continued support for human rights in Cuba.''
   ``The president commended Mr. Bofill's efforts on behalf of human
rights and added that they serve as an inspiration for activists
worldwide,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters.
   Fitzwater said the committee, an independent human rights group
hostile to the Castro government, ``was a factor in leading to a
U.N. Human Rights Commission visit to investigate the situation'' in
Cuba.
</TEXT>
