<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing first 16 grafs, picking up 9th graf pvs,
``I'll be</NOTE>
<HEAD>GOP Claims Mitchell Election Moves Senate To Left</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day after he was elected majority leader,
Sen. George Mitchell said today that Democrats and Republicans
should move past their campaign attacks to face their biggest shared
problem _ the federal deficit.
   ``The campaign is over. We have serious problems, important
challenges facing the country,'' the Maine Democrat said, as he met
with his Republican counterpart, Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas.
   Both pointed to the budget shortfall as Congress' top priority.
But each stuck to his party's position:
   _Mitchell said Bush should submit his own proposals to cut the
deficit before Congress negotiates with the White House on such
touchy topics as spending cuts and tax increases.
   _Dole said Bush could wait, letting President Reagan submit his
fiscal 1990 budget next month and then, when the new president takes
office, make his own recommendations for changes.
   Appearing separately, the speaker of the House, Rep. Jim Wright,
called on Bush to reject his advisers' suggestions and quickly give
Congress his plan for cutting the deficit as a way of calming
jittery financial markets.
   Democrats want to force Bush to be specific on how he would cut
the deficit without raising taxes and still keep his other campaign
promises to boost spending in such areas as education, day care and
environmental cleanup.
   Bush has been silent on the question of whether he will submit
his own spending plan or simply go directly into negotiations with
Congress over the 1990 budget.
   While Republicans agreed with Democrats today on the need to work
together, Republicans made it clear Tuesday that they will point out
differences between themselves and the liberal Mitchell.
   ``I think it's a very good choice. George is very liberal, and it
will push the Senate to the left,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, a
conservative. ``Whoever won that race was destined to be the
spokesman for the Democrats in America.''
   ``It seems to me the Democrats have decided to move toward the
left wing of the party and decided to do so with considerable
momentum,'' said Richard Lugar, R-Ind. ``This could make it easier
for Bob Dole, as our leader, to obtain majorities.
   ``They are swimming against the tide of national politics,'' he
said.
   Mitchell, 55, of Maine, was elected Tuesday by the Democrats of
the next Senate, handily defeating rivals Daniel Inouye of Hawaii
and Bennett Johnston of Louisiana. Mitchell won 27 votes on the
first ballot, compared with only 14 each for the others, and he then
was declared the winner by acclamation.
   The former federal judge and prosecutor emerged from Tuesday's
secret meeting and sounded a tone of caution and compromise,
declaring that the Democrats would develop an agenda and ``wait with
interest and enthusiasm for the proposals of the next
administration.''
   ``We hope to move forward on a broad range of issues,'' he said,
citing the federal deficit, health care, day care and the
environment.
   Dole, R-Kan., a colleague of Mitchell's from the Senate Finance
Committee who was re-elected to his post by GOP colleagues on
Tuesday.
   ``I'll be able to work with George Mitchell,'' said Dole, ``He is
a very bright, able and articulate senator.''
   Mitchell received congratulatory telephone calls Tuesday from
President Reagan, President-elect George Bush, and Sen. Dan Quayle,
R-Ind., the vice-president elect. Mitchell and Bush discussed plans
to meet soon.
   As majority leader, Mitchell is in charge of the legislative
schedule, a power that will put him at the center of every important
issue. He'll bring to the role a far different style from that of
the man he's succeeding, Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.
   Byrd, the Democrats' leader for the past decade, is known for his
intricate, behind-the-scenes legislative maneuvering. Mitchell is a
relative newcomer to the Senate _ he was first appointed in 1980 _
and is more comfortable on television and in public debate.
   His voting record received an 85 percent rating from the liberal
Americans for Democratic Action, compared to a 14 from the American
Conservative Union.
   Mitchell's opponents followed Senate courtesy after the election,
praising and defending the new leader.
   He will be ``a great spokesman'' who will put a personal stamp on
the Senate and help the party, predicted Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev.,
who had supported Inouye.
   ``I think he'll do a competent job. He's judicious. I think he
will make a good spokesman, articulate, thoughtful,'' said Howell
Heflin, D-Ala., who supported Johnston.
   ``Whomsoever leads the party, I think is going to try to keep it
in the mainstream,'' said Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, who was the
Democrats' vice presidential nominee.
   Bentsen's Texas colleague, Republican conservative Phil Gramm,
said the choice showed that the Democrats had not learned the lesson
of Michael Dukakis' losing candidacy.
   ``The fact that the only candidate who called himself a liberal,
that the only candidate from the Northeast won, is an indication
that the 1988 elections were not an aberration,'' he said. ``It
reflects the heart and soul of the Democratic Party.''
   Byrd steps down from his majority leader post to take the title
of president pro tempore of the Senate, a largely ceremonial post
which puts him third in succession to the presidency. The real plum
for Byrd is that he also will be chairman of the powerful Senate
Appropriations Committee, which approves spending by government
agencies.
   Both Inouye and Johnston will continue to be powerful senators,
with Inouye remaining as part of the leadership structure and
becoming chairman of the Senate appropriations subcommittee on
defense.
</TEXT>
