<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LaRouche 1stLd-Writethru a0452 11-30 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Told LaRouche Advised He Not Obligated to File Tax Returns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with testimony; picks up 4th graf pvs, Welsh's
testimony. Removes last 4 grafs pvs to shorten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tax lawyer advised staffers of Lyndon H.
LaRouche Jr. to file federal tax returns even though it was not
clear that the law required LaRouche to, a witness at the political
maverick's conspiracy trial testified today.
   Richard Welsh, a LaRouche finance officer, said he met with the
tax lawyer to see whether LaRouche was obligated to file returns
even if he had no income and all his expenses were paid for by
organizations that were part of his political movement.
   Welsh told the jury he was told that the assistance to LaRouche
should be treated as ``ordinary business expenses'' by the companies
and not as LaRouche's personal income.
   A federal grand jury has charged that LaRouche conspired to
defraud the Internal Revenue Service by not declaring the personal
and household expenses he received as income and by not filing
federal income tax returns since 1979.
   Welsh said the tax lawyer ``recommended that a tax return be
filed, not because it was required'' but because LaRouche was ``a
controversial public figure'' and filing the returns ``would be kind
of a public relations act.''
   Welsh said the tax lawyer told LaRouche staffers ``it was a gray
area. It was not clear liability existed.''
   Welsh said that although returns were prepared after 1979 they
were not filed because they included only arbitrary estimates of the
amounts that could be attributed to LaRouche's personal and
household expenses.
   In earlier testimony, Welsh said LaRouche has been the ``leading
thinker'' for his politically extreme movement but never asserted
strong financial control over its operations.
   ``I don't recall him involved in day-to-day financial
operations,'' Welsh, a LaRouche financial official for 14 of his 15
years with the movement, said Tuesday, testifying under a grant of
immunity from prosecution.
   Welsh's testimony distancing LaRouche from his financial
operations could be crucial when jurors decide whether he and six
associates conspired to avoid repayment of loans the movement
received.
   That is the main charge against all seven defendants in the U.S.
District Court trial. LaRouche also is charged with conspiring to
defraud the Internal Revenue Service by failing to pay taxes after
1979.
   LaRouche showed little emotion as Welsh described the three-time
presidential candidate as ``the founder and leading thinker'' of the
movement, and ``the primary person who defines broad policies ...
general objectives and political goals.''
   The movement relies on conspiracy theories to explain world
events, and it often alleges that figures such as Henry Kissinger
and Queen Elizabeth participate in those conspiracies. LaRouche
backers, who advocate a quarantine for AIDS victims, also have been
accused of harboring anti-Semitic beliefs.
   While denying that LaRouche had a heavy hand over finances, Welsh
said those who did handle the books _ including himself _ had
launched an ambitious plan to straighten out the movement's
financial mess in 1986.
   The witness said the program, which he dubbed ``Project Apollo,''
came to a quick halt on Oct. 6, 1986, when federal and state law
enforcement authorities raided LaRouche's Leesburg, Va.,
headquarters and ``seized just about every scrap of paper having to
do with any financial record.''
   Welsh said the project was set up to either repay loans, convince
lenders to convert them to gifts, or persuade the contributors to
ease the terms of the loans.
   But he told jurors the raid wasn't the only development that
jolted the repayment plan.
   In April 1987, he related, the three main LaRouche organizations
that owed lenders money were placed in involuntary bankruptcy. The
federal government action froze the groups' ability to conduct any
financial transactions.
   To make matters more complicated, Welsh said, several banks froze
LaRouche organization accounts after it became public knowledge that
a federal grand jury in Boston was investigating the movement's
financial dealings in a separate case from the trial here.
   The grand jury indictment says more than $30 million in loans
were made to LaRouche organizations. Welsh said some $5 million were
repaid, adding that the indebtedness was reduced by $1.5 million
during Project Apollo before it was stopped.
   Under questioning from Assistant U.S. Attorney Kent Robinson,
Welsh said LaRouche was buying expensive Virginia properties at a
time when millions of dollars in loans went unpaid.
   Welsh said a LaRouche real estate company spent about $4 million
on land for a security training facility, for a summer camp for
children of LaRouche employees and a farm where LaRouche and his
wife, Helga, live when in the United States.
   During the same period, around May 1986, LaRouche wrote a woman
who was seeking repayment of nearly $113,000 in loans that she could
not be repaid because no discretionary funds were available.
</TEXT>
