<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1447EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SenateLeaders     11-30 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate Leaders,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitchell, Dole Huddle Over Senate Agenda</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
declaring ``the campaign is over,'' sat down with Republican
counterpart Bob Dole on Wednesday to begin work on their legislative
agenda at the dawn of the Bush administration.
   Mitchell, elected leader of the Senate's 55 Democrats on Tuesday,
went to Dole's Capitol office for private discussions and a later
lunch with leaders of both parties.
   Mitchell, a liberal from Maine, played down his ideological
differences with the new Bush administration. ``The campaign is over
and we've got serious problems, important issues facing the
country,'' he told reporters.
   ``We look forward to cooperating,'' Mitchell said.
   Asked what advice he would have for President-elect Bush,
Mitchell said, ``I'm going to listen to him and try to be
accomodating to his concerns.''
   ``Clearly, the president-elect, having assumed the leadership of
the nation, will want to put forth his own ideas,'' Mitchell said.
``I think we should wait and see what the president-elect's plans
are.''
   Mitchell was also referring to the fiscal 1990 budget, which the
administration will send to the 101st Congress shortly after it
convenes next January.
   Dole, who was re-elected as Republican leader on Tuesday, said
Bush probably will wait until President Reagan formally proposes the
next budget before acting.
   ``The president-elect has a little problem,'' Dole, of Kansas,
said. ``He's not the president yet.''
   ``Perhaps what he may do is let the Reagan budget come up and
then submit some recommendations,'' Dole said. ``That makes sense.''
   However, Dole cautioned, ``we can't wait too long. The American
people want Bush to succeed, they want Mitchell to succeed.''
   But, Dole said, ``They don't want to wait much more than six or
seven months.''
   ``By custom, by tradition, by law and by common curtesy, he
should be allowed to set his agenda,'' Mitchell said of Bush.
   Meanwhile, Mitchell said, Senate Democrats are ``acting to
develop and identify our own agenda.''
   ``We anticipate there will be substantial overlap,'' he said,
citing mutual concerns over the deficit and other issues.
   Mitchell and Dole were joined by other party leaders elected
Tuesday for the lunch, which also included discussions of committee
assignments in the upcoming session. Later in the day, Mitchell was
calling on House Speaker Jim Wright, a fellow Democrat, to discuss
party issues and priorities.
   Meanwhle, four of the five new Democratic members of the Senate
met with reporters and with Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., who was
chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
   Kerry called the group's election ``an affirmation of basic
Democratic values'' by the voters, noting it was the first time in
50 years that the party winning the White House lost seats in the
House and Senate.
   ``If there is a mandate ... it is to deal with education, our
competitive posture, housing, health care and child care,'' Kerry
said, noting that those were issues that not only the Democrats, but
also the winning Republicans in this election, had run on.
   In one way or another, the four new Democrats _ Herb Kohl of
Wisconsin, Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut
and Richard Bryan of Nevada _ repeated those themes as their
priorities in the 101st Congress.
   ``I won because I expressed the mainstream of the Democratic
Party,'' Lieberman said. ``I promised the people of Connecticut I
would fight for the things that matter to them and to their
families.''
</TEXT>
