<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Dodd-LatinAmerica     11-30 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dodd-Latin America,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dodd To Talk Economic Problems With Latin American Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd left Wednesday on a
20-day trip to meet with officials in five Latin American nations to
discuss the region's economic problems, including its heavy foreign
debt.
   Dodd, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on
Western Hemisphere affairs, will meet with government banking and
business officials as well as opposition political figures in
Mexico, Chile, Argentina, Uruguay and Brazil.
   ``The greatest challenge to democracy in Latin America lies not
in alien political forces but in the threat posed by economic
instability,'' the Connecticut Democrat said in a statement. ``And a
key factor in the region's economic difficulties is the capital
drain and resulting fiscal sacrifice caused by mammoth long-term
debt.''
   He said Congress and the incoming Bush administration must
address Latin America's debt problems ``squarely, credibly and
quickly.''
   Dodd will be a guest at the inauguration in Mexico City of Carlos
Salinas de Gotari as Mexico's next president. He will be accompanied
on the Latin American trip by Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., chairman of
the Senate Banking Committee's subcommittee on international finance.
</TEXT>
