<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--SkiPatrol     11-30 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ski Patrol,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plainclothes Deputies Will Patrol Summit County Slopes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRISCO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plainclothes deputies will be on the slopes
this winter, ready to arrest anyone caught skiing out-of-bounds.
   Such skiers ``will be taken to the jail and booked and we will
take their skis and poles as evidence of a crime,'' Summit County
Sheriff Delbert Ewoldt said Tuesday.
   Sixteen avalanche deaths have been reported in the last two
winters, and Ewoldt said he planned to strictly enforce the Colorado
Skier Safety Act in an effort to prevent further tragedy.
   Last year, Ewoldt's skiing deputies nabbed six violators. They
were not released from jail until they paid bail and each eventually
suffered the maximum penalty _ a fine of $300.
   Under the policy, deputies ski off-duty for no extra pay. Usually
one deputy skis while another prowls in a snowmobile.
   ``We ski alongside the boundaries,'' said Lt. James Doughty. ``We
have to observe the person going out of bounds.''
   Doughty said few skiers would stand a chance of eluding him.
   ``I had the snowmobile clock me,'' Doughty said. ``I was doing 50
mph.''
</TEXT>
