<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   11-30 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Born Jewish Settler Convicted of Manslaughter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court found a U.S.-born Jewish settler guilty
of manslaughter Wednesday in the shooting death of an Arab shepherd,
the first such conviction of an Israeli in the nearly yearlong
Palestinian uprising.
   Five Palestinians were reported shot in clashes with soldiers in
the occupied territories, hospital officials said.
   In Arab east Jerusalem, two firebombs were thrown at the U.S.
Consulate but caused no damage or injuries, consulate spokesman
David Good said.
   Good said the two gasoline-filled bottles were tossed over a
surrounding wall and hit the side of the building. But the firebombs
burned out harmlessly, he said.
   The settler, Israel Zeev, 38, was found guilty in Jerusalem
District Court for the May 5 shooting death of 28-year-old Jude
Abdallah Awad in a field near the Jewish settlement of Shillo in the
West Bank.
   Another Palestinian was wounded.
   Zeev, who claimed he fired in self-defense after the shepherds
threw stones, could be sentenced to up to 20 years in prison.
   Yakov Weinrott, Zeev's attorney, said he probably would appeal
the verdict but would wait until after the sentencing Sunday to make
a decision.
   A relative who asked not to be identified said that Zeev was
raised in Chicago and is the father of six children.
   The May 5 incident began when a Jewish woman spotted several Arab
shepherds in a field between the Arab village of Turmus Aiya and
Shillo, 18 miles north of Jerusalem.
   She called for help, and Zeev came and fired at the shepherds.
Witnesses told reporters that Zeev fired without provocation. They
said the victim knew Zeev and shouted, ``Israel, don't shoot.''
   District Judge Tzvi Cohen was quoted on Israel radio as saying
``reality is not a Western'' and concluding that ``Israel Zeev had
to know there's a possibility of somebody getting hurt when he fired
from the hip.''
   At least 316 Palestinians and 11 Israelis have been reported
killed in the uprising since it began Dec. 8, 1987. It is not known
how many victims may have died from civilian gunfire.
   Pinhas Wallerstein, a Jewish settler leader, is still being tried
in the slaying of a 17-year-old Palestinian in January.
   Police recommended last week that Rabbi Moshe Levinger, a founder
of the settlement movement, be tried in the shooting death of a
shopkeeper during a Sept. 30 stone-throwing clash. No action has
been taken.
   Leaders of the settlement movement, meanwhile, called on the army
to take harsher steps against Arab rioters.
   ``It seems to me we have a war going on here, but it is being
treated like a demonstration,'' said Haim Granit, a brigadier
general in the reserve army who lives in the West Bank settlement of
Elkana.
   The group urged the deportation of Palestinians caught throwing
stones and a ban on employment of anyone arrested for protests.
   About 1.5 million Palestinians live in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, which Israel has occupied since the 1967 Middle East war.
   On Wednesday, troops shot and wounded five Palestinians in
stone-throwing clashes in the occupied areas, Arab hospital
officials said.
   The army confirmed that one person was wounded in the West Bank
refugee camp of El Ain near Nablus, and said it was checking the
other reports.
   Also Wednesday, police released three Israelis suspected of
setting a fire that burned three Arab laborers to death as they
slept in a shack near Tel Aviv in August.
   Police freed the suspects after holding them for 90 days. Israeli
radio said police did not have enough evidence to bring charges.
</TEXT>
