<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SouthernBaptistFirings     11-30 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Southern Baptist Firings,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firing Of Southern Baptist Ministers On The Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANDERSON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bad communication with congregations and
pastoral immorality have led an increasing number of Southern
Baptist churches to fire their ministers, denomination officials say.
   A recent survey found that each month an average of 116 of the
approximately 37,000 churches in the Southern Baptist Convention
fire their pastors, said Norris Smith, the forced-termination
consultant for the Southern Baptist Sunday School Board.
   Other reasons given for the firings, which are up 31 percent over
a 1984 survey, were performance dissatisfaction, power struggles and
personality clashes, he said.
   Smith said he was surprised to find that the controversy in the
Southern Baptist Convention between moderates and conservatives was
not a big factor.
   Smith said that in many denominations, a pastor who is having a
problem can be transferred to a more receptive parish by the
denomination's hierarchy. But Baptist congregations hire and fire
their own pastors.
   The 1984 study, done by the Southern Baptist Convention's Sunday
School Board, surveyed only fired ministers. Smith's survey
interviewed directors of missions, who in the Southern Baptist
denomination may direct mission work in several churches in an area
and frequently are called on to mediate church controversies.
   A lack of communication between the pastor and church leaders was
cited in 13.4 percent of the firings, the most frequent reason given
by directors of missions for forced terminations. Smith said both
sides usually communicated poorly and lacked systems to deal with
conflict.
   Immorality was the primary cause in 12.9 percent of forced
terminations. That category included sexual immorality, theft or
mismanagement of church money and problems of personal integrity.
   Smith said various subjective reasons accounted for 44.6 percent
of the terminations.
   Details of the survey were reported by the Baptist Press, the
convention's news service.
</TEXT>
