<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1549EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EECSummit     11-30 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EEC Summit,0671</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit to Review Progress Toward Single Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the 12 European Economic
Community nations meet this week to review progress toward their
ambitious goal of forging a single-market EEC by the end of 1992.
   The two-day summit in Greece that starts Friday is the first
since British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher told her partners in
September that she can never accept a United States of Europe.
   Mrs. Thatcher favors removing barriers hampering free trade but
wants EEC borders to remain for security reasons. She does not want
a single market to lead to a monetary union with a single currency
and a central EEC bank after 1992.
   But French President Francois Mitterrand, West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and her nine other partners say the EEC must precisely
go down that road if it is to compete effectively with Japan and the
United States.
   The single market plan has also worried the EEC's two main
trading partners.
   Greek Deputy Foreign Minister Theodore Pangalos said the meeting
on the resort island of Rhodes will reassure Washington and Tokyo
that Europe won't turn protectionist.
   ``The spirit in which the (draft summit) declaration has been
formulated will have the effect of reassuring these unjustifiable
fears'' of a `Fortress Europe,' Pangalos said this week.
   The leaders will also review East-West relations and the Middle
East situation after the Nov. 15 declaration of the Palestine
National Council, the Palestinian parliament-in-exile, proclaiming
an independent Palestine.
   Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, the summit chairman, may
ask the EEC leaders to meet with Palestine Liberation Organization
leader Yasser Arafat. Greece has suggested an EEC-Arafat meeting
before, but to no avail.
   Last week the EEC nations welcomed the council's implicit
recognition of Israel, called for an international Middle East peace
conference but stopped short of recognizing the Palestinian state on
Israeli-occupied territories.
   Jacques Delors, president of the EEC executive commission, said
the summit must produce ``a major initiative'' on East-West
relations to coordinate efforts by EEC nations to extend trade
credit to the Soviet Union.
   In recent weeks, several EEC nations, including West Germany,
have granted some $8 billion in such credit to Moscow.
   Mrs. Thatcher goes to Rhodes pleased that her Sept. 20 bombshell
speech in Bruges, Belgium, launched a debate about the future of the
EEC, aides said.
   Delors said if Britain does not fall into line, its partners may
go it alone in creating a monetary union. He told the European
Parliament this month there was ``a deep political disagreement''
over the future of the EEC.
   ``I cannot exclude a crisis,'' Delors said on British television
this week.
   The summit will assess progress to date in creating a single
market, officials said. Such a market is said to boost economic
growth in the EEC by 5 percent, lower prices by 6 percent and create
some 2 million jobs.
   Under a 1985 treaty, this requires adopting 279 EEC laws, 40
percent of which have already been enacted.
   Among the proposed laws is a bid to harmonize value added taxes.
   Britain and Denmark oppose a proposal for two bands of VAT rates,
from 4 percent to 9 percent for some goods and from 14 percent to 19
percent for others. Britain sees VAT on food and children's clothing
as politically unattractive and heavily taxed Denmark fears a loss
of revenue and believes taxes on alcohol and tobacco must remain
high for health reasons.
   Mrs. Thatcher, facing a persistent terrorism problem in Northern
Ireland, is adamant that border checks can be abolished for goods
and services but, for security reasons, must remain for travelers.
   Pangalos said Greece will also guide the summit to discuss ways
of establishing EEC-wide social policies dealing with, among others,
workers' rights. This includes creation of a European company
statute that provides for worker participation in management, an
issue Mrs. Thatcher opposes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
