<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Tower     11-30 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tower,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prospective Pentagon Chief Tower Works for Five Defense Companies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. John G. Tower, the leading
candidate to be the new secretary of defense, works as a consultant
for five major defense firms, congressional records and a Tower
associate said Wednesday.
   The companies, which include some of the nation's largest defense
contractors, build an array of weapons ranging from nuclear-tipped
missiles to airplanes.
   Before retiring from the Senate in 1985, Tower was chairman of
the Armed Services Committee, a post in which he oversaw Pentagon
spending. During his 24 years as a senator, he was a strong
supporter of a variety of weapons, including those built by the five
companies.
   Tower did not return telephone calls Wednesday, but Richard
Billmire, a Tower associate, said the former senator was on an
annual retainer from Martin-Marietta, Textron, LTV Aerospace and
Defense Co., Rockwell International, and British Aerospace.
   Tower & Associates, the consulting firm formed by Tower,
registered with Congress last Feb. 2 as a lobbyist, according to
Senate records.
   According to Billmire, Tower registered as a lobbyist because he
had been asked by the White House to help lobby the Senate for
approval of the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces (INF) treaty.
Tower would not be required to register as a lobbyist in his
capacity as a consultant for the defense companies unless he lobbied
Congress on their behalf.
   Billmire, who works for Tower & Associates, said, ``We registered
because the White House asked for our help on the INF treaty and we
were working as consultants for these companies at the same time.
The companies make some components which go into systems that are
used for weapons affected by the treaty.''
   ``Tower wanted to be absolutely clear and up front about his
connections with the companies and he didn't want anybody saying
that the reason Tower was saying this or that about the treaty was
because it would have helped one of his clients,'' Billmire said.
   After retiring from the Senate, Tower was named by President
Reagan as a member of the U.S. team negotiating with the Soviets for
deep reductions in the U.S. and Soviet arsenals of long-range
weapons.
   After resigning that post, the former senator formed Tower &
Associates.
   Billmire declined to say what the firm was paid by the five
companies. But Tower might be expected to have received more than
$50,000 annually from each, according to a defense contractor who
spoke Wednesday on condition he not be named.
   Tower is also a member of the board of directors of the U.S.
subsidiary of British Aerospace.
   His work for the five firms was first revealed by New York
Newsday.
   Tower remains the leading candidate to become secretary of
defense in a Bush administration and has met several times with
President-elect George Bush, sources said Wednesday.
   Although Bush is expected to name Tower, the public announcement
is being delayed while representatives of the two men negotiate over
who might be named to other Pentagon jobs, said the sources,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
