<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-Hiring     11-30 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Hiring,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Chief Recruiter Says Number of Political Jobs Not Huge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's chief recruiter assured the
public Wednesday that the new president won't bring ``armies and
legions of political hacks'' with him when he takes the reins of
government next month.
   Even if Bush were inclined to dispense patronage that way, there
simply aren't that many openings in high places, transition
personnel chief Chase Untermeyer said.
   Untermeyer also predicted ``it may take longer to fill positions
in this administration than ever before'' because of the extensive
financial and security clearances required.
   There are 4,307 full-time political jobs in the government, but
Bush will not get to fill them all next year, Untermeyer said at a
news conference.
   Many Reagan appointees who have already been asked to submit
their resignations will not be tossed out on the street come Jan.
20, he said.
   Instead, the president-elect wants most to stay on until his
headhunters complete the task of finding all the ``fresh faces''
that Bush has promised to bring to Washington, Untermeyer said.
   Eventually, most of the holdovers will get their walking papers.
   ``This is not Ronald Reagan's third term. It will be George
Bush's first term,'' said Untermeyer, 42, a former assistant Navy
secretary for manpower.
   Untermeyer, whom Bush has already said will be his White House
personnel chief, sought to dispel the notion that the patronage
possibilities for the new president are boundless.
   He said political appointees comprised only 0.0014 percent of the
government's civilian work force, or ``one-seventh of 1 percent.''
   ``This I think would surprise a lot of people who imagine that
when any new administration comes in line, that there are armies and
legions of political hacks who are ready to take over all the
federal agencies around the nation and the world,'' he said.
   ``The four-star, main line jobs'' that require Senate
confirmation pay salaries that start at $80,000 and reach $99,500
for Cabinet officers.
   Also on Wednesday, four persons were named as the transition
office contacts for three departments and the Veterans
Administration. They are:
   _Energy Department, B. Reid Detchon, 40, a Bush speechwriter.
   _Health and Human Services Department, Margaret D. Garikes, 29, a
campaign policy analyst and former trial attorney for the Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission.
   _Labor Department, Richard W. Porter, 29, a campaign domestic
policy analyst and former lawyer-economist for the Chicago
consulting firm of Lexecon, Inc.
   _Veterans Administration, retired Air Force Col. Antonio Lopez,
54, a campaign deputy research director.
   By Untermeyer's count, there are a total of 5,807 political
appointments if Bush does not expand the ``Schedule C'' appointees
to Cabinet departments and agencies beyond the current 1,601.
   The 5,807 jobs include a maximum of 691 Senior Executive Service
slots for political appointees.
   But 1,600 of them are part-time appointments to boards and
commissions, many of them prestigious but not highly remunerative.
   And not all of the 4,307 full-time political appointments will
come open next year.
   They include the 860 federal judges, who are appointed for life
and usually turn over at the rate of 56 a year; 135 ambassadorships,
only about 50 of which are usually given to non-career Foreign
Service officers, and 138 regulatory agency chiefs, about 35 of whom
are chosen each year.
   Untermeyer acknowledged that apart from the high-level transition
officials gathering names and preparing lists of people for Bush to
choose, the president-elect's son, George Jr., was heading a
separate screening team looking out for the interests of longtime
Bush loyalists.
   He said that back in 1981, in the early days of the Reagan
administration, it became apparent that ``some of the spear
carriers, the people who'd worked precincts or driven cars for the
candidate or done all the usual dirty fingernail work of politics
were not being thought of.''
   ``There are such people in every campaign. There certainly are
people in the world of George Bush,'' said Untermeyer. The
president-elect ``got where he is retail, by remembering people one
at a time and we don't aim to forget them.''
   That doesn't mean jobs for all of them, he added. Some will wind
up on ``invitation lists to events at the White House'' or ``the
Christmas card list.''
</TEXT>
