<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Irish-Bombings     11-30 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish-Bombings,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Senior Retired Judges Criticize Bombing Convictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A campaign to reopen the case of four Irish people
serving life terms for bombings in Britain got a boost Wednesday
when two senior retired judges published an attack criticizing their
convictions.
   In a full-page article in the Times of London, Lords Devlin and
Scarman said evidence that surfaced since the trial of the
``Guildford Four'' should be heard by a jury, including testimony by
two IRA men who claimed they were responsible.
   Instead, an Appeals Court judge rejected the evidence and denied
a retrial.
   ``Our constitutional law on which our freedoms depend has been
disordered,'' wrote Devlin and Scarman, former Law Lords who
constitute the highest court in Britain.
   An array of public figures including lawmakers, newspapers,
former government ministers and the heads of both the Anglican and
Roman Catholic churches in Britain have called for a retrial or
outright acquittal.
   The case could have implications for joint Anglo-Irish attempts
to combat the Irish Republican Army. It comes amid persistent
complaints that British courts are biased against Irish suspects,
and at a time when the two countries are again quarreling over the
extradition of IRA suspects to Britain.
   The convictions under criticism are those of Carole Richardson,
29; Patrick Armstrong, 36; Paul Hill, 34; and Gerry Conlon, 33.
   On Oct. 22, 1975, after a five-week trial, London's Old Bailey
Central Criminal Court jailed them for life for IRA bombings a year
earlier at two pubs at Guildford, 30 miles southwest of London. Five
people were killed in one pubs while the other was evacuated in time.
   Armstrong and Hill received additional life terms at the same
trial for an IRA bombing Nov. 7, 1974, at a pub at Woolwich in
southeast London in which two people died.
   The pubs were all frequented by soldiers _ the IRA's prime target
in its war to rid Northern Ireland of British rule and unite it with
the Irish Republic.
   In 1977 the Appeal Court rejected the plea of innocence of the
Guildford Four. But in 1986, former Home Secretary Merlyn Rees
publicly questioned the convictions, and last year an all-party
delegation of legislators called for a review of the case.
   They argue the convictions were based solely on confessions that
may have been extracted with beatings and drugs. They also said two
IRA men convicted in another case, Joe O'Connell and Brendan Dowd,
claimed after the trial that they carried out the bombings and had
never heard of the Guildford Four; and that at least one of the four
had an alibi.
   Scarman and Devlin reasoned that since the Appeals Court does not
have juries, the Guildford Four could not have the confession of
O'Connell and Dowd weighed by a jury, as should have been their
right.
   ``Were they (O'Connell and Dowd) lying? ... That was a question
for a jury as it certainly would have been if the evidence had been
given at the trial,'' they wrote.
   They did not criticize the trial procedures, saying the judge and
jury behaved scrupulously, and they did not say whether they
supported outright acquittal or a retrial.
</TEXT>
