<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     11-30 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan Swears In National, Provincial Assemblies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benazir Bhutto took the seat her
father once held as parliamentary leader Wednesday and awaited an
invitation from Pakistan's president to form a government.
   She and other legislators in Pakistan's national and provincial
assemblies, elected in the first free vote in more than a decade,
were sworn in Wednesday.
   Ms. Bhutto, mobbed by well-wishers as she arrived at the National
Assembly, told reporters: ``As leader of the largest party in
parliament, I'm looking to the president to call on our party to
form the government.''
   If President Ghulam Ishaq Khan selects her, Ms. Bhutto would be
the first woman to lead a Moslem nation. The president is to
designate a prime minister Thursday night.
   In the National Assembly, Ms. Bhutto sat in the house leader's
chair, a seat her father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, occupied from 1973
until he was overthrown by Gen. Mohammed Zia ul-Haq in a bloodless
1977 coup.
   Bhutto was executed in 1979 after he was convicted of conspiring
to kill a political rival.
   Next to Ms. Bhutto sat her mother, Nusrat Bhutto, who also won
her first seat in the legislature in the Nov. 16 National Assembly
polls.
   The Bhuttos' Pakistan's People's Party won 93 of 205 seats at
stake, compared to 55 taken by their conservative rivals. The
remainder went to independent candidates and minor parties.
   The national legislature drew nearer to its full count of 237
members Wednesday as the new lawmakers voted to fill 20 seats
reserved exclusively for women. By-elections for the other seats
will be held later although no date yet has been set.
   Ms. Bhutto said her party can command a majority but refused to
say who else has promised to support her.
   Justice S.A. Nusrat, chief election commissioner, led 194
national assembly members in the oath of office.
   Then Ms. Bhutto rose as the first to sign the parliamentary role
book as her party group stood and applauded.
   ``I realize how important the struggle has been but we have
finally reached Parliament,'' she told reporters. ``Although there
are many limitations we are still hopeful of bringing about change.''
   Under the constitution, the president must designate a prime
minister from among the National Assembly who is most likely to
survive a vote of confidence.
   Ms. Bhutto has pledged to help restore democracy after 11 years
of Zia's rule.
   Under the Constitution, the president must designate a prime
minister from a person in the National Assembly who is most likely
to survive a confidence vote.
   Ms. Bhutto's has pledged to help restore democracy to Pakistan
after 11 years of Zia's rule. Zia, U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel and
28 others were killed in a Aug. 17 plane crash. An investigation
found sabotage as a probable cause for the crash, but no arrests
have been made and the probe is continuing.
</TEXT>
