<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1706EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Soviet     11-30 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Soviet,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Departs for Landmark Visit to Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's foreign minister travels to Moscow on
Thursday for the first Sino-Soviet foreign minister-level talks on
Russian soil in 31 years.
   Qian Qichen, and his Soviet counterpart Eduard Shevardnadze, are
to lay the groundwork for another landmark: a 1989 summit that will
bring a formal end to three decades of hostility and mistrust
between the world's two great socialist powers.
   Qian's two-day visit is to focus on the war in Cambodia, which
has been the main roadblock to an early summit between President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and China's senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   China has demanded that the Kremlin use its influence to prompt
Soviet ally Vietnam to withdraw its troops from Cambodia, where they
have been fighting China-backed resistance forces for the past 10
years.
   Deng and Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang have said a summit
could take place in the first half of 1989, depending on the pace of
progress on Cambodia at the foreign ministers' talks.
   Shevardnadze is slated to visit Beijing, probably in January, for
what could be the final meeting before the summit date is set.
   The last Sino-Soviet summit was in 1959 when Nikita S.
Khrushchev, accompanied by Foreign Minister Andrei Gromyko, met with
Mao Tse-tung in Beijing on the occasion of Communist China's 10th
anniversary celebrations.
   No Chinese foreign minister has gone to the Soviet Union for
talks since Chou En-lai, then also prime minister, in 1957.
   China and the Soviet Union split in 1960 after Mao accused
Khrushchev of ``revisionism'' and compromising with the capitalist
West. The Soviet Union responded by withdrawing Soviet engineers and
technology from hundreds of joint projects, dealing a painful blow
to China's fragile industrial base.
   Relations reached a nadir in 1969 when the two sides battled
along their disputed border. Mao called on the nation to prepare for
all-out war and each side stationed at least 1 million troops along
the frontier.
   The two countries began political normalization talks in 1982,
opening the way for an easing of tensions and a gradual increase in
trade, scientific and cultural exchanges.
   Last year border talks were resumed after a nine-year suspension,
and the foreign ministers have met the last two years during the
United Nations General Assembly session.
   However, China continues to stress there are ``three obstacles''
to full political and party-to-party relations _ Cambodia, Moscow's
occupation of Afghanistan and Soviet troop strength on the Chinese
border.
   The Soviet Union's decision to leave Afghanistan and its
withdrawal last year of an army division from Mongolia have shifted
China's attention to the Cambodian question.
   Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Li Jinhua said last week, ``the
Soviet Union has indicated on many ocasions its willingness to work
for an early settlement to the Kampuchean (Cambodian) question.''
But she called on Moscow to make further ``practical efforts'' to
get Vietnam out of Cambodia.
   In a commentary on Qian's visit, the official Xinhua News Agency
said, ``the normalization of relations between Beijing and Moscow
conforms to the fundamental interests of the two countries and
desires of the two peoples.''
   It said, ``both the Soviet Union and China are carrying out
across-the-board reforms to speed up the development of their
national economies, which require a peaceful external environment,
and good-neighborly relations in particular.''
   However, it stressed that normal relations do ``not mean a
comeback of alliance ties such as that in the 1950s'' when China was
heavily dependent on the Soviet Union for economic assistance and
followed the Moscow line on international issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1627EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FarmPrices     11-30 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Prices,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Prices Decline in November</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products in November
declined slightly from a month earlier but remained nearly 8 percent
above their level of a year ago, the Agriculture Department said
Wednesday.
   The department's Agricultural Statistics Board said in its
preliminary report that lower prices for hogs, corn, grapefruit and
soybeans were partly offset by higher prices for tomatoes, potatoes,
milk and sweet corn, resulting in an overall drop of nearly 1
percent for the month.
   In part driven by the summer's drought, prices received by
farmers had been rising throughout most of 1988 until September,
when the increase leveled off. November's decline was the first drop
in the price index since February.
   Despite the decline of the overall price index, some commodities
continued higher in November. Wheat, for example, rose an additional
6 cents per bushel to a U.S. farm price average of $3.90 per bushel,
the highest since it was $3.95 in May 1981.
   Prices of livestock and livestock products as a group were off
just less than 1 percent from October. Hog prices, at $36 per
hundredweight, were the lowest since June 1980, while beef cattle
prices were unchanged at $67.10. Dairy products and eggs were
higher, while broiler prices declined. Compared with November 1987,
the index was up 5.6 percent.
   The department's all-crops price index for November, although
unchanged from October, was up 11 percent from a year earlier.
Prices of feed grain and hay as a group declined 3.7 percent from
last month and averaged 49 percent above the year-earlier level.
   Prices of commercial vegetables were up 22 percent from October
but off 30 percent from November 1987. Tomatoes led the price
increases, while carrot prices decreased slightly.
   Although the projections are subject to change, USDA economists
say that net cash income of farmers may be in the range of $55
billion to $60 billion this year, compared with the record level of
$57.1 billion in 1987. That is the difference between cash receipts
and cash expenses during the calendar year.
   Preliminary figures show that food prices for 1988 will average a
4 percent increase, about the same as last year's increase. For
1989, department economists are projecting food cost hikes in the
same range, about 3 to 5 percent.
   The report said:
   _Cattle averaged $67.10 per 100 pounds of live weight nationally,
the same as a month ago and up from $62 in November 1987. Those are
averages for all types of cattle sold as beef.
   _Hogs averaged $36 per 100 pounds, compared with $38.70 in
October and $40.60 a year earlier.
   _Corn, at $2.46 a bushel, was down from $2.58 in October and up
from the average of $1.61 per bushel a year earlier.
   _Wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures,
averaged $3.90 per bushel, compared with $3.84 in October and $2.69
a year earlier.
   _Rice averaged $6.38 per 100 pounds, compared with $6.75 in
October and $7.08 a year earlier.
   _Soybeans were $7.27 per bushel, compared with $7.53 in October
and $5.36 a year earlier.
   _Upland cotton was reported at 54 cents per pound, the same as
October and down from 66 cents in November 1987.
   _Eggs were 59.4 cents per dozen, compared with 58.7 cents in
October and 53.6 cents a year earlier.
   _Milk was $13.20 per 100 pounds, compared with $13 in October and
$12.90 a year earlier.
   _Broilers were 35 cents per pound, live weight, compared with
37.5 cents in October and 26.3 cents a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
