<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoliceCalendar     11-30 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Calendar,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Calendar No Hit With Chief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto AX4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fund-raising calendar featuring 12 officers in
mildly racy poses and brandishing weapons is under attack from the
police chief for glorifying guns.
   The calendar, produced by the police union to raise funds for
charity, shows officers pointing guns directly at the photographer
in several shots, including the cover photo. In one picture, an
officer is holding a machine gun, while a different photo shows a
female officer in a police T-shirt and black fishnet stockings
holding a pump-action shotgun.
   ``In today's violent society, I don't think anyone should glorify
guns,'' said Police Chief Morris Redding, who initially approved the
fund-raising idea.
   ``After viewing the finished product, I was disappointed,''
Redding said Tuesday. ``I was hoping it would show the officers in a
more professional light.
   But Detective Ken Cullifer, treasurer of the International
Brotherhood of Police Officers Local 623, which produced the
calendar, said it was perfectly natural for the officers to be
pictured with guns.
   ``If you were a plumber, you'd be standing there with a
plunger,'' Cullifer said. ``Police carry guns, so we used guns as
props.''
   Despite Redding's statements, police spokesman Cal Jackson said
he knew of no plans by the department to block calendar sales.
   Union officials said the police chief's approval was not
necessary for officers to appear in the calendar.
   If the 5,000 calendars that were printed sell, the union plans to
publish a calendar yearly. Cullifer said the $7 calendars have been
selling well.
   A message from the police union on the calendar says it was
produced to raise funds and ``to show you, the public, a different
side of the police officers who serve you every day throughout the
year.''
   Profits will go to the Atlanta Disabled Officers Fund and one
other yet-to-be-named charity.
   ``I hope no one takes it too seriously,'' said Detective Lisa
Roey of the Sex Crimes Unit. ``We're just trying to show that police
are people too, and we do people things just like everyone else.''
</TEXT>
