<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FactoryFire     11-30 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Factory Fire,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Probe Factory Fire As Firefighters Recover From Fumes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire at a plastics factory left 60
firefighters overcome by toxic fumes and prompted officials to
evacuate up to 800 people, authorities said.
   Twelve firefighters remained hospitalized Wednesday.
   ``The conditions were unusual,'' fire Capt. James Bielby said of
Tuesday night's fire. ``We had strong winds driving those chemicals
right at our guys. They went right to work and strapped their air
packs on, but you get a certain amount of that stuff just by being
around the fire. It only takes a few breaths.''
   Bielby said his department had lost track of records indicating
dangerous chemicals were stored at Divorce Plastics Inc. because it
had changed hands.
   ``It used to be a garage door manufacturer, but we weren't made
aware of it,'' he said. ``It's one of those cases where everything's
against you.
   As many as 800 residents were evacuated as 55-gallon drums
containing the chemical isocyanate exploded during the blaze, which
erupted about 8 p.m., officials said. They were allowed to return to
their homes about 3 a.m. Wednesday.
   Bruce Dorland of the Genesee County Coordination Center said
residents were evacuated as a precaution because isocyanate _ used
by the company to manufacture plastic automotive bumpers _ could be
harmful if swallowed or absorbed through the skin.
   The firefighters were listed in good condition.
   The fire caused about $3 million in damage and was under
investigation.
</TEXT>
