<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dali     11-30 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dali,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dali Remains in Critical Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surrealist painter Salvador Dali remained
in extremely critical condition Wednesday, but his secretary said he
asked to listen to Bach violin concertos when he woke up after a
quiet night.
   The 84-year-old artist is suffering from severe heart trouble
aggravated by blood clots in the lungs, according to doctors at the
Quiron Clinic.
   They limited the number of visits to the painter after too many
government officals called on him Tuesday.
   Maria Teresa Brugues, Dali's personal secretary, said Dali had a
``quiet night'' and asked to listen to classical music, particularly
the violin concertos of composer Johann Sebastian Bach.
   One of five doctors attending the painter said the fact there had
been no change in Dali's condition since Tuesday ``is a positive
sign, even if it does not clear away the uncertainty about his
future condition,'' according to the Spanish news agency EFE.
   However, his extremely critical condition should not be minimized
to create false expectations about a strong recovery, said the
doctor, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Dali was taken to the hospital in his hometown of Figueras, about
60 miles north of Barcelona, on Sunday after he developed pneumonia
and heart trouble. On Monday night, he was rushed to the intensive
care unit of the Quiron Clinic.
   The flamboyant artist, one of the founders of the surrealist
movement, is the last member of a generation of Spanish painters
that included Pablo Picasso, who died in 1973, and Joan Miro, who
died a decade later.
   Dali has lived in seclusion and suffered from frequent bouts of
depression since the death in 1982 of his wife, Gala.
   In 1984, Dali was severely burned in a fire at his home in the
hamlet of La Pera, 40 miles south of Figueras, and was hospitalized
for three months. Since then, he has been bound to a wheelchair, fed
through a nasal tube and attended by nurses round the clock.
   After his 1984 hospitalization, Dali moved to a residence
attached to his Theater-Museum in Figueras. In 1986, doctors gave
him a pacemaker.
</TEXT>
