<2ND_LINE>AM-Veep Mansion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veep Mansion Needs Work Before Quayles Can Move In</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lede and 5th graf, Mrs. Quayle, to change reference to
day of Mrs. Quayle's remarks to Monday sted Tuesday</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Quayle Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The vice presidential mansion may need some
alterations before the Quayle family can move in, Vice
President-elect Dan Quayle said Wednesday, echoing a sentiment
expressed two days earlier by his wife Marilyn.
   But Quayle's staff was quick to say the family is not finding
fault with the Victorian residence on the grounds of the Naval
Observatory and is actually pleased at the prospect of living there.
   Quayle said the mansion is not configured for a family with three
children. It does have six bedrooms, but some of those serve as
offices and servants' quarters and some do not have closets.
   ``There's just not enough bedrooms there for the children, so we
probably won't be able to move in right away after the Bushes move
into the White House,'' Quayle said in an interview.
   Mrs. Quayle told Senate wives the same thing on Monday, but an
aide said she had not seen the house at the time. Since then, she
has toured the house with Mrs. Bush and is ``quite eager to move
in,'' said spokesman Jim Carroll.
   ``She thinks it is a beautiful place and acknowledges they have
to make some modifications to accommodate three young children, but
is quite pleased with the residence,'' he said.
   The Quayles will continue to live at their home in McLean, Va.,
until they can move into the official residence. Their three
children _ Tucker, 14, Benjamin, 12, and Corinne, 10 _ will continue
attending public schools in Virginia for the time being, Quayle said.
   In 1975, the federal government spent about $311,000 to convert
the mansion on Embassy Row into an official vice-presidential
residence. The vice presidents who have used the house did not have
school-age children at the time.
   Nelson Rockefeller refurbished the mansion but did not live
there. Walter Mondale did not redecorate the house.
   Friends of the Bushes raised more than $100,000 in 1981 to
redecorate the residence and refurbish public rooms used for
official entertaining.
</TEXT>
