<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1802EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nuclear-Zech 1stLd-Writethru a0639 11-30 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear-Zech, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zech Says Nuclear Plants Safer, More Efficient</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 12 grafs after 6th graf bgng ``The capacity'' to
UPDATE with specific figures from NRC spokesman and comment from
anti-nuclear groups; pickup last 2 grafs pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
said Wednesday that U.S. nuclear power plants have grown safer and
more efficient over the last four years.
   The remarks by Chairman Lando W. Zech Jr. came at ceremonies to
dedicate an 18-story headquarters building for the NRC in suburban
Rockville, Md.
   He noted that ``in 1984 NRC began trend analysis of the key
nuclear parameters used to monitor reactor operation safety. From
1984 until now, there has been a clear and definite improvement.''
   Zech said there had been reductions in unplanned automatic
shutdowns, other safety system alarms and exposure of workers to
radiation.
   ``Along with this improvement in critical safety performance
indicators, we have seen improvements in plant reliability and
availability,'' Zech said. ``Recent data shows an increase in the
average capacity factors for U.S. reactors from about 59 percent in
1986 to almost 67 percent in 1988.''
   The capacity factor represents the actual output of a plant
compared to what it would generate if it operated at full power all
the time.
   NRC spokesman John Kopeck later provided the following specific
figures for the performance indicators cited by Zech:
   _``Significant operating events,'' meaning major problems: 2.4
per operating reactor in 1985; 1.6 in 1986 and 0.8 in 1987.
   _Unplanned automatic shutdowns: 5.24 per reactor in 1984; 5.04 in
1985; 3.96 in 1986 and 3.24 in 1987.
   _Safety system actuations: 2.76 per reactor in 1984; 2.6 in 1985;
2.04 in 1986 and 1.68 in 1987.
   _Precursor events signaling the possibility of a major accident:
a nationwide total of 17 in 1984; 10 in 1985 and 6 in 1986.
   _Radiation exposure: 714 man-rem in 1984; 574 man-rem in 1985;
431 in 1986 and 425 in 1987.
   Man-rem is a measure of radiation exposure for large numbers of
people. For example, when 100 people receive an average exposure of
0.01 rem, that would result in a figure of 1 man-rem.
   Spokesmen for anti-nuclear groups questioned Zech's assessment.
   Kenneth Bossong of Public Citizen, a Washington-based public
interest group founded by consumer advocate Ralph Nader, said:
``It's a mixed bag. There are some positives and there are some
negatives. It's not fair or accurate for Zech to say everything is
looking better because it's not.''
   For example, Bossong said, ``on the radiation issue, what he said
is true as far as it went, but it's not complete. The average dose
per worker at nuclear power plants has decreased since 1984, but the
number of workers exposed, on the other hand, has increased.''
   He said the number of workers exposed has increased from 93,000
in 1985 to slightly more than 100,000 in 1986 and 104,000 workers in
1987.
   Michael Mariotte, director of the Nuclear Information and
Resource Service, another Washington-based public interest group,
said: ``There may be a slightly improving track record. However,
there's no reason to be smug about it. ... It seems like every time
they think something has been solved, they find a new problem.''
   The new 286,000-square-foot NRC headquarters building, purchased
by the government for $47.5 million, provides space for about 1,400
NRC employees. It marks an effort to consolidate operations of the
agency, which previously were dispersed among 10 separate buildings.
   A second structure is to be built at the same Rockville site by
1991 to accommodate the rest of the agency's Washington area
employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
