<HEAD>Restoration of Marcus Aurelius Statue Completed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marcus Aurelius is back in the saddle.
   The Roman emperor and his horse were reunited Tuesday after an
eight-year restoration of the gilded bronze equestrian statue.
   Restorers had detached the emperor from his steed after age and
traffic pollution took their toll on the 1,800-year-old work that
graced Rome's municipal square atop the Capitoline Hill.
   The statue will be on display at the San Michele Central
Restoration Institute for a month while city officials and experts
decide whether to return the work to the square and risk repeated
damage, or put it in a museum.
