<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chelsea-BU     11-30 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chelsea-BU,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Plan to Take Over Schools Clears Two Hurdles, Faces More</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston University's proposal to overhaul Chelsea's
impoverished public schools is close to a contract, but opponents
promise to fight private management of the tax-funded system.
   The unprecedented offer was made three years ago, when Chelsea
began looking for outside help. The 3,400-student district has the
highest dropout rate in the state and has not built a school since
1923.
   On Tuesday, Suffolk Superior Court Judge Walter Steele denied the
Massachusetts Federation of Teachers an injunction stalling the
contract with the university, although he noted there are questions
about its legality.
   Union lawyers said they would pursue their legal challenge,
maintaining that the contract would usurp local officials'
authority, particularly in the hiring and firing of teachers.
   The Chelsea School Committee nevertheless voted 5-2 Tuesday night
to tentatively accept the university's offer to run the district for
10 years. Officials said they expect to have a finished contract
within the next few weeks.
   John Zimini, president of the Chelsea Board of Aldermen, which
would have to approve the contract, defended the proposal Wednesday.
   ``We have to step out of the 19th century and get into the 20th
century,'' Zimini said.
   ``I think that it takes an awful lot of courage on the part of
the city to say, `Hey, look we've tried our best, the money's just
not there,''' he said. ``Unfortunately in our society any kind of
change is always a fear factor.''
   The working-class town on Boston Harbor, with its influx of
Hispanic and Southeast Asian immigrants, has been strained
financially by a 1980 state tax-limiting law.
   Zimini said he cannot predict how aldermen will vote, but
believes the contract will eventually be approved. It also requires
approval by the Legislature.
   ``It's not over yet,'' said Paul Devlin, president of the
Massachusetts Federation of Teachers. ``A decision as critical as
the constitutionality of privatizing a public school system should
be made by the higher courts.''
   University officials maintain they won't be taking the public
schools private, but will simply be managers who have to answer to
the School Committee.
   The university proposes to revamp the curricula, build new
schools, provide mothers and pregnant teen-agers counseling on
nutrition and child-rearing, tailor learning plans to individual
students and set up after-school programs.
   The state Board of Education has voted against the proposal in
its present form, saying it could not accept failure to require the
university to open its books. The board's approval is not needed,
but its recommendation could influence legislators.
</TEXT>
