<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     11-30 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>11 Die in Guerrilla Attack on Army Outpost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas Wednesday
attacked an army outpost with rifle and mortar fire, killing nine
soldiers and wounding several, the armed forces said.
   Two rebels died and about 15 were wounded in the two-hour
firefight, according to an army spokesman who requested anonymity.
   He said two air force jets and several helicopters armed with
rockets and machine guns helped repel the pre-dawn attack on El
Roblar, about 15 miles north of San Salvador near the Guazapa
volcano.
   In the eastern San Salvador suburb of Soyapango, guerrillas
burned a city bus and sprayed gunfire on a second Tuesday night, but
no one was injured, the spokesman said.
   Soyapango justice of the peace Isaac Fayes Gonzalez said four men
who had witnessed the attack were killed about a half hour after the
ambush, but he said he ``cannot affirm that the same ones who
attacked the buses also killed the four. That is conjecture.''
   In another incident Tuesday night, two guerrillas were killed in
a skirmish with troops outside the city of Jutiapa, about 20 miles
northeast of San Salvador, the army reported.
   Marxist guerrillas have waged a 9-year-old civil war against the
U.S.-backed government led by President Jose Napoleon Duarte. An
estimated 65,000 people, most of them civilians, have been killed.
</TEXT>
