<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Mail     11-30 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Mail,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legal Experts Criticize Police For Seizing Mail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legal experts have accused police of breaking the
law by seizing mail during a crackdown on contraband, an official
newspaper said Wednesday.
   Chinese lawyers and legal experts attending a seminar in the
northeastern city of Shenyang said police had violated citizens'
freedom of communication when they took 1,509 mail bags off a train
in September, the China Daily reported.
   The police action produced 27,387 cartons of cigarettes,
pornographic videos and other black market items on their way to
Shenyang.
   The bags were held for a month before being returned _ minus the
contraband _ to the post office for delivery, the newspaper said.
   A newsletter of the Post and Telecommunications Ministry, quoted
by the China Daily, said police failed to go through legal channels
and should undergo judicial review.
   ``The mail is protected by the law and you cannot act regardless
of the law ... even if your intentions are worthy,'' the newsletter
was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
