<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AmnestyApplicant     11-30 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty Applicant,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alien Applying For Amnesty Says U.S. Government `Trying To Help Us'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Amnesty Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesus Hernandez clutched the papers he hoped
would give him permanent residency status in the United States and
said Wednesday he believed the government is ``trying to help us.''
   The 25-year-old from Jacisco, Mexico, and his 20-year-old
brother, Jose, were among the illegal alien agricultural workers who
lined up in Oklahoma City to beat a midnight deadline for seeking
immigration amnesty.
   ``I have been here for four years, and I like it,'' Hernandez
said. ``Oklahoma is a real nice state.''
   Although he said he now works ``drawing designs'' for a monument
company in Enid, Hernandez said he and his brother harvested crops
before that. They will have to prove that to the satisfaction of
Immigration and Naturalization Service investigators to be eligible
for U.S. residency.
   A special provision of the 1986 amnesty law set a midnight
deadline for illegal alien agricultural workers to prove they
harvested perishable crops in the United States for at least 90 days
in the one-year period that ended May 1, 1986. If they do so, they
will receive temporary residency; later, they may apply for
permanent residency.
   Hernandez said he did not have too much trouble making it to
Oklahoma in 1984.
   ``I took a bus to the (Rio Grande) river and then walked,''
Hernandez said. ``I walked for two days and two nights until some
friends came for me in a car. They brought me to Oklahoma, and here
I am.''
   Hernandez' brother stayed in the background among the 50 or more
applicants waiting in the INS office as Hernandez spoke. The brother
shook his head no when asked if he would like to add anything.
   Some illegal aliens have expressed concern about the amnesty
program, fearing it was just a ruse to get them to come out of
hiding so they can be deported.
   ``I don't think so,'' Hernandez said when asked whether he
thought the government was fooling the aliens. ``I think they are
trying to help us. I think they want to help us.''
</TEXT>
