<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     11-30 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>12,000 Leftists Seek Ouster of U.S. Bases, Protest Crackdown On
Unions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of leftist workers and
youths cheered Wednesday as protesters burned an American flag and
shouted slogans seeking the ouster of U.S. bases and against an
alleged crackdown on militant labor unions.
   Elsewhere, the military reported eight people, six of them women,
were killed in three separate shootings on southern Mindanao island.
   Wednesday's rallies were led by the militant labor confederation
May First Movement to mark the 125th birthday of Andres Bonifacio, a
19th Century leader who led the fight against Spanish colonialists.
   Smaller rallies were also held outside the U.S.-run Clark Air
Base and in the central city Cebu, about 350 miles southeast of
Manila.
   Police said about 1,000 people turned out for the rally at Clark,
about 50 miles north of Manila. The U.S. military's Far East Network
television station said the main gate to the base was closed and
urged American servicemen to avoid the rally.
   In Manila, police estimated that some 12,000 protesters attended
the rally, most of them carrying red streamers with anti-U.S.
slogans. The protesters shouted slogans and waved banners calling
for the dismantling of six U.S. installations in the country.
   The demonstrators burned a U.S. flag at a downtown square in
front of the central post office and later marched to Mendiola
Bridge, the main gateway to President Corazon Aquino's office.
   About 500 police were deployed at the bridge, where the marchers
held a brief rally.
   Leto Villar, vice chairman of the May First Movement, told the
crowd the government was mounting an anti-communist propaganda
campaign but ``we know that communism is not the cause of poverty.''
   Leftists have accused the police and military of cracking down on
legal left-wing organizations. Two leaders of a Movement-affiliated
transport workers union were arrested last week and charged with
inciting to sedition after leading a strike of passenger jeep
operators.
   Dozens of activists and leftist union organizers have disappeared
in recent weeks. Their families believe they were either kidnapped
or murdered by police or soldiers.
   The military claims the Movement is a communist front, but union
officials deny the charge.
