<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     11-30 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syrian Soldiers Raid Homes To Search For Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian troops raided suspected weapons
depots in Moslem neighborhoods Wednesday after six days of violence
between rival militias killed 40 people and wounded 87.
   The Syrian command said the searches by 200 helmeted Syrian
troops in trucks and an armored personnel carrier were aimed at
making west Beirut a demilitarized city.
   The cleanup operation was launched Monday after almost a week of
clashes between members of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of
God, and the pro-Syrian Amal, Arabic for hope, in south and west
Beirut.
   The battles between the militias may be endangering the lives of
14 Western hostages, including nine Americans, believed held by
Hezbollah in the slums of Beirut.
   In the past two days, Syrian troops detained 350 suspected
militia gunmen in house raids, said a police spokesman, who demanded
anonymity. He said most of them have been released after being
interrogated, but about a dozen remain in custody.
   ``The Syrian command should disarm both Amal and Hezbollah to
prevent further clashes,'' said Sheik Mohammed Mehdi Shamseddin,
Lebanon's senior Shiite cleric, in a broadcast on the Moslem Voice
of Nation radio.
   On Wednesday, Syrian troops confiscated two rifles buried in an
empty lot in the Mossaitbeh district, witnesses said.
   The Syrians entered two buildings occupied by Shiite squatters in
the old Jewish quarter of Wadi Abu Jamil and a deserted Shiite
mosque in the Rawsheh neighborhood, but they found no weapons, said
one witness, who refused to be identified.
   ``A Syrian officer asked several residents in Wadi Abu Jamil
whether they had weapons. All of them said they didn't have weapons
and the officer seemed to believe them because he did not order the
troops to search their apartments,'' the witness said.
   The two militias are vying for dominance of Lebanon's 1 million
Shiites, the nation's largest religious sect.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 40,000 troops
in the eastern and northern provinces and in Beirut.
   The Syrians entered the city on Feb. 22, 1987, to end three years
of battles between militias that has resulted in killings,
kidnappings and robberies.
</TEXT>
