<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1721EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Economy     11-30 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Personal Income Makes Largest Gain in 12 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American personal income posted its largest
gain in a year in October, the government said Wednesday in a report
cited as more evidence of economic strength and inflationary
pressure.
   However, a separate report to the Federal Reserve Board found
evidence of ``an apparently slower pace'' of growth. Financial
markets rallied, interpreting it as a signal that Fed members are
less worried about inflation than previously thought.
   The Commerce Department said personal income rose 1.8 percent,
the biggest rise since October 1987, to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of $4.18 trillion last month. The gain followed modest
increases of 0.5 percent in September and 0.4 percent in August.
   The department attributed about half of last month's increase to
farm subsidy payments and bonuses to auto workers. However,
excluding those factors, income still would have risen a hefty 0.9
percent.
   ``This throws cold water on the view the economy slowed down
much,'' said John Hagens, an economist with The Wefa Group, a Bala
Cynwyd, Pa., forecasting firm. ``It may have taken a bit of a pause
in August and September, but it came roaring back in October.''
   The concern in financial markets has been that growth is too
strong. High levels of employment will lead to higher wages, and
strong consumer demand will lead to higher prices, they fear.
   Sandra Shaber, an economist with The Futures Group, a Washington
consulting firm, said retailers likely will be pleased with the
income gains.
   ``There are more people working and people are earning more
money,'' she said. ``Retailers will be at least reasonably satisfied
with the Christmas season.''
   However, in a review of the economy based on assessments from the
12 regional Federal Reserve banks, the Fed reported ``an apparently
slower pace'' of growth, moderate wage increases and slightly eased
price pressures in several manufacturing industries.
   ``It doesn't sound like the same economy we're looking at,''
Hagens said.
   Personal consumption spending, which includes everything except
interest payments on debt, was up a robust 0.8 percent to an annual
rate of $3.30 trillion following a weak 0.1 percent rise in
September.
   The biggest spending increase last month was for services, up 1.4
percent, followed by a 0.6 percent increase for non-durable goods.
Spending on durable goods, ``big ticket'' items expected to last
three or more years, fell 0.6 percent.
   With income rising faster than spending, Americans saved more
than in any month since October 1987. The personal savings rate _
savings as a percentage of after-tax income _ was 5.2 percent, up
from 4.2 percent in September.
   Disposable, or after-tax income, was up 1.9 percent last month,
also the largest increase in a year, after rising 0.6 percent a
month earlier.
   Wages and salaries, a key component of personal income, were up a
strong 1.5 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $2.51
trillion, bolstered by a 2.1 percent increase in manufacturing
salaries. The auto bonuses accounted for about 60 percent of the
manufacturing increase.
   Farm income rose a huge 76.2 percent to an annual rate of $46.7
billion, largely because of government payments for corn harvested
in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
