<1ST_LINE>u w AM-EconomicOutlook     11-30 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economic Outlook,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy a0730</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fed Reports Slower Industrial Growth, Eased Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve's district banks in
November reported ``apparently slower'' growth, moderate wage
increases and slightly eased price pressures in several
manufacturing industries, according to a report released Wednesday.
   The new report, based on surveys conducted by the 12 Fed district
banks, stirred a rally in financial markets Wednesday as investors
interpreted the findings as a signal that the Fed might be williing
to loosen its credit policy because of signs of a slowing economy
and easing inflationary pressures.
   However, some private economists said they believed the Fed
district banks were overstating the economic slowdown and the
central bank will still be forced to tighten credit conditions in
coming months.
   ``We think there will be more consumer price inflation,'' said
John Hagens, chief economist for the WEFA Group, an economic
consulting firm. ``We think it is almost inevitable that the Fed
will continue to tighten.''
   The Fed survey was prepared for the Dec. 13-14 meeting of the
Fed's policy-making Open Market Committee, the panel which sets
monetary policy for the central bank.
   ``Most districts report continued economic growth, but at an
apparently slower pace than in previous months,'' the Fed survey
said. ``Only Dallas, St. Louis, and Kansas City report generally
sluggish business conditions and cite persistent weakness in many
sectors.''
   The survey of economic conditions, known as the Tan Book, said
that wage increases continued to be moderate even though labor
markets around many part of the country are tight.
   ``Capacity pressures, and consequently price pressures, have
reportedly eased slightly in several industries, including paper,
chemical, steel and textiles,'' the survey found.
   The survey said that while retail sales have been slow there was
optimism in many cities for a pickup in sales during the holiday
shopping season.
</TEXT>
