<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Prince-Drugs     11-30 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prince-Drugs,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Prince Was Investigated for Cocaine Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A German prince who killed himself
after his wife died of a drug overdose was investigated for a
cocaine deal also involving deceased film director Rainer Werner
Fassbinder, a newspaper said Wednesday.
   Bild, a mass-circulation Hamburg paper, also said officials in
Hanover called off another drug-related investigation of 33-year-old
Prince Ludwig Rudolf of Hanover last week for lack of evidence.
   Ludwig, great-grandson of Germany's last emperor, Kaiser Wilhelm
II, was found dead Sunday in Austria with his hunting rifle at his
side.
   Austrian police said he killed himself after finding his wife,
Princess Isabelle, 26, dead of a cocaine overdose earlier in the day
in their bedroom at the luxurious Koenigin-Villa at Gmunden, 90
miles northeast of Salzburg.
   Bild said the couple ``appear to have had a long drug career
behind them.''
   The daily said Hanover officials last week called off for lack of
evidence an investigation that the jet-set prince had purchased
drugs.
   It said Munich officials also investigated the prince in 1981 for
a cocaine deal said to have involved Fassbinder, the West German
movie director who died in Munich in 1982 of a cocaine and sleeping
pill overdose at age of 36.
   ``He (Prince Ludwig) was suspected of buying 33 grams (slightly
more than one ounce) of `coke' for 6,725 marks (just under
$3,900),'' said the newspaper.
   It said authorities suspected Fassbinder of buying cocaine in the
same deal, but the investigation was dropped because of insufficient
evidence.
   Heinz Stocker, head of the Munich prosecutor's office, and
officials at the Hanover prosecutor's office could not be reached
for comment on the Bild report. A woman at Stocker's office, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said he was not in town.
   Bild quoted Johann Haberl, the Austrian doctor who performed
autopsies on the prince and princess, as saying: ``There were about
a dozen puncture marks in the princess' arm and they had not healed.
Some of them are probably no more than a week old.''
   Prosecutors in Austria said investigators found punctures on the
arms of the prince as well.
   Austrian police say the case is under court investigation, but
refused to give details.
   Bild said Ludwig and some musician friends tried to revive his
wife for about an hour through mouth-to-mouth resuscitation and
heart massage, to no avail. Ludwig then went to a wooded area and
shot himself, it reported.
   Ludwig and his wife moved in the world of rock music and fashion
and both lived for years in England.
   The prince was a distant relative of Queen Elizabeth II of
Britain and Bild said Elizabeth plans to send a representative to
the couple's funeral on Friday near Gmunden.
</TEXT>
