<DOCNO> AP881130-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1939EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SocialSecurityAppeals     11-30 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Social Security Appeals,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Urge Bush To Block Social Security Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-five senators on Wednesday urged George
Bush to stop the Social Security Administration from restricting the
rights of the elderly and disabled to appeal decisions denying them
benefits.
   In a letter to the president-elect, 34 Democrats and Republican
Dave Durenberger of Minnesota urged Bush to make it clear that
``such a policy will have no place in your administration.'' The
letter was initiated by Sen. Howard Metzenbaum of Ohio.
   Last year the agency received 5.5 million claims for Social
Security, Medicare and welfare benefits, and more than 300,000
appeals from its no-benefit rulings. The government lost more than
half of the cases that were appealed, according to a draft of the
proposal to change the rules on appeals hearings.
   Agency spokesman Philip Gambino has described the proposal as an
attempt to improve efficiency.
   But the senators' letter said the ``astonishingly high'' number
of cases won by people who were denied benefits ``suggests to us
that the Social Security Administration consistently makes
system-wide errors in determining eligibility.''
   ``But instead of correcting its mistakes the Social Security
Administration is trying to make it harder for claimants to appeal
those mistakes,'' said the letter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
