<HEAD>State Legislator, Brother Indicted on Theft Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state representative and former head of
the Kentucky Democratic Party was indicted Wednesday along with his
brother on charges they misused more than $150,000 in state funds.
   State Rep. Jerry Lundergan and his brother, Tom Lundergan, were
charged with unlawful use of influence by a legislator and two
counts of theft. His brother, who is not a legislator, was charged
under the same crime as a conspirator.
   Jerry Lundergan resigned in August as state Democratic Party
chairman during investigations into his catering company.
   Most of the Franklin County grand jury indictment centers on a
state contract payment of more than $153,000 to a competing catering
company. The check allegedly was deposited in the bank account of
the Lundergan family's company, Lundy's Catering.
   The Lundergans are accused of using the name of a different
company _ Perfection Catering _ to hide the involvement of Lundy's
Catering in the no-bid contract.
   ``All I can tell you is, that my wife and I feel like human
footballs, and we're a strong family and we'll see this thing out to
the end,'' Jerry Lundergan said. ``I just hope this doesn't happen
to anybody else who has ever served in the General Assembly because
it's a frightening experience.''
   If convicted, Jerry Lundergan faces forfeiture of office on the
unlawful influence charge. Each of the theft counts carries maximum
penalties of five years in prison and a fine of $10,000.
   No court dates were set.
