<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WVaPrison     11-30 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WVa Prison,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Court Orders Prison Closed in Four Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court on Wednesday
ordered the 122-year-old state penitentiary in northern West Viginia
closed in less than four years, and warned it may order the release
of all prisoners there if the state does not comply.
   Calling conditions at the West Virginia Penitentiary deplorable,
the court said releasing the prisoners ``may be the only remaining
alternative'' if a new prison is not built by July 1992.
   In a unanimous opinion written by Justice William Brotherton, the
court did not order construction of a new maximum-security prison
but recommended that the state Building Commission refrain from
buying or leasing any new buildings so the state can afford to
construct a replacement by the July 1, 1992, shutdown date.
   Gov.-elect Gaston Caperton, who enters office Jan. 16, declined
comment.
   William Whyte, executive assistant to state Corrections
Commissioner A.V. Dodrill, said the decision ``puts state government
on notice. ... They've given us sufficient time to get started on a
replacement.''
   Prisoners at the penitentiary in Moundsville just south of
Wheeling have complained of raw sewage, rats and unbearable heat and
cold in their cells. On New Year's Day 1986, prisoners rioted and
took 16 prison employees hostage, killing three fellow inmates
before releasing the hostages two days later.
   Then-Circuit Judge Arthur Recht ruled in 1981 that conditions at
the aging prison in Moundsville just south of Wheeling were
unconstitutional, and the state has done little to improve the
prison despite repeated court orders, the high court said Wednesday.
   ``If possible, the conditions have deteriorated even more,''
Wednesday's court order said.
   The court scheduled a hearing May 2 for state officials to give
their reasons why the justices should not place the prison in
receivership, give the receiver power to build a new prison, and
order the state Building Commission to finance the project.
</TEXT>
