<DOCNO> AP881130-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1952EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StormSewers     11-30 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Storm Sewers,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New EPA Rules Require Permits for Industrial, City Storm Sewers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency on
Wednesday unveiled draft regulations aimed at bringing storm-water
runoff under control, something that will require thousands of
industrial plants and scores of cities to apply for permits to
operate storm sewer systems.
   The regulations will not apply to the combined sanitary-storm
sewers commonly found in older Eastern cities, nor to plants whose
storm sewers discharge into a municipally owned system.
   The draft would exempt systems run by counties or other
non-municipal bodies. The exemption was called illegal by the
Natural Resources Defense Council.
   Stormwater runoff can be a major source of stream pollution in
urban areas, picking up oil from service station pavements, dirt
from construction sites, pesticides and fertilizers from lawns and
gardens, contamination leaking out of landfills and other forms of
pollution. Twenty-one states have reported construction site runoff
as a major source of pollution.
   EPA's draft regulations, ordered by 1987 legislation and
published for 90 days of public comment, require the nation's 170
cities of more than 100,000 people to get permits for their storm
sewer outflows. Officials said they did not know how many might not
qualify because the storm and sanitary sewers are combined.
   In addition, some 25,000 industrial facilities might have to
apply for permits, said James Elder, director of EPA's Office of
Water Enforcement and Permits. He said 75,000 to 100,000 probably
are connected to municipal systems, and these, though not needing
permits, will be required to inform the municipalities how they are
handling storm runoff.
   Cities below 100,000 population will not be brought under
regulation until after 1992, Elder said. Cities larger than 250,000
will have two years after publication of final regulations to
complete their permit applications; cities between 100,000 and
250,000 will have until February 1992.
   Final regulations might not be published until next February,
which would be a year after the congressional deadline, Elder said.
   Smaller cities, as in suburbs, with storm sewer systems that
connect with those of larger cities may be required to get permits
at the discretion of the regional EPA director or state authorities
in the 38 states with authority to run their own water pollution
control programs.
   The agency intends to avoid numerical concentration standards,
relying on requirements for good management of runoff.
Municipalities are being asked to almost write their own permits in
their applications, Elder said.
   The agency will require discovery and elimination of ``illicit
connections'' where sanitary sewers have been connected to storm
sewers.
   Plants required to get permits are those with not necessarily a
complete storm sewer system, but just ``any point source used for
collecting and conveying'' runoff.
   The agency will encourage general permits for construction
companies that would not be tied to specific sites, and will try to
grant group permits to plants that can show they are similar, he
said.
   The agency asked for specific comment on its plans to ignore
county-run systems for the moment, an exemption that Bruce Bowen, an
aide to EPA Administrator Lee M. Thomas, said was made ``in the
interests of administrative feasibility. We want to make sure we
don't bite off more than we can chew.''
   Bob Adler, a lawyer for the Natural Resources Defense Council,
said 410 counties were large enough to be covered by the rule, and
their inclusion would mean storm sewers serving 66 percent of the
population would be covered instead of just 25 percent.
   Adler said the omission of counties was ``deliberately flouting
Congress' instructions,'' and the omission of specific control or
treatment requirements meant ``an institutionalization of the
fox-in-the-henhouse approach to pollution control.''
   But he said the plan was ``not all bad,'' and applauded EPA's
emphasis on the elimination of illicit connections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1954EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LaRouche 1stLd-Writethru a0675 11-30 0831</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Aide Suggests Kissinger To Blame For Group's Woes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 14th graf pvs, bgng: ``Welsh said...''
to add details; picks up 15th graf pvs, bgng: ``LaRouche was...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asscoiated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A financial officer for political
extremist Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr. testified Wednesday he wrote
LaRouche in 1984 that he suspected that former Secretary of State
Henry Kissinger was responsible for some of the movement's money
problems.
   Richard Welsh told LaRouche's conspiracy trial that he suspected
Kissinger's involvement after obtaining a copy of a letter Kissinger
wrote to the FBI soliciting advice about his own security from the
LaRouche organization.
   LaRouche and six co-defendants contend that government harassment
impeded their fund-raising capabilities and is at the root of a
failure to pay back the bulk of more than $30 million in loans to
LaRouche organizations.
   LaRouche and the six associates are charged with conspiring to
defraud those who lent the movement money by devising a scheme to
avoid repayment.
   The Kissinger letter to the FBI was obtained by the LaRouche
movement under the Freedom of Information Act, and admitted into
evidence at the U.S. District Court trial. Dated Aug. 19, 1982, and
addressed to former FBI Director William Webster, Kissinger wrote:
   ``I appreciated your letter forwarding the flier which has been
circulated by Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr.
   ``Because these people have been getting increasingly obnoxious,
I have taken the liberty of asking my lawyer, Bill Rogers, to get in
touch with you to ask your advice, especially with respect to
security.''
   Welsh testified that he sent a memo to LaRouche in October, 1984,
in the midst of LaRouche's second of three presidential campaigns.
   ``You stated in the memo that Kissinger was behind the actions?''
to hurt the LaRouche organization financially, asked Assistant U.S.
Attorney Kent Robinson.
   ``It was the primary but not the only suggestion I made,'' Welsh
testified.
   Welsh, however, did not specify how he thought that Kissinger,
long a target of verbal assaults by LaRouche, could have created
financial problems for the movement by privately expressing concern
for his security.
   Welsh also testified that a tax lawyer advised him and other
LaRouche staffers to file federal tax returns even though it was not
clear that the law required LaRouche to do so.
   Welsh said he met with the tax lawyer to see whether LaRouche was
obligated to file returns even if he had no income and all his
expenses were paid for by organizations that were part of his
political movement.
   Welsh told the jury he was told that the assistance to LaRouche
should be treated as ``ordinary business expenses'' by the companies
and not as LaRouche's personal income.
   LaRouche alone is charged in the case with conspiring to defraud
the Internal Revenue Service by not declaring the personal and
household expenses he received as income and by not filing federal
income tax returns since 1979.
   Welsh said the tax lawyer ``recommended that a tax return be
filed, not because it was required'' but because LaRouche was ``a
controversial public figure.''
   In an effort to convince the jury that money spent for LaRouche's
security was actually used for his personal expenses, the
prosecution called to the stand Kathy Magraw, a LaRouche financial
staffer who testified under a grant of immunity from prosecution.
   She acknowledged under prosecution questioning that the security
account paid for a $7,000 piano, cufflinks for LaRouche, shoes for
his wife, Helga, clothing, luggage, a $10 haircut for LaRouche and
reimbursement for a purchase of wine.
   Ms. Magraw said the account also paid expenses for guests who
stayed at LaRouche's Leesburg, Va., estate.
   Seeking to rebut the argument that the money was used improperly,
LaRouche attorney William Moffitt attempted to question Ms. Magraw
about security expenses for two Latin American members of LaRouche's
organization whose lives had been threatened by drug dealers.
   However, U.S. District Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr. refused to allow
the defense to delve into the Latin American figures' backgrounds,
thus scuttling efforts to show there were legitimate expenses in the
security account that were not for LaRouche's personal benefit.
   LaRouche was indicted in October on 13 counts of mail fraud,
conspiracy to commit mail fraud and conspiracy to defraud the IRS.
The mail fraud counts stem from promissory notes and letters of
credit sent through the mails by the LaRouche organization.
Conviction on all counts could carry a maximum penalty of 65 years
in prison and fines of $3.25 million for LaRouche.
   The six associates face lesser sentences if convicted of the mail
fraud and conspiracy charges, which cover the years 1983 to 1987.
   In the tax conspiracy count, the federal grand jury charged that
LaRouche failed to declare as income the personal and household
services provided by his organizations.
   On trial with LaRouche are his chief fund-raiser, William Wertz;
his legal adviser, Edward Spannaus; and four fund-raisers: Michael
Billington, Dennis small, Paul Greenberg and Joyce Rubinstein.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1956EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dominican-President     11-30 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican-President,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Dominican Leader Returns To Fight Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President
Salvador Jorge Blanco returned home Wednesday to fight his
conviction on charges of political corruption and was taken to jail
immediately.
   Jorge Blanco arrived with several lawyers who traveled with him
from Atlanta, Ga., where he had undergone treatment for a heart
condition since May 1987.
   Soldiers and special security forces surrounded the international
airport of this Caribbean capital, keeping journalists away from the
former president.
   Jorge Blanco, 60, was tried in absentia and found guilty Sunday
of taking part in a scheme to sell overpriced equipment to the army
and police.
   Two businessmen, Leonel Almonte and Juan Thomas Pena Valentin,
were convicted of selling $35 million worth of equipment during
Jorge Blanco's four-year term, which ended in 1986.
   Jorge Blanco was taken in a helicopter to a the Preventive
Prison, a jail in Santo Domingo's La Fe district for people
appealing convictions. As a cell, Jorge Blanco was given a
comfortable room reserved for the prison warden.
   His lawyers presented a letter signed by Jorge Blanco asking the
judge who ruled against him to begin appeal proceedings as soon as
possible.
   Judge Juan Maria Severino ruled that Jorge Blanco ordered
military chiefs to buy 75 percent of the food, uniforms and vehicles
for police and armed forces from companies owned by Almonte and Pena
Valentin.
   Severino sentenced Jorge Blanco and the two businesssmen to 20
years in prison each and levied fines totaling $17.3 million.
   On Tuesday, Jorge Blanco blamed the verdict on President Juaquin
Balaguer, his political foe.
   ``I want to defend my honor,'' he said. ``My honor is above my
liberty. I never, ever used my influence as president to buy or to
order any purchase fr anyone.''
   Jorge Blanco campaigned for president as a moderate reformer. His
term was marked by bloody riots in April 1984, after his government
raised food prices dramatically as part of an austerity program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1853EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Secrets     11-30 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Secrets,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Critics Attack Bill to Reform British Secrecy Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government presented a bill Wednesday to ease
Britain's secrecy laws, but critics from the opposition, media, and
activist groups said it would leave the nation still the most
secretive of Western democracies.
   The bill, if made law, would decriminalize minor leaks and make
some prosecutions more difficult.
   Critics have said a major flaw in the bill is that it does not
allow officials who leak information about questionable government
conduct, commonly known as whistle-blowers, to argue as a defense
that they acted in the public interest or that the information has
already been published elsewhere.
   The bill also provides no automatic right of access to official
information. Mrs. Thatcher has ruled out a Freedom of Information
Act like that of the United States.
   ``To claim this as a major advance toward ending secrecy in
government is nonsense,'' Maurice Frankel, director of the Campaign
for Freedom of Information, said in an interview.
   ``Britain will remain extremely secretive and much worse off than
the major English-speaking countries with which we compare
ourselves: the United States, Canada, Australia and New Zealand.''
   The opposition Labor Party maintained Wednesday that the proposed
measure will give the Conservative government of Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher increased powers ``to withhold and conceal
information it might find politically embarrassing.''
   The bill, based on much-criticized proposals published last June,
confines secrecy mainly to defense, security and foreign affairs.
   In a change from the June proposals, only leaking or publishing
information about bugging, telephone tapping, and mail interception
by the secret security services would be an automatic offense. In
cases of other unauthorized disclosures by journalists or civil
servants, prosecutors would have to prove these harmed the national
interest.
   But a lifetime gag remains on members of the MI5
counterintelligence agency and MI6 intelligence agency and their
unauthorized memoirs.
   In the most notable recent case, the government lost a three-year
battle this year to ban publication of ``Spycatcher,'' the memoirs
of ex-MI5 agent Peter Wright, who lives in Australia.
   The bill, likely to become law by next summer, will amend a
section of the Official Secrets Act making it a criminal offense to
reveal any official information, however trivial, without
authorization.
   The act, passed hastily in 1911 during a German spy scare, has
bolstered Britain's reputation for secrecy, particularly since Mrs.
Thatcher won power in 1979.
   ``The bill is a notable essay in openness,'' Secretary Douglas
Hurd said in a statement as the measure was proposed Wednesday in
the House of Commons. ``We want to narrow drastically the scope of
official information covered by the law.''
   The draft measure stipulates penalties of up to two years in jail
for people convicted of unauthorized disclosures.
   However, the National Council of Civil Liberties said the lack of
a defense arguing that information was released in the public
interest means journalists could be jailed for ``disclosing
information in order to expose fraud, negligence or unlawful
activities.''
   In 1985, a jury acquitted civil servant Clive Ponting on grounds
that his exposure of a government cover-up surrounding the sinking
of an Argentine cruiser in the 1982 Falkland Islands war was in the
public interest. Critics say Ponting would likely be convicted under
the new bill.
   Michael Corner, spokesman for the Guild of British Newspaper
Editors, said the bill was seriously flawed ``as far as freeing
information is concerned and as far as the press is concerned in
carrying out its proper function.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 2003EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SuicidePact     11-30 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Suicide Pact,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comatose Man Who Sued Judas Priest Rock Group Pronounced Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who sued the heavy-metal rock group Judas
Priest, contending its music drove him to a 1985 suicide attempt,
has died after lapsing into an unexplained coma.
   ``The Judas Priest lawsuit is going forward. We are not daunted
one bit. As a matter of fact, it's more important than ever,''
attorney Timothy Post said Wednesday.
   James Vance, 23, was pronounced dead at 10:48 p.m. Tuesday at
Washoe Medical Center, where he had been in a coma since
Thanksgiving Day, said spokesman David Stipech.
   Vance had been on a life support system since he lapsed into a
coma. He was disconnected from the respirator after he was declared
brain dead.
   Vance and his parents sued Judas Priest and CBS Records, alleging
that subliminal messages in the British group's music caused Vance
and Raymond Belknap, 19, to make a suicide pact after listening to
the ``Stained Class'' album for six hours while smoking marijuana
and drinking beer.
   The two took a shotgun to a church playground in nearby Sparks
two days before Christmas 1985 and shot themselves in the head.
Belknap died instantly and Vance was disfigured after shooting away
part of his face.
   The lawsuit, which was filed by both families, is pending in
Washoe District Court.
   Judge Jerry Whitehead has ordered CBS to produce the 24-track
master tape of the ``Stained Class'' album, but so far the
defendants have found the master for every track but a song called
``Better By You _ Better Than Me.''
   Prosecution attorneys contend that song contains the hidden
message, ``Do it. Do it,'' and claim those words along with other
references to death and suicide pushed the young men into their pact.
   Without evidence of subliminal messages, Whitehead said the case
would not go to trial since music and lyrics are protected by the
First Amendment.
   If subliminal messages do exist within the ``Stained Class''
album, Whitehead said the trial would concentrate on whether such
hidden communication deserves the same First Amendment protection.
   Vance was admitted to the hospital's psychiatric ward Nov. 15 for
treatment of depression and was scheduled to be released last
Thursday, the day he went into a coma.
   An autopsy was pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 2005EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chess 1stLd-Writethru a0701 11-30 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chess, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0701,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Men, Hungarian Women Receive Gold Medals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to SUBS 2 grafs for grafs 4-5 to CLARIFY that
Soviet player is second-ranked and that Ahkmilovskaya's medals are
individual, FIX typos thruout, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALONICA, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet men's chess team and the
Hungarian women's team on Wednesday received their gold medals as
champions of the 28th Chess Olympiad.
   The chief arbiter, Svetazor Gligoric of Yugoslavia, announced
England won the silver medals in the men's competition on a
tie-breaker over the Netherlands, which took the bronze in the
biennial world team championship.
   In addition to their team golds, world champion Garri Kasparov of
the Soviet Union and Judit Polgar of Hungary, the highest ranked
12-year-old in history, each recieved two gold medals for their
brilliant individual results.
   There was laughter from some spectators at the gold medal
ceremony when the Soviet women's team captain, Rima Bilunova, came
forward to collect the two individual silver medals won by Elena
Akhmilovskaya, the second-ranked Soviet player who eloped on
Saturday with John Donaldson of Seattle, captain of the U.S. men's
team. They have flown to Frankfurt, West Germany, en route to the
United States.
   Jeers followed when Bilunova was presented with the silver medal
for Akhmilovskaya's individual performance of eight wins and one
draw.
   Eric Schiller of the American professional chess Assocation,
Pro-Chess, asked the Soviet delegation to pass on Akhmilovkskaya's
individual medal.
   He carried a letter she wrote before her sudden departure, torn
and taped together, giving a U.S. colleague permission to collect
her remaining possessions.
   Vitaly Sevastianov, the president of the Soviet Chess Federation,
said in a message sent via an interpreter that Akhmilovksaya could
only have her medal if she contacted the Soviets directly.
   ``She can call Mrs. Bulinova by phone and ask her personally. She
must do it herself,'' the interpreter said.
   Schiller said he told the Soviet women's captain to ``please take
care of the medal and we will try to arrange for Elena to call.''
   According to chess insiders, the letter had been partially torn
by a member of the Soviet delegation during an altercation earlier
this week with an American who collected Akhmilovskaya's luggage.
   While there has been a degree of sympathy for the Soviets over
the loss of their most successful player at a crucial stage of the
competition, the sentiment appears to have been more than tempered
by a desire among chess fans for a Hungarian victory.
   The loudest ovations from the audience were reserved for Miss
Polgar and the Hungarian team, which also included her two sisters.
   The president of the International Chess Federation, Florencio
Campomanes of the Philippines, said in his closing address, that
``this is the first time in Olympic history that a team of juniors
has won the gold medal.''
   The Hungarian team also featured Miss Polgar's 19-year-old
sister, Zsuzsa, who played on board one, and her 14-year-old sister,
Zsofia. The fourth team member was 19-year-old Ildiko Madl.
   The Soviet men won their competition Tuesday by a crushing
six-point margin with 40{ points out of a possible 56. England and
Netherlands finished with 34{ points.
   The Hungarian women made 33 points out of a possible 42, while
the Soviets dropped a half point behind their rivals in a
nail-biting last round climax to finish on 32{. Yugoslavia took the
bronze.
   In chess, a win always scores a point and a draw a half.
   Kasparov, 25, who won seven games with three draws, took gold
medals for the highest score on board one and the ``best absolute
individual result,'' in the men's competition. Former world champion
Anatoly Karpov was second.
   Judit Polgar amassed an astonishing total of 12 wins and one
draw. She netted gold medals for the best absolute women's
performance and the highest score on board two.
   The Olympiad, held in Greece's second city located 300 miles
north of Athens, featured teams representing 106 nations.
   The 29th Olympiad will be held in 1990 in the Yugoslav city of
Novi Sad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 2007EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LeadersSummit     11-30 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Leaders Summit,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets, Americans To Brainstorm Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 200 leading young Soviets arrive here
Thursday for a week of talks with their U.S. counterparts and for a
taste of football, music and American-style protests.
   The U.S.-U.S.S.R. Emerging Leaders Summit is designed to produce
joint ventures and friendships that will strengthen bonds between
the two superpowers, organizers say.
   ``We've been looking for some of the best emerging leaders in
each of 16 fields,'' said Thomas J. Henry, vice president for
development of the American Center for International Leadership,
which is co-sponsoring the gathering with the Soviet Union's
Committee of Youth Organizations.
   As of Wednesday, 169 Americans and 170 Soviets ages 28 to 40 were
expected, Henry said. The Soviets also were sending about 15
staffers and journalists, he said.
   The delegates will break up into commissions to discuss the arts,
environment, medicine, the military, religion and other topics. They
also will attend part of Saturday's Army-Navy football classic, tour
Independence Hall and attend dinners at the homes of Philadelphians.
   ``The political commissions on both sides are very high-level
now, and all the commissions are composed of people who are likely
to become more important later,'' Henry said. ``It's very possible
that they will be looking at each other across a summit table in the
future.''
   But at least one group is planning to protest the Soviet presence.
   Orysia Hewka, a Ukrainian activist in Philadelphia, said
anti-Soviet picketing is planned outside the hotel where most of the
meetings will occur. She contended the Soviet delegates have been
handpicked and will avoid such topics as religious persecution.
   The Soviet delegation arrived in Chicago on Tuesday for a two-day
visit before flying to Philadelphia. They will go to Washington for
four days after the conference ends Wednesday.
   The American delegates, including congressmen, educators, clergy
and artists, started arriving in Philadelphia on Wednesday.
   This week's meeting of the Supreme Soviet and next week's visit
to the United Nations have forced cancellation of a telecast from
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev. But organizers are hoping
President-elect George Bush or Vice President-elect Dan Quayle will
speak, Henry said.
   A reciprocal summit is planned next year in the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet delegation includes Viktor Mironenko, head of the
Communist Youth League; Natalya Negoda, star of the
critically-acclaimed ``Little Vera,'' the first Soviet film to
contain an explicit sex scene; and Archimandrite Alexi, head of the
Trinity-St. Sergius Church in Zagorsk, one of the oldest Russian
Orthodox monasteries in the Soviet Union.
   The U.S. delegation includes Deborah Steelman, Bush's chief
health policy adviser during the campaign and a contender to be
Health and Human Services secretary; DePauw University President
Robert Bottoms; and Michael Oppenheimer, senior scientist for the
Environmental Defense Fund.
   At the end of the summit, the conferees will issue a document
called ``The Final Appeal,'' which Henry said would be general in
nature.
   The $550,000 tab for the conference will be paid mostly by
foundations and corporations, although the U.S. Information Agency
is contributing $60,000 for general support, Henry said. Volunteers
are contributing another $150,000 in services and meals, he said.
   The American Center for International Leadership is a non-profit,
non-partisan organization based in Columbus, Ind., which has
organized similar but smaller exchanges since 1983. Its alumni
include new Hungarian Premier Miklos Nemeth and Carlos Salinas de
Gortari, who will be sworn in as Mexico's president Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1904EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i UN-PLO 2ndLd-Writethru a0729 11-30 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>UN-PLO, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0729,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assembly Censures U.S. for Refusing Arafat Visa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly on Wednesday censured
the United States by a vote of 151-2 and gave it 24 hours to reverse
itself and grant a visa to PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat so he can
speak here.
   The world body, spurred on by the Arab nations, will ask for an
extraordinary protest session in Geneva in mid-December to hear the
Palestine Liberation Organization leader if the United States
persists in its refusal, as expected.
   A second resolution to this effect is expected to be voted upon
Friday, or early next week. The reconvened session in Geneva would
be held Dec. 12-16.
   The United States and Israel were alone Wednesday in voting
against the resolution.
   Britain abstained, saying the criticism of its U.S. ally was too
harsh. But all other U.S. allies voted against Washington's position.
   The resolution asked Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to
inform the General Assembly on Thursday of the U.S. response. The
United States says it will defy the resolution.
   The vote in the 159-member assembly was conducted in a rare roll
call ballot requested by Jordan, a departure from the standard
electronic voting.
   Absent were Dominica, Grenada, St. Kitts and Nevis, Paraguay and
South Africa.
   The State Department denied a visa to Arafat last Saturday on
grounds he condones and encourages terrorism. Arafat addressed the
world body in 1974.
   Arab diplomats said they will swiftly introduce a new resolution
shifting to Geneva the assembly meeting on the Palestine problem and
the Middle East. Arafat would explain there the recent PLO
declaration of an independent Palestinian state.
   Washington says it does not oppose a move to the Swiss city and
would participate in the debate there. Some diplomats say shifting
the session could set an unfortunate precedent, alienate the United
States and encourage it to deny visas to other U.N. visitors it
considers dangerous or offensive.
   ``I feel very pained to see that the United States is the odd
couple with Israel in the United Nations,'' said Clovis Maksoud,
ambassador of the Arab League, which sponsored the resolution
deploring the U.S. action.
   ``We are hopeful the international outcry against the U.S.
position will jolt the subsequent U.S. administration into a
reassessment of its policies of bias toward Israel.''
   Iraqi Ambassador Ismat Kittani said before the vote that U.S.
failure to change its stand ``will constitute a grievous blow to the
process of peace in the Middle East.''
   He said Secretary of State George P. Shultz now ``has a chance to
rise to the occasion and prevent a grievous wrong, untold injury to
the United Nations and its relations with the host country.''
   But Shultz said earlier Wednesday the United States would not
change its mind.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun, the acting U.N. representative,
told the assembly the U.S. government ``does not agree with the tone
or substance of the resolution and voted against it.''
   ``The denial of a visa to Mr. Arafat is fully consistent with the
Headquarters Agreement between the United States and the United
Nations and this includes our right to protect our national
security,'' Okun said.
   The 1947 U.S.-U.N. Headquarters Agreement requires visas to be
granted to U.N. diplomats and people invited on U.N. business.
   The adopted resolution ``deplores the failure by the host country
to approve granting of the requested entry visa,'' and urges the
United States to reconsider and reverse its decision.
   Arafat want to address the assembly to explain the Nov. 15
declaration of an independent Palestinian state and PLO plans for a
Middle East peace settlement.
   He has said he wants to explain the new position taken by the
Palestine National Council, which acts as the PLO legislature, in
implicitly recognizing Israel by accepting U.N. resolutions on the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
   If the session moves to Geneva, the world body's European
headquarters, it would be the first time the assembly has done so in
protest of an action by the host country. Arab diplomats say they
have the necessary majority to accomplish it.
   The PLO, which has non-voting observer status, has had a U.N.
mission since 1975. The United Nations regards the PLO as the sole
legitimate representative of the Palestinian people and invites it
to speak in debates concerning Palestinians and the Middle East.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1911EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-PLO 2ndLd-Writethru a0729 11-30 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0729,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assembly Censures U.S. for Refusing Arafat Visa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to include cycle designator. New material and
editing throughout, No pickup</NOTE>
