<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Chappell     11-30 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chappell,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Rules Against Chappell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican political newcomer Craig
James sealed his narrow victory over U.S. Rep. Bill Chappell as the
state Supreme Court on Wednesday turned down the congressman's
request to void a county's votes.
   ``We are delighted we had a victory for the people of the 4th
District,'' James said, adding he had 11 lawyers research state law
for the court challenge. ``To attempt to disenfranchise the voters
of the 4th District is tantamount to being un-American.''
   The state's election canvassing commission, consisting of Gov.
Bob Martinez, Secretary of State Jim Smith, both Republicans, and
Commissioner of Agriculture Doyle Connor, a Democrat, certified the
results last week.
   Chappell's lawsuit, however, delayed sending the 4th
Congressional District results to federal election officials.
   The suit seeking to have Flagler County's results invalidated
claimed the county elections supervisor's office missed a seven-day
deadline to file returns with state elections officials.
   The canvassing commission said it would be unjust to disqualify
voters because of a technicality. Chappell released a brief
statement saying he would have more comment after consulting with
his attorneys.
   ``We are disappointed with the court's ruling today, and now
await the court's (written) opinion,'' the statement said. The high
court planned to issue an opinion explaining its ruling.
   Chappell, a 20-year congressman tainted by reports linking him to
the Pentagon procurement scandal, lost to James by 732 votes in a
recount of the Nov. 8 general election.
   Without the 10,907 votes from Flagler County, Chappell would have
won by 288 votes.
   James, a DeLand lawyer, said in a telephone interview from
Washington that he hopes Chappell will concede and help ``with an
easy transition.''
</TEXT>
