<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru a0753 11-30 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0753,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Party Ruling Body Rejects Coalition Talks with Likud</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Likud-Shas agreement, other detail;
EDITS to Trim. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, ISRAEL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Party's ruling body defied its
two principal leaders Wednesday in a narrow decision against
negotiating with the rival, conservative Likud bloc on a possible
coalition government.
   The 61-57 vote in a closed meeting of Labor's executive bureau
went against the wishes of Foreign Minister Shimon Peres and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, a former prime minister, party spokesmen
said. One member abstained.
   Israel radio reported late Wednesday that Likud and the
right-wing Shas party, a small orthodox group, had signed a
coalition agreement giving Shas two Cabinet posts.
   Likud won 40 of the 120 parliament seats in the Nov. 1 election
and Labor got 39. Orthodox religious parties have 18, including six
held by Shas, and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, the Likud leader,
has been holding coalition talks with them.
   In his proposal to Labor, Shamir had offered two of the four most
powerful Cabinet jobs _ defense and either foreign or finance.
   Shamir said in a statement: ``I'm sorry that we have lost an
opportunity to form a broad government as was the wish of the
majority of the people. Within the next few days I will present to
the Knesset (parliament) a government that will serve well the
people and the country.''
   Labor and Likud have been equal partners in a ``national unity''
coalition since the inconclusive election of July 1984. Peres was
prime minister and Shamir foreign minister during the first two
years, then they switched jobs.
   The Labor decision leaves Shamir the task of making coalition
deals with far-right and ultra-Orthodox parties.
   His offer to Labor of a junior coalition partnership came after
talks with fundamentalist parties bogged down over their demands for
Cabinet posts and a ``Who is a Jew'' law under which only
conversions to Judaism by Orthdox rabbis would be accepted.
   American Jews, more often affiliated with the Conservative or
Reform movements, oppose such a law.
   At the Labor meeting, Rabin said ``it is a serious mistake not to
enter negotiations,'' party spokeswoman Michal Cohen said.
   Many in the party contended, however, that Labor would have to
give up its principles to join a Likud government.
   The current coalition was paralyzed on an approach to peace with
the Arabs because of conflicts between the hard-line Likud and
Labor, which took a more dovish approach.
   Peres and Rabin left immediately after the vote but other
Laborites received the results with loud applause, kissing and
hugging each other and shouting: ``We did it, we did it!'' Israel
radio said.
   The radio described the vote as a ``revolutionary situation'' of
a younger opposition voting against the old party leadership of
Peres and Rabin, who ``got their faces slapped.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
