<2ND_LINE>AM-Tornadoes,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families Mourn Victims; Gov. Seeks Disaster Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weeping schoolmates of a 12-year-old tornado
victim attended his funeral Wednesday as his mother, her face badly
bruised, clung to a wooden jewelry box her son made in shop class.
   ``Only Pete would give me a present even after he's dead,'' Patty
Fulghum said of her son, Edwin ``Pete'' Fulghum.
   Pete made the box in shop class and signed his name inside,
intending it to be a Christmas present for his mother. A friend
brought it to her.
   Hundreds of relatives and friends mourned the death of the boy,
one of four people killed when tornadoes struck along a 200-mile
stretch of eastern North Carolina Monday. One hundred fifty-seven
people were injured and 850 left homeless. Damage was estimated at
$100 million.
   A funeral for Janet Barnes, 9, of Raleigh, was scheduled for
Wednesday afternoon. Also killed were Lee Roy and Mary Alston of
Nash County, who will be buried Sunday afternoon.
   Also Wednesday, Gov. Jim Martin requested $9.3 million in federal
disaster assistance in a letter to President Reagan that state
officials planned to hand-deliver to the White House.
   The letter asks Reagan for a disaster area declaration that would
make victims eligible for assistance from the Federal Emergency
Management Agency.
   ``We feel confident that the final determination will be
positive,'' said Joe Dean, Secretary of the state Department of
Crime Control and Public Safety. He said he hoped FEMA would rule on
the application within two days.
   ``What we will do ... hopefully within four days, is set up
disaster assistance centers'' in the affected counties, Dean said.
``Then we will discuss with (tornado victims) what kind of
assistance they can and cannot get.''
   If the application is approved, individuals and families could
receive grants of up to $10,000 per household, loans and housing for
up to 18 months.
</TEXT>
