<HEAD>13-Year-Old Cleared of Murdering Girl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury acquitted a 13-year-old girl
Wednesday of murdering another girl after the defendant said she was
elsewhere at the time engaging in sex, drinking and drugs with
teen-age friends.
   The jury at Northampton Crown Court deliberated for more than
seven hours before finding the teen-ager innocent of murder and
manslaughter. Under British law, minors involved in legal cases
cannot be identified.
   Carol Baldwin, 13, died after she was stabbed in the back as she
walked to a friend's house across a park on the evening of March 26
in this northern English community.
   The prosecution claimed the defendant murdered Miss Baldwin, whom
she did not know, because the victim called her a name.
   But the defendant testified she was frightened into wrongly
telling police she committed the murder.
   The accused girl, who was 12 at the time of the killing, said
that while the murder was being committed, she was engaging in sex,
drinking and aerosol-sniffing with older teen-age friends.
