<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NightStalker 1stLd-Writethru a0643 11-30 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Night Stalker, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0643,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Phase of Jury Selection Nears End in Night Stalker Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 1st to UPDATE with attorneys finishing
questioning; picks up 3rd graf pvs: `Testimony about ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of the so-called ``Night Stalker''
defendant officially began four months ago, but not a single juror
has been seated as the notorious case stretches into its fourth year.
   Attorneys in the Richard Ramirez case finished asking questions
Wednesday in the second of three phases of jury selection _ an
intensive inquiry into the views of prospective jurors about the
death penalty.
   ``I believe that does it,'' said Superior Court Judge Michael
Tynan as he concluded an interview of the last prospective juror to
be quizzed.
   During Wednesday's session, one woman was excused after she said
the case was giving her nightmares and threatening her health.
   Another woman was allowed to remain although she said she had
consulted with her minister on the troubling question of whether she
could vote for the death penalty if necessary. She said she decided
she could.
   The judge recessed the trial until Dec. 12 when the third phase
of jury questioning begins.
   Testimony about the killings that spread fear throughout Los
Angeles in the summer of 1985 is still months away.
   In Los Angeles and across the country, witnesses wait for a call
from Deputy District Attorney P. Philip Halpin telling them it is
time to recount their ghastly tales of horror.
   Many of their accounts were first told two years ago at a
preliminary hearing for Ramirez, 28, who is from El Paso, Texas. A
judge who heard that testimony about rape, murder and, in one case,
the gouging out of a victim's eyes, ordered Ramirez to stand trial.
   Ramirez, who is said to have dabbled in Satanism and once
shouted, ``Hail Satan!'' in court, faces 13 counts of murder in the
string of nighttime attacks. He also is charged with 30 other
felonies including rape, robbery and attempted murder.
   The shaggy-haired drifter, linked to the crimes through items
stolen from victims' homes, was captured and beaten by angry
residents of an East Los Angeles neighborhood as he tried to steal a
car on Aug. 31, 1985.
   If jurors convict him of even one murder and special circumstance
allegation, they must then decide whether to impose the death
penalty or sentence him to life in prison without parole.
   In spite of the painstaking jury selection, Ramirez' lawyer,
Daniel Hernandez, insists publicity has made it impossible for his
client to receive a fair trial.
   ``We've seen some very fine people come through here,'' Hernandez
said. ``These jurors have made a commitment to be as fair and
impartial as they can be. But it's an impossible position to put
them in.''
   He said many prospective jurors lived in fear when the Night
Stalker crimes were going on.
   ``Because of the (publicity) saturation and the fear and terror
they would be unable to be fair,'' he said.
   Halpin disagrees.
   ``We have been in a process of jury selection since July 21,
1988, and that process has validated our belief that Los Angeles
with its large and diverse population does afford the defendant a
forum in which he can get a fair trial,'' said Halpin.
   So far, more than 1,500 people have been summoned to the
courtroom of Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan. Hundreds were
excused because they could not afford to spend an estimated two
years in court. More were dismissed because they believed Ramirez
was guilty of the ``Night Stalker'' slayings.
   In the latest phase, about 150 prospects were turned away because
of unalterable views for or against the death penalty.
   On Dec. 12, some 145 jury finalists will return for further
questioning on more general subjects. From that pool, 12 jurors and
12 alternates will be chosen. Tynan hopes to seat a jury by
mid-January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
