<1ST_LINE>u i AM-CaveDweller 2ndLd-Writethru a0628 11-30 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cave Dweller, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0628,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Scientist Spends 111 Days in Dark Cave</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs to include age.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scientist who lived for 111 days in an underground
cave emerged from her near-total isolation Tuesday and said she had
become attached to her damp surroundings and even had talked to the
stalactites.
   ``At last! Smells, vegetation and brouhaha!'' Veronique Le Guen,
32, said excitedly when she walked from a cave in l'Aven du
Valat-Negre, in the Aveyron region of southern France to end the
experiment into how isolation affects the body.
   Photographers, television crews and relatives were on hand to
greet Mrs. Le Guen, who had been cut off from the outside world
since Aug. 10 in her campsite 275 feet underground, where the eerie
silence was broken only by the sounds of dripping water and the
beating of her heart.
   Pale and wearing special sunglasses, she had to be helped to a
waiting car that took her to a hospital for medical tests.
   ``Before surfacing, I talked to the cave, I listened for the last
time to the sounds of the water dripping off the stalactites,'' she
said. ``Mixed with the joy of being reunited with my family was a
poignant sadness at leaving this cave which I'd become attached to
after all.''
   The purpose of the experiment was to see how the human body
responds when it is deprived of light and cut off from the natural
cycles of day and night.
   Mrs. Le Guen was wired with electrodes that sent signals to
scientists above ground indicating her sleep cycles and following
the temperature curve of each breast. The data will help medical
researchers in Strasbourg studying tumor detection based on changing
breast temperatures.
   She also collected urine and saliva samples that charted her
body's chemical reactions to caffeine.
   Mrs. Le Guen's only contact with the outside world was through
telephone calls from project head Michel Siffre. But she said they
hurt more than they helped.
   ``The calls put into my ears the sounds of people living without
me, in the free air. I missed that and felt bad about it,'' she said.
   Mrs. Le Guen lived in a large tent equipped with electricity,
three freezers and a stove on which she cooked all her meals. Her
diet was normal _ only chocolate and alchohol were forbidden because
they interfered with her metabolization of caffeine.
   The tent was at the back of a long passage way leading to the
cave's entrance, giving her about 100 yards in which she could
exercise.
   Although she had neither watch nor clock, she said she had the
feeling that time was passing quickly. She thought she had been in
the cave for only 42 days and nights, not 111.
   Christian Vasseur, a computer scientist analyzing data from the
project, said Mrs. Le Guen had ``days'' that lasted 40 hours,
followed by 38 hours of uninterrupted sleep.
   ``In the beginning, I thought I would spend most of my time
thinking about metaphysical questions,'' Mrs. Le Guen said. ``But
when you're alone down there you only think about taking care of
yourself. I cooked, I washed dishes, I read and I wrote a lot.''
   Her fondest memory, she said, was reading Gabriel Garcia
Marquez's ``One Hundred Years of Solitude,'' while the hardest part
of her daily routine was tending to scientific matters.
   ``At the end I couldn't stand it not to be able to urinate in
peace, to have to prick my fingers to take blood samples, to spit
and collect my saliva, to hook up the electrodes before sleeping,
and _ I'll skip the details, much worse,'' she said.
   President Francois Mitterrand sent a telegram congratulating Mrs.
Le Guen for completing a ``great scientific adventure'' and for her
``remarkable personal commitment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
