<HEAD>Light Snow In The Northern Tier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Light snow fell on the nation's northern midsection on Wednesday,
scattered showers fell on northwestern New York state, and high wind
warnings were posted for the Pacific strais of Washington.
   Snowshowers extended over northern portions of Indiana and
Illinois, across michigan, Wisconsin, Minnesota, South Dakota and
Nebraska, turning to scattered showers over northwest New York state.
   Warnings of gale-force winds also were posted for Lake Ontario.
Wind advisories remained in effect in southwest California, where
winds reached 75 mph at Laguna Peak, in the hills above Point Mugu,
Calif.
   Forecasters predicted 1 to 3 inches of snow overnight for
northern and northwest Lower Michigan, with locally heavier amounts
of up to 6 additional inches of snow near the lakes.
   Low temperature for the nation Wednesday morning was 9 degrees
below zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 15
degrees at Ely, International Falls and Warroad, Minn., to 85
degrees at Fort Myers, Fla.
   The national weather forecast for Thursday called for snowshowers
from the upper two thirds of the Appalachians across the lower Great
Lakes and northern Indiana; rain over the Northern Pacific coast,
with strong and gusty winds across the mountains of Wyoming.
   High temperatures will be in the 20s and 30s from northern New
England across the Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley, and the upper
Mississippi Valley; in the 30s and 40s across the central rockies;
the 40s and 50s from southern New England across the Carolinas,
Tennessee Valley, inland central Gulf of Mexico states, lower
Mississippi Valley, and From the Dakotas across Oklahoma and western
Texas, and the remainder of the Rockies; in the 70s for southern
Florida; the 70s and low 80s from the desert Southwest across the
southern coast of California, and generally in the 60s over the
remainder of the nation.
