<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NukeOutage     11-30 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuke Outage,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unusual Event Declared At Vermont Yankee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRATTLEBORO, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusual event was declared Wednesday
at the Vermont Yankee nuclear power plant when a valve motor failed
in the reactor core cooling spray system, a utility spokesman said.
   The unusual event, the least severe of four nuclear emergency
levels, ``does not denote an emergency and doesn't indicate an
impact on the safety of plant personnel or the general public,''
plant spokesman Gordon Bristol said.
   The unusual event was declared at 5:30 p.m., and repairs to the
valve motor continued more than two hours later. Bristol said the
reactor would be shut down within 24 hours if the motor cannot be
fixed.
   He said Vermont Yankee notified the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
and officials in Vermont and New Hampshire, part of which lies
within the plant's 10-mile emergency-planning zone.
   Bristol said the plant experienced a similar problem with a core
spray valve motor several months ago.
   Earlier Wednesday, plant spokesman Harry McBrien said the reactor
had begun cutting power by one-quarter of 1 percent per day in
anticipation of a Feb. 11 shutdown.
