<HEAD>Police Say Manet Work is Recovered</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with painting recovered after tearful
thief calls police, details</NOTE>
<DATELINE>YAPHANK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Impressionist painting worth more than $1
million that was stolen from a museum was recovered Wednesday in New
York City when a tearful thief called police, authorities said.
   The bandit, however, described as ``remorseful, crying and
upset,'' was not regretful enough to turn himself in, said Suffolk
County Police Detective Sgt. Gene Gross, who took two calls from the
man.
   The man called police at 8:45 a.m. to tell them they should find
a claim adjuster because he had information about the painting,
Edouard Manet's ``Bouquet of Peonies,'' which was stolen Sunday from
the Heckscher Museum in Huntington.
   He called back at 9:30 a.m. and told police the painting was at
an apartment complex in the borough of Queens, Gross said.
   Suffolk County Police Commissioner Daniel Guido said the thief
told police the painting could be found in the basement laundry room
but it was not there when police arrived shortly before noon.
   He said Benjamin Pagan, the building superintendent, had found
it, thought about hanging it in his apartment, but decided to put in
it a storage room because he didn't think it was attractive.
   Heckscher museum Registrar William Titus said Wednesday the
painting was authentic and undamaged.
   Investigators said the painting was taken from the wall of the
museum probably as patrons in the room watched a videotape about
another exhibit. Two uniformed guards were patrolling the five-room
exhibition area at the time, Kiley said.
   The 1880 Manet painting is a still life of red and pink flowers
in a glass vase. It had been lent to the Heckscher by its anonymous
owner.
   The full estimated value of the painting was not made public, but
police and museum officials said it was more than $1 million.
   The painting, in its frame, measures about 16{ by 21{ inches and
could have fit under a coat, Kiley said Monday.
