<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 3rdLd-Writethru a0750 11-30 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0750,0778</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa, Miodowicz Hold Unprecedented TV Debate on Unions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-3 YPDATE with debate live, uncensored. Picks up
3rd graf pvs, Jubilant Solidarity ... editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa urged the government Wednesday
night in an unprecedented TV debate with the head of Poland's
official unions to legalize Solidarity, the banned labor federation
he helped found in 1980.
   The debate after the evening news represented the first time in
five years that Walesa, the 1983 Nobel Peace laureate, had a chance
to defend Solidarity on state-controlled television and was his most
extensive TV appearance ever.
   The exchange was televised live and uncensored. A clock was even
placed in the background of the set to demonstrate that no deletions
were made.
   Jubilant Solidarity advisers declared victory afterward. Hundreds
of spectators who crowded around television sets at Warsaw's Central
Station also seemed to score it a win for Walesa.
   ``We have to agree for Poland. Poland needs agreement,'' Walesa
told Alfred Miodowicz during the 43-minute debate.
   Referring to Miodowicz's membership in the ruling Politburo,
Walesa said serious talks between the opposition and government
could begin when officials acknowledge Solidarity's right to exist.
   Soldarity, the first free union movement in the Soviet bloc, was
founded legally during a turbulent summer of strikes in 1980, but
was suppressed and outlawed after martial law was declared in
December 1981.
   ``If you can make a man's decision that there is a place for
Solidarity, we will immediately roll up our sleeves and we will
begin working hard for Poland, because time is running out,'' Walesa
told Miodowicz.
   Grzegorz Streszynski, a young man at the railroad station, missed
his train to western Poland to watch the contest. ``Walesa made
great remarks. I waited seven years to hear them,'' he said.
   Walesa ``stepped on him,'' said Adam Michnik, a senior adviser to
the Solidarity founder.
   ``This is a fantastic day, beautiful, which will be noted in the
history of our country as a great victory for Solidarity,'' said
film director Andrzej Wajda, a Solidarity supporter.
   Walesa said later his performance suffered because he had a
severe case of flu.
   The official news agency PAP was noncommittal: ``In spite of the
fact that the approaches remained divergent, the very fact of the
meeting is a good prognosis for overcoming barriers in reaching .. .
dialogue and national agreement.''
   Dressed in a gray suit, with a Solidarity badge and an image of a
madonna on his lapel, Walesa looked relaxed as he and Miodowicz sat
side by side.
   Miodowicz began the program, urging that there be no divisions
among workers.
   ``Please join us (in the official trade unions.) Join our
democratic elections,'' said Miodowicz, who wore a black shirt and
no tie with a gray suit.
   Walesa said: ``You want me to come on my knees to your union. I
don't want to. I want to be myself.''
   As the debate progressed, Walesa became more animated, gesturing
broadly with his hands. Miodowicz's opening remarks lasted five
minutes longer than Walesa's, but the Solidarity leader did most of
the talking afterward.
   When Miodowicz said authorities were moving step by step to
improve the political and economic situation in Poland, Walesa
agreed but said Poland was taking small steps while the rest of the
world rushed toward progress.
   The debate was proposed by Miodowicz on Nov. 14 and accepted
swiftly by Walesa. A television official had predicted that all of
Poland would come to a halt to see the confrontation.
   In addition to being head of the alliance, created by the
government in 1982 to replace the banned Solidarity, Miodowicz, a
59-year-old former steelworker, is a member of the ruling Politburo
of the Polish United Workers (Communist) Party.
   Until this year, Walesa had been treated as virtually a
non-person by authorities and was not permitted into Polish TV
studios.
   Walesa, 45, has led Solidarity since its creation in 1980 when it
grew into a 10 million-member labor movement, the first independent
union in the East bloc.
   Despite being outlawed under martial law, Solidarity has remained
active, first as an underground organization and more openly since
1986. Union supporters staged two waves of strikes this year and
demanded it be made legal again.
   Walesa and Miodowicz differ fundamentally on trade union issues.
Miodowicz says there can be only one union in one factory.
   Walesa advocates allowing official unions and independent unions
like Solidarity to co-exist in factories, but to negotiate jointly
with management.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
