<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bus-Body     11-30 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus-Body,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Killed; City Bus Drags Him More Than Seven Blocks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was struck and killed by a city bus
Wednesday, and his body was dragged more than seven blocks and
through at least five stops without the driver or passengers knowing
it, police said.
   The body of the victim, a man in his 50s, was eventually
discovered in the street by police officers, said Louis Cella of the
police Major Accident Investigation Section.
   ``The bus driver and the 30 to 35 people on board the bus were
totally unaware of what had happened,'' Cella said. ``Nobody felt
anything and nobody saw anything.''
   Cella said the innermost tire on the right rear wheel struck the
man's head and his body was caught on the suspension.
   Two city transit employees traveling behind the bus saw something
drop from the undercarriage but didn't realize it was a body, said
Chicago Transit Authority spokesman Jeff Stern.
   Police were withholding the man's identification until family
members could be notified.
   Cella said police were convinced that the bus driver did not know
an accident had occurred and no charges were filed against him.
