<DOCNO> AP881130-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 2245EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     11-30 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Revival of Lanford Wilson's `The Rimers of Eldritch' Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a tiny Midwestern hamlet called Eldritch,
population 70, the people can be friendly, caring and close-knit.
They also can be gossipy, insular, unforgiving and downright
murderous.
   Lanford Wilson examines a dozen or so of the town's residents in
``The Rimers of Eldritch,'' which was revived Wednesday by
off-Broadway's Second Stage. The play still tantalizes, but this
production doesn't. It's a fluid but emotionally barren revival that
doesn't capture the power of Wilson's dark story or his poetic,
almost lyrical sense of everyday language.
   ``The Rimers of Eldritch'' is early Wilson, a large, messy play
that was first performed off-off-Broadway at LaMama in 1966. The
evening is an unsentimental mosaic of rural life. But nothing is
straightforward. Scenes bleed into each other. Conversations overlap
and sometimes are repeated. Action occurs in a time frame that skips
from spring to summer to fall and back again.
   Ultimately, pieces of the story fit together, building toward a
climax that has been hinted at from the beginning of the play. Until
then, the audience has to absorb a remarkable number of characters
and incidents.
   The opening sequence is promising. Two old biddies, played with
hilarious righteousness by Georgia Creighton and Mary Jay, cackle
about the goings-on between the owner of the town cafe and her
amorous hired hand.
   Gradually, the rest of the large cast is introduced.
   There's Patsy Johnson, described by the playwright as ``the
prettiest girl at Centerville High.'' Patsy longs to move to
Centerville, some 20 miles away, but she's trapped in Eldritch, and
can only leave on a school bus.
   Her speeches of longing, particularly when recited by an actress
as sympathetic as Jennie Moreau, are among the production's few
affecting moments.
   There's also a parade of eccentric characters who seem, in this
revival at least, to reside in Dogpatch rather than Eldritch. They
include Skelly, the town hermit; the emotionally unstable Nelly
Windrod and her senile mother Mary; the ultra-religious Evelyn
Jackson and her crippled daughter Eva, and a strange young man named
Robert Conklin who is amorously pursued by Eva.
   The plot involves a murder and a subsequent trial. Neither is
presented chronologically, and information about both is revealed
between slices of Midwest life, often performed at much too high a
pitch.
   Director Mark Brokaw hasn't gotten much out of his actors besides
an ability to scamper up and down designer Santo Loquasto's mountain
of rough-hewn boards. In addition to Miss Moreau, only Adam Storke
as the troubled Robert evokes much sympathy or interest. Even
Jennifer Tipton's lighting seems unrealized, more murky than
revealing.
   As an examination of small-time people in a small-town,
oppressive atmosphere, ``The Rimers of Eldritch'' remains
intriguing. It's just hard to see what makes them tick in this
leaden production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 2252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CatholicComa     11-30 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Catholic Coma,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comatose Woman Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Glenn is CQ</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marcia Gray, a comatose woman kept
alive near three years by a feeding tube while her family
successfully fought to stop feeding her, died Wednesday after
surviving two weeks without nourishment.
   Mrs. Gray, 49, died at 8:18 p.m. at South County Hospital in
South Kingstown, said Philip Tracy, the hospital's senior vice
president.
   ``Death was attributed to kidney failure and respiratory
arrest,'' he said. ``Most of the family were with her,'' including
her husband, H. Glenn Gray, who fought for his wife's right to die.
   ``Her family was all with her and Glenn was able to hold her. It
was a very quiet, peaceful passage,'' said the family's attorney,
Linda MacDonald.
   ``He's taking it pretty hard. He said, `It's an easy passage for
her, but it's not for us.' He's not going to be talking to anybody
for a while, probably for at least a week,'' Ms. MacDonald said.
   Along with Gray, 47, were Mrs. Gray's 23-year-old son,
21-year-old daughter and about eight other relatives and in-laws,
Ms. MacDonald said.
   Her death was the final chapter in her family's controversial
appeal to a federal judge and a Roman Catholic theologian that Mrs.
Gray did not want her life prolonged artificially.
   Mrs. Gray suffered a burst blood vessel in her brain on Jan. 4,
1986. She has been in what doctors called ``a persistent vegetative
state'' since then, confined mostly at the state General Hospital.
   Gray and other family members contended throughout the
controversy that Mrs. Gray told them before she was stricken that
she did not want to be kept alive by artificial means.
   State officials refused to remove her feeding tube, arguing it
was morally wrong that she endure a cruel and painful death by
starvation.
   The Gray family then sued the state in an attempt to force
officials to let Mrs. Gray die. U.S. District Judge Francis J. Boyle
on Oct. 17 sided with the family and ordered the state to remove the
feeding tube or find another hospital that would by Nov. 16.
   Bishop Louis E. Gelineau of the Providence Roman Catholic
Diocese, drew national attention last year when he approved a
theologian's opinion that it was morally permissible to withhold
nutrition from Mrs. Gray.
   After the federal decision, Thomas Romeo, state director of the
Department of Mental Health, Retardation and Hospitals, still
expressed reluctance in removing Mrs. Gray's nutrition. He wrote to
more than 270 hospitals in Rhode Island, Massachusetts and
Connecticut, asking them to accept Mrs. Gray.
   She was transfered to South County Hospital on Nov. 16. Dr.
Robert Conrad, who has worked at South County for 23 years, removed
the tube. He said at the time that he was concerned Mrs. Gray was
being kept alive against her wishes.
   Tracy said Mrs. Gray's death was expected.
   ``Right from day one she's been deteriorating, but the past few
days, more so,'' he said. ``There's not much more you can say. It's
done and other with.''
   He said there were no attempts to resuscitate Mrs. Gray on
Conrad's orders.
   The family began a bedside vigil Monday after several instances
when Mrs. Gray's blood pressure dropped sharply and her heart began
beating irregularly, Ms. MacDonald said.
   ``She kept rallying. This morning they thought she was going and
she held on for another 12 hours,'' the lawyer said. ``Every one of
her organs was beginning to shut down, from what the doctors said.''
   Ms. MacDonald said that although it has been painful for the
family, Gray ``is proud of the fact that his wife did not die in
vain, that Marcia's death, as unprivate as it was, opened the path
for other families not to go through the same thing.''
   At one point in the state's attempts to find a health care
facility tht would take Mrs. Gray, Romeo sought the advice of U.S.
Surgeon General C. Everett Koop.
   Koop, who had said that although he didn't endorse the removal of
patients' feeding tubes in general, the Gray family's request was
acceptable because Mrs. Gray had previously asked to be allowed to
die.
</TEXT>
