<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 2338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SRP-Leaks     11-30 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SRP-Leaks,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Faulty Seals And Gaskets Cause Plutonium Leaks At SRP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaky seals and gaskets caused a series of
plutonium leaks at the government's Savannah River Plant in Aiken
County, S.C., and more leaks could occur before the problem is
fixed, scientists said Wednesday.
   Three separate unplanned releases of plutonium have occurred at
the nuclear weapons material production plant in the past six weeks
_ the most recent on Nov. 22. Fifteen workers have picked up minute
quantities of the radioactive material on the soles of their shoes
as a result of the leaks.
   John Porter, a technical superintendent at the plant near
Augusta, Ga., told The Atlanta Constitution Wednesday the source of
the releases appears to be a contaminated filter room at a
laboratory near SRP's plutonium refining facility.
   Over a period of years, plutonium had built up in the room as
filters designed to trap radioactivity were replaced. Some of the
accumulated plutonium then was sucked accidentally out of the lab's
exhaust air stack without passing through filters.
   The accidental releases occurred because several seals and
gaskets that should have been airtight were not, Porter said.
   Since the first leak was discovered in late October _ after six
workers had gone home with plutonium on their shoes _ air flow
through the laboratory has been restricted and gaskets in the filter
room have been replaced.
   As a result, Porter said the chances of more releases occurring
have been reduced but not eliminated. ``It's unlikely that more will
be released, but it's not impossible,'' Porter said.
   One microcurie of plutonium has been found outside of a plutonium
refining facility, according to SRP officials. If all of that had
been swallowed by a single person, that person would receive only
about one-third of the radiation dose permitted by federal
regulations.
   However, Bill Reinig, SRP health physics superintendent,
acknowledged that some plutonium could have escaped from the plant
without being measured.
   None of the three reactors at SRP are operating. They have been
shut down because of safety and other concerns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
