<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-BehindtheWheel ADV10-11   11-30 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Behind the Wheel, ADV10-11,0776</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 10-11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hyundai Excel Is Car of Contrasts</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hyundai Excel is a car of contrasts. Its base price of $5,499
attracts budget-minded consumers, yet sales figures show the average
buyer winds up with an Excel model averaging at least $8,300.
   Auto critics have panned the little South Korean-built Excel
since its debut in February 1986, yet Americans flocked to the
showrooms and made Hyundai the fourth-biggest importer in its first
year.
   Despite the lower profit margins offered to car dealers from
Hyundai compared with other automakers, the company reports about
one out of every three U.S. dealers have applied for a Hyundai
dealership.
   That's not bad for a car whose name many folks can't pronounce
(it rhymes with Sunday and means ``modern'' in Korean).
   Hyundai officials say they merely found a market niche _ the low
end of the small car market that had been nearly abandoned by the
domestics. Even the Japanese have departed the niche over the last
few years as carmakers moved upscale.
   Buyers get more bang for the buck with our car, more value, a
Hyundai spokeswoman said when asked what sets Hyundai apart from
other subcompacts.
   She said sales rose from 168,882 in the introductory year of 1986
to 263,610 in 1987. Sales in the first 10 months of this year
totaled 225,198 vs. 226,191 in the same period in 1987. The
spokeswoman attributed the slight decline to a strike earlier this
year in South Korea that curtailed production. She said the company
has not projected 1989 sales.
   The average Excel buyer is between 25 and 35 with average income
from $25,000 to $35,000 a year, Hyundai said. Fifty-two percent are
females, and 32 percent are college graduates. A majority have some
college education.
   The test car was a front-drive GLS sedan with a base price of
$7,749 plus $1,300 for options, way above the base Excel at $5,499.
   The Excel GLS had a good set of standard features, such as
tachometer, full cloth seats and a driver seat with height and
lumbar adjustment. These items are not part of the base Excel
package, however.
   The GLS also had a spongy suspension and substantial road noise.
Unfortunately, they are part of the base Excel. And both models have
the underpowered, 1.5-liter four-cylinder, carbureted engine that
has been criticized by auto test drivers.
   I had to agree with them. I found that passing other vehicles _
even on the highway _ took some doing because the Excel's
powerplant, capable of 68 horsepower at 5,500 rpm, just labored. I
put the accelerator to the floor and got no immediate response.
   The engine was teamed with a five-speed manual overdrive
transmission. A drive in a three-speed automatic Excel proved no
better performance-wise. I also dropped the left two wheels off the
highway onto the paved shoulder and had a time getting the Excel
back onto the road.
   Handling is imprecise. Still, in the city I appreciated the Excel
in difficult parking maneuvers. It was a breeze to squeeze into
small spaces. The Excel's fit and finish was superb inside and out.
   The interior was well done, though the rear seat would be a
nearly impossible fit for three decent-sized adults. Legroom was OK
in back if the front seats were moved all the way up, but there
wasn't be much legroom in back if the front seats were pushed back
all the way.
   The trunk had a nice flat floor, but the carpet wasn't fastened
down in the middle and tended to bunch up under luggage.
   Consumer Reports said the Excel reports of trouble from owners in
its first year here, 1986, were average.
   Overall, the Excel seemed to have the trade-offs expected of a
small car priced as low as $5,499.
   But with the test GLS priced at more than $9,000, I had to wonder
whether this is really a low-priced car for a special market niche.
At $9,000, a buyer could widen his or her scope to the Honda Civic
DX hatchback at around $8,450 or a Ford Escort, which starts around
$7,000. Then, the niche is gone, and perhaps that's the biggest
contrast of all.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, former executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 10-11</NOTE>
