<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   11-30 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0512</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All three earlier bidders for RJR Nabisco Inc.
say they submitted new proposals by the company-decreed deadline for
revised bids in the takeover battle that has pushed the price tag
for the tobacco-and-food giant over $21 billion.
   Neither the bidders nor the special RJR committee overseeing the
bidding divulged details of the proposals, and officials of the
Atlanta-based company said Tuesday they expected no immediate
announcement about the bids.
   All three bidders confirmed they submitted new proposals to the
committee which had set 5 p.m. EST Tuesday as the limit for
accepting them.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's economy shrugged off the summer
drought and grew at a 2.6 percent annual rate from July through
September, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that growth in the gross
national product, the broadest measure of economic health, slowed in
the third quarter after growing at an annual rate of 3.0 percent in
the second quarter and 3.4 percent in the first three months of the
year.
   It was the slowest pace since the fourth quarter of 1986, when
the economy grew at a sluggish 1.4 percent rate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Losses in the savings and loan industry shrank
by 60 percent in the third quarter, reflecting rescues of insolvent
institutions that transferred the red ink to the government's books,
a top regulator says.
   Federal Home Loan Bank Board Chairman M. Danny Wall, in a
luncheon meeting with reporters, said Tuesday that the nation's
3,028 federally insured S&Ls lost $1.52 billion in the
July-September period, down from a revised $3.82 billion in the
second quarter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New construction contracts rose slightly in
October after a three-month slump, on the strength of residential
building everywhere except in the Northeast, a business-research
company says.
   The F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co. said
Tuesday that new construction projects last month were up 1 percent
to an annualized value of $240.2 billion. Construction contracts
fell 3 percent in September, following drops in the previous two
months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. corporations reported a slight 0.2 percent
increase in profits in the July-September quarter after posting a
large gain in the previous three-month period, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday third-quarter profits after
taxes rose $400 million to $163.1 billion, the worst showing since a
2.5 percent loss in the final quarter of 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The value of U.S. farm exports should increase
slightly to $36.5 billion this year but the volume of sales will
fall about 8 percent largely because of last summer's drought,
according to the Agriculture Department.
   Export values are expected to grow by $1 billion in fiscal 1989,
while volume will drop to 136 million metric tons in the year ended
Sept. 30, Richard W. Goldberg, acting undersecretary of agriculture
for international affairs and commodity programs, said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
