<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   11-30 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0497</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists are not likely to see higher prices at
the gas pump yet as a result of the latest agreement by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, analysts say.
   Analysts said Tuesday that growing gasoline inventories and
plenty of cheap crude oil supplies made higher gasoline prices
unlikely any time soon.
   OPEC signed an agreement Monday to reduce the amount of crude oil
it produces to 18.5 million barrels a day starting in 1989 from its
current level of approximately 22.5 million.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Four major U.S. airlines are reducing some of their air fares,
only a week after the biggest carriers made sweeping hikes in
discount fares.
   Eastern Airlines and Continental Airlines, both subsidiaries of
Texas Air Corp., said Tuesday they are cutting their fares to
Florida for travel from Jan. 5 through Feb. 15. Delta Air Lines said
it will match the fare reductions.
   Northwest Airlines, the nation's fourth-largest carrier,
announced it is taking 10 percent off its domestic fares for
passengers 62 or older.
