<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     11-30 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Weaken Amid OPEC Skepticism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil futures market is showing increased
skepticism to OPEC's new production accord.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, settled down 11
cents to $14.92 a barrel Tuesday, after trading as high as $15.25.
Other contract months mostly were lower.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange Tuesday,
the December contract for wholesale home heating oil lost 0.86 cent
to settle at 47.79 cents a gallon. The December contract for
unleaded gasoline settled at 46.87 cents a gallon, up 0.50 cent from
Monday.
   Analysts said the market was directionless following Monday's
agreement by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to
limit crude production to 18.5 million barrels a day, well under the
estimated 22.5 million it now is pumping.
   ``I think confusion is the watchword,'' said Peter Beutel, an
energy analyst for Elders Futures Inc. ``I don't think OPEC answered
a lot of questions the market has.''
   Beutel said many traders are wondering what the cartel members
would do before the accord takes effect Jan. 1, whether some would
flood the market with oil before the date or start cutting
production early. He said traders also are wondering whether all
members would adhere to the voluntary cuts once the agreement is in
place.
   Just after the pact was announced Monday, the United Arab
Emirates said the output level set in the OPEC agreement was not his
official ceiling, although the nation's oil minister later promised
to abide by the quota.
   Runaway oil production has been responsible for worsening a
worldwide surplus that has sharply reduced oil prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
