<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AirFares     11-30 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Fares,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Air Units, Delta, Northwest Cut Some Fares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just a week after the nation's major airlines
raised most of their discount air fares, four big carriers announced
reductions in some of their fares.
   Eastern Airlines and Continental Airlines, both subsidiaries of
Texas Air Corp., said Tuesday they are cutting their fares to
Florida for travel from Jan. 5 through Feb. 15. Delta Air Lines, a
close competitor of Eastern in the market linking the Northeast and
Florida, said it will match the fare reductions.
   Northwest Airlines, the nation's fourth-largest carrier,
announced in St. Paul, Minn., that it is taking 10 percent off its
domestic fares for passengers 62 or older. A companion accompanying
a senior citizen also is entitled to the reduction, regardless of
the companion's age, Northwest said.
   The limited fare cuts follow a move last week by the nation's big
airlines to boost most of their lowest discount fares and eliminate
the cheap fares that can be booked a few days before a flight.
   The changes, which were initiated by Continental and took effect
last Tuesday, revamped the popular advance-purchase ``MaxSaver''
fares used by most vacation travelers. About two-thirds of the
MaxSaver fares were increased, while the rest were reduced.
   The airlines also dropped the so-called ``junk fares'' available
four to seven days before a flight and used mainly by business
travelers.
   In making the changes last week, Miami-based Eastern said it
planned to keep its fares intact in the highly competitive
Northeast-Florida market. Its competitor Delta also put off revising
fares in the Florida market.
   Eastern, the biggest airline in the Florida market with about a
third of the passenger traffic, announced Tuesday it is cutting its
MaxSaver fares from the Northeast to 11 Florida cities by around $40
on a round-trip ticket. The new one-way fares range from $79 to
$119, down from the current $109 to $149.
   Delta is matching Eastern's fare cuts to Florida, Delta
spokeswoman Glenda Hatchett Johnson said from the carrier's Atlanta
headquarters.
   Eastern said tickets must be purchased from Nov. 30 through Dec.
15, for travel to Florida from Jan. 5 through Feb. 15. Fares are
based on a round-trip purchase and are non-refundable. Tickets must
be purchased within 24 hours of making a reservation.
   Eastern also said it is offering a $50 discount on its winter
vacation packages to Florida for travel through Feb. 15.
   ``Ten years of (airline) deregulation has taught us that price
discounting really does work ... We know that discounts can
stimulate business,'' George Brennan, Eastern's vice president of
marketing, told a news conference in New York.
   With the cheaper fares, Eastern is aiming to attract more
passengers to Florida in January, which is not as heavily booked as
February and March, Brennan said.
   Houston-based Continental announced similar reductions for travel
from 17 cities in the Northeast and Midwest to nine Florida
destinations. Tickets must be bought from Nov. 30 through Dec. 16,
for flights beginning on or after Jan. 5 and completed by Feb. 15.
   The non-refundable tickets require a Saturday night stay and
round-trip purchase. Continental said seats are limited at the
special fares, but are ``generously available.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
