<1ST_LINE>r f PM-USHondas-Japan Bjt   11-30 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US Hondas-Japan, Bjt,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Made Hondas Selling Well In Japan, Company Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEITH ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demand in Japan for American-made Hondas
has been so strong that the company says it has increased production
to satisfy orders for the autos, which it began exporting to its
home country earlier this year.
   Honda, the fourth-largest automaker in the United States, will
ship 6,000 two-door Accord Coupes to Japan by the end of this year,
up from its original estimate of 4,000, according to Roger Lambert,
a spokesman for Honda of America Mfg. Inc.
   Lambert said Tuesday that the first shipment, which arrived in
Tokyo last spring, aroused curiosity among Japanese dealers and
customers. There were orders for 2,000 Accord Coupes when the
initial load of 540 cars was shipped.
   ``They asked, will these cars be as good as the cars that come
out of Japan?'' he said. ``When the first cars arrived, they were
put under the microscope...and they were very well-received.''
   ``Reports continued to come back that orders were pouring in and
that any increase in production would be welcome,'' he said.
   Few Honda dealerships in Japan have the Accord Coupe on display,
primarily because they lack showroom space and because of the
one-month delivery time for the car, said Toshiaki Mishiba, a Honda
dealer in Tokyo. Of the six dealerships in Tokyo that belong to
Honda Daiichi Sales, Mishiba's is the only one displaying the car.
   In Japan, the Coupe sells for 2.6 million yen, about $21,300 at
current exchange rates. A comparable car sells for from $11,650 to
$15,300 in the United States, depending on equipment.
   Mishiba, who has sold about 30 of the Coupes since April, said
Japanese buyers are attracted to the left-side steering wheel in the
U.S.-made Honda. Japanese cars have the steering wheel on the right
side.
   ``It gives Japanese an American feeling combined with confidence
in Honda's quality,'' Mishiba said. ``With its leather seats,
aluminum wheels and (American-made) Bose stereo system, it's
relatively cheap, about 300,000 yen ($2,500) less than a comparable
car sold in Japan.''
   Maryann Keller, an analyst with Furman Selz Mager Dietz & Birney
of New York City, said that although the U.S.-made Hondas were
selling well in Japan, the auto must prove it is a well-made car
that retains its value if the company is to reach its export growth
goals.
   ``The Japanese customer may very well be buying this car this
year because it's new, it's different. It has its badge of
distinction,'' Ms. Keller said.
   Honda will export a total of 12,000 cars this year, including
4,500 Accord four-door sedans to Canada and 1,500 of the same car to
Taiwan, Lambert said. The company hopes to export 70,000 U.S.-made
cars by 1991, including 50,000 to Japan, he said.
   In comparison, General Motors Corp. plans to export 80,000
vehicles worldwide by the end of the year, Ford Motor Co. 42,000 and
Chrysler Corp. 55,000.
   Lambert said Honda plans to export about the same number of
Accord Coupes in 1989 as it exports this year. The car is produced
only at the Marysville plant, about 35 miles northwest of Columbus
in central Ohio.
   Honda began manufacturing in the United States in September 1979
with a motorcycle plant in Marysville. The auto plant at Marysville
began production of the Accord four-door sedan in November 1982, and
an engine plant at Anna in western Ohio started production in July
1985.
   The first U.S.-made Accords shipped to Japan arrived there April
8, the same day Honda of America's one millionth car rolled off the
Marysville assembly line.
   Honda, which holds 3.5 percent of the world auto market, expects
to produce 360,000 cars at its Marysville plant this year.
   The Civic four-door sedan was added to production at Marysville
in July 1986, and production of Civic engines began at Anna two
months later.
   Near the Marysville operation, Honda is building a new assembly
plant that is scheduled to begin production of Civic four-door
sedans in Fall 1989.
</TEXT>
