<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PrimeComputer     11-30 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prime Computer,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Rejects Buyout Offer, Discloses `Third Party' Inquiry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc., has rejected a $970 million
buyout offer MAI Basic Four Inc. and said it had received an
unsolicited overture from a third party.
   Prime on Tuesday called the $20-a-share offer from a subsidiary
of MAI, which is controlled by investor Bennett S.
LeBow,``inadequate'' and said in a statement that Prime's recent
acquisitions and consolidation measures would soon boost the
company's performance.
   ``We believe the unsolicited $20 offer by Choice fails to
recognize either the intrinsic value of the company today or the
long-term values achievable by the company for all its
stockholders,'' said David Dunn, Prime Computer's chairman.
   In trading Tuesday, Prime's stock closed up 87{ cents a share at
$16.50 in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Also Tuesday, Prime said in a Securities and Exchange Commission
filing that it had ``received an unsolicited preliminary inquiry
from a third party with respect to a possible negotiated business
combination.''
   Prime spokesman Joseph Gavaghan said the company's board did not
want to disclose the source of the inquiry because it might disrupt
potential negotiations. No discussions have yet begun, he said.
   In a prepared statement, LeBow responded: ``It is quite
surprising that the Prime board, chaired by Mr. David J. Dunn, a
self-avowed advocate of shareholders rights and opponent of
management entrenchment devices such as poison pills and golden
parachutes, would choose to stonewall the MBF offer with such
devices.''
   ``We are opposed to their actions and will continue to pursue
vigorously our acquisition of Prime,'' LeBow said.
   John Adams, an analyst for Adams Harkness & Hill in Boston, said
the announcement of the third-party inquiry did not necessarily
herald the arrival of a ``white knight'' bidder to thwart an MAI
takeover.
   MAI Basic, based in Tustin, Calif., owns 4.1 percent of Prime's
48.5 million shares outstanding.
   In its filing with the SEC, Prime said it was not actively
engaged in any substantive discussions or negotiations that could
lead to a transaction such as a merger, sale or purchase of assets
or a change in Prime's current capitalization and dividend policy,
but might do so.
   The third-party inquiry was made sometime between Nov. 15, when
MAI Basic made its tender offer, and Nov. 22, when the Prime board
voted to keep the source of the inquiry secret.
   The board's unanimous decision to reject the MAI bid was made in
a meeting on Monday and was announced Tuesday. In addition to
rejecting the MAI bid, Prime retained a ``poison pill'' shareholder
rights plan designed to make unwelcome takeovers prohibitively
expensive.
   Last week Prime sued MAI Basic, saying its offer was illegal and
flawed.
   Some analysts have speculated that LeBow has attempted the
takeover to induce Prime to buy his company.
   Dunn said the Prime board considered several factors, including
Prime's business and financial condition, its prospects,
recommendations from the company's financial advisers and the recent
value of its stock, before rejecting the offer.
   The Prime directors felt the current market price of Prime common
stock reflects the negative effects of the costs and expenses
associated with the acquisition of Computervision, acquired in
February for $435 million.
   The company expects belt-tightening measures in certain areas to
improve near-term and long-term operating results of the company and
increase values for stockholders.
   Prime is second to International Business Machines Corp. in the
field of computer-aided design and manufacturing systems. It also
makes sophisticated computer work stations for engineers and
database management systems.
</TEXT>
