<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed against most major foreign
currencies in early European trading today. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said the market focused on the pound,
which was strengthened by last week's increase in British interest
rates and by Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's pledge
Tuesday to main high interest rates to combat inflation.
   ``Interest rates are so enticing at the moment in the U.K. that
the pound is bound to keep rising,'' said one trader in Milan, Italy.
   The Bank of England raised the base lending rate one percentage
point to 13 percent last week.
   Other traders said the market is waiting for the release of
several key U.S. economic indicators this week. The October index of
leading economic indicators is scheduled to be released on Thursday
followed by November unemployment statistics on Friday.
   Better-than-expected job figures could fuel inflationary trends
in the U.S. economy and cause the Federal Reserve to increase
short-term interest rates, dealers said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.30 yen to a closing 121.85. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 121.91 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.7347 West German marks, up from 1.7285; 1.4515
Swiss francs, up from 1.4481; 5.9250 French francs, up from 5.9125;
1.9552 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9530; 1,282.70 Italian lire, up
from 1,281.25; and 1.1885 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1930
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8468, slightly more
expensive for buyers than late Tuesday's $1.8425.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $421.15 a troy ounce,
down from $422.75 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $421.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $421.25, down from $422.25 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 69 cents to close at a bid
$422.62.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.08 a troy ounce,
down slightly from Tuesday's $6.09.
</TEXT>
