<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     11-30 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Inches Down, Stocks Up Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen
today after its decline in New York, and share prices rose sharply
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 121.85 yen, down 0.30 from Tuesday's close
of 122.15 yen. Opening at 121.77 yen, it moved within a narrow range
of 121.70-121.90 yen.
   The U.S. currency's lower opening in Tokyo followed losses in New
York after Tuesday's release of U.S. gross national product figures
for the third quarter of 1988. The GNP growth was 2.6 percent,
compared to the previous quarter's 2.2 percent.
   Some dealers said the GNP increase was smaller than currency
traders had anticipated.
   But a dealer at Mitsubishi Bank said the GNP figure did not
create a strong downward force on the dollar in Tokyo trading, which
he said was moving little before Friday's scheduled release of the
U.S. unemployment rate.
   A dealer with the Chemical Bank said ``participants were sitting
on the sidelines ahead of the U.S. unemployment rate report.''
   Both dealers spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Meanwhile, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Exchange, which gained
334.98 points the previous day, added 260.60 points, or 0.89
percent, to close at 29,578.90, a new high. The index quickly gained
162.55 points shortly after the market opened and continued upward.
On Monday, the Nikkei closed at 29,318.30.
   The Nikkei's previous record high was 29,430.12 on Nov. 22.
   Share prices were higher almost across the board on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange following the rise in the Dow Jones Industrial
Average overnight in New York and the U.S. GNP announcement.
   ``Market players in Tokyo took the GNP figure positively, mainly
because it was more or less within the range that most of them had
expected,'' Toshiyuki Nishiguchi of Daiwa Securities said.
   ``Now the market is waiting for the U.S. jobless rate to
determine how to act,'' he said.
   Other dealers said the GNP figure boosted buying by institutional
investors as well as individuals.
   In a heavy trading with volume traded on the first section
estimated at 1.6 billion shares, steels, financial and paper-related
issues attracted participants.
