<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0746EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Salinas-Economy Bjt   11-30 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salinas-Economy, Bjt,0805</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salinas Will Walk A Delicate Line Between Hope and Fear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who takes office as
president on Thursday, will be walking a delicate line between
inflation and deep recession, between debt and investment, and
between his people's hopes and their fears.
   The staggering $102 billion foreign debt is the best-known of
Mexico's economic problems, but it is far from the only one.
   Mexico has gone into recession this fall, partly as a result of a
government deficit and partly as a result of efforts to control
inflation, which was over 140 per cent in 1987.
   The recession is a further blow to a people who lost about half
their buying power during six years of austerity under President
Miguel de la Madrid _ an austerity Salinas presided over as budget
director.
   The economy also has bright spots, such as tremendous growth in
non-petroleum exports, and businessmen are facing the future with
more confidence than they did in 1982.
   ``Back then everybody was trembling, afraid of what was going to
happen next,'' said Ramon E. Alatorre, an assistant to the president
for Howard Johnson of Mexico, a restaurant and motel franchiser.
   Among other things, petroleum prices had plunged, Mexico had run
out of money to pay its foreign obligations and President Jose Lopez
Portillo had just nationalized the banks.
   It was Salinas who led the effort to modernize Mexico's economy,
selling state-owned companies, reducing subsidies and increasing
competition, all policies Salinas intends to continue.
   The dark side was squeezed pocketbooks and political unrest, a
boon to the opposition in the July 6 presidential elections.
   Salinas won, but barely, and, says the opposition, unfairly. He
is now under pressure to resume growth, relieve unemployment and
restore the damaged standard of living.
   A study by a private enterprise group estimated Mexico's economy
created only 350,000 jobs last year _ 650,000 fewer than it needs to
to keep up with the number of young people entering the job market
every year.
   The official unemployment figure is 8 percent, but a study by
Salinas' own Institutional Revolutionary Party estimated the real
rate at 14 percent. Other economists put it as high as 20 percent.
   The latest example of the human strain came this week in the
state of Michoacan, where disgruntled political opponents occupied
city halls in 30 towns and cities and said they wanted Salinas out.
   ``We have to provide housing, education, sanitation and other
basic services,'' Salinas said in a recent televised interview.
   There is a growing consensus that Mexico will get international
help. It will pay $14 billion in interest and principle on its
foreign debt this year, money that could have been used for
investment in development and growth.
   Mexico's debt obligations ``should be designed subject to (its)
capacity to pay under conditions of growth,'' said a study released
this month by the Bilateral Commission on the Future of United
States-Mexican Relations.
   Although Salinas is aiming for a growth rate of 5 percent and
hopes to gain $5 to $6 billion a year in fresh credits and debt
relief, he has already said he expects little growth in 1989.
   A ``social compact'' between government, labor and business has
helped control prices and wages, and Salinas' trickiest immediate
assignment may be ending the pact without reigniting inflation,
recently close to zero.
   Mexico also has had capital outflow since the end of April, when
Mexico boasted $16.2 billion in hard-earned foreign exchange.
   That figure was below $10 billion by October, according to
Jonathan Heath, director of the economic forecasting firm Macro
Asesoria, as Mexico began showing a trade deficit and spent money
supporting the peso.
   Heath and other economists said many feel the financial community
owes Mexico, which has done everything it was asked to do in
revamping its economy and imposing austerity.
   One sign of U.S. confidence and support was a recent $3.5 billion
loan offer to give Salinas some breathing room.
   Oil, which used to account for 90 percent of Mexico's income, now
accounts for about a third _ a diversification in products and
customers that has made it less vulnerable to oil price swings and
the strength of the U.S. economy.
   Mexico should be helped by higher oil prices if a recent
agreement by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
stands up.
   Alatorre, the hopeful businessman, says the progress made should
not be forgotten.
   ``They wouldn't have been able to sell Aeromexico if things had
stayed the way they were,'' said Alatorre, referring to last week's
sale of a government-owned airline for $345 million. ``Nobody would
even have bought a ticket.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
