<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0752EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-StormSewers     11-30 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Storm Sewers,0338</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 11:30 a.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>EPA to Require Permits for Storm Sewers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cities of more than 100,000 population will be
required to obtain federal pollution discharge permits for storm
sewers from the Environmental Protection Agency, EPA said today.
   The same requirements will fall on certain large industrial
plants with their own storm sewers, but generally not plants that
discharge into a municipal storm sewer system.
   The requirements come in draft regulations required by 1987
legislation to bring storm sewers under the agency's permit system.
   Several studies have shown that storm runoff and melting snow can
pick up pesticides and fertilizers from lawns, oil from garages and
service stations and other contaminants from construction sites,
landfills, junkyards, construction sites and even dry cleaners.
   Twenty-one states have listed construction-site runoff as a major
source of harm to stream water quality.
   A major feature of the regulations will ban cross-connections
between storm sewer systems and sanitary sewage lines. These
connections, called illicit connections because they are frequently
just that, can result in the discharge of industrial process waste
or household sewage to rivers and streams without proper treatment.
   ``Removal of these illicit connections often presents
opportunities for dramatic improvements in the quality of
storm-sewer discharges,'' EPA said.
   Cities with combined sanitary and storm sewers, generally older
cities in the East, are covered by a separate set of regulations.
   Cities will be allowed to propose their own permit conditions.
EPA said that for the initial five-year permit terms, cities would
have to start identifying pollution sources, conduct an initial
analysis of illicit connections, and describe their storm sewer
management plans and priorities.
   The plans will place heavy emphasis on optimum management
practices, including appropriate local ordinances, instead of
requiring new treatment facilities, EPA said.
   The agency said it would hold several hearings around to country
through February seeking comments on the draft regulations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
