<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CaribbeanConference     11-30 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Caribbean Conference,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dominican President: Economic Discipline Answer To Latin Debt Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strict economic discipline is the only way to
overcome the mounting public debt facing some Latin American
countries, said President Joaquin Balaguer of the Dominican Republic.
   ``The problem of the public debt in Latin America is the product
of a lack of forethought,'' Balaguer said Tuesday night in the first
address at the 12th annual Miami Conference on the Caribbean.
   ``Those governments in power happily contracted those loans and
then without thought failed to manage funds responsibly,'' he said.
   The debt can be surmounted only through strict economic
discipline and adjustments, not through ``gifts or donations'' from
the United States or the International Monetary Fund.
   Debt in Latin America and underdeveloped countries worldwide is
not just an economic or political problem, but a human one, Balaguer
said.
   The greatest challenge ``isn't payment of the debt, but sustained
economic growth and increased per capita income,'' said Balaguer,
speaking in Spanish. ``The first challenge is to live _ the second
is to pay.''
   ``We have to seek the causes of underdevelopment of the Third
World, especially the Latin underdevelopment,'' he said. ``Something
must exist... that would allow some nations to advance while others,
in many cases exceptionally endowed by nature, haven't been able to
reach the level that corresponds to them.''
   About 2,000 delegates, including Latin and Caribbean officials
and investors from outside the region were expected to participate
in the four-day conference on trade, investment and development.
   Preceeding Balaguer with welcoming remarks were Miami Mayor
Xavier Suarez, Prime Minister Maria Liberia Peters of the
Netherlands Antilles and French Minister of State for Foriegn
Affairs Ewige Avice.
   ``We have big expectations towards the Bush administration and
the newly elected Congress,'' said Ms. Peters, adding that the
smaller countries of the Caribbean should find a way to join the
United States and Canada in their free trade agreement.
   In addition to Balaguer, the Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo
and the prime ministers of Barbados, Belize, Dominica, Jamaica, the
Netherlands Antilles, St. Lucia and St. Vincent and the Grenadines
were to attend.
</TEXT>
