<DOCNO> AP881130-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 0948EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-MeatBan     11-30 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Meat Ban,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, EEC To Discuss Hormone Dispute Again In Montreal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In another attempt to stave off a
trans-Atlantic trade war, U.S. and EEC officials plan to meet in
Montreal to discuss an EEC plan to ban imports of U.S. meat treated
with growth-boosting hormones.
   EEC External Trade Commissioner Willy De Clercq said Wednesday he
and EEC Agriculture Commissioner Frans Andriessen will discuss the
ban with U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter and U.S.
Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng on Friday.
   ``We should try everything possible and decent to avoid the
clash,'' De Clercq told reporters.
   Friday's encounter will precede next week's meeting in Montreal
to review progress in the Uruguay round of global trade
liberalization talks within the 96-nation General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
   The 12-nation European Economic Community has complained to GATT
about the growth hormones, which it considers a health hazard, and
about U.S. threats of retaliation.
   The meat import ban is scheduled to take effect on Jan. 1. The
ban would affect about $145 million annually in exports of U.S. meat
to the EEC.
   The United States argues that hormone-treated meat poses no
health hazard as the EEC contends and considers the ban a
protectionist measure.
   The United States has threatened to retaliate against imports
from the EEC which in turn has threatened a counter-retaliation.
   The hormone debate has been around for two years without the EEC
and the United States being able to resolve the dispute.
   De Clercq, Andriessen, Lyng and Yeutter last discussed the issue
at a meeting on Nov. 18.
   De Clercq denied press reports that since then the two sides have
come nearer a compromise and gave no indication the EEC was ready to
drop the ban.
   The EEC has offered to exempt meat for pet food from its ban and
raise imports of top-quality U.S. beef if it is free of hormones.
   The United States has accepted the pet food proposal but has said
the high-grade beef proposal did not remove America's fundamental
objections to the EEC ban.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
