<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1004EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CoalSuit     11-30 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coal Suit,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HL&P, Railroad Settle Coal Transport Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burlington Northern Inc. has agreed to pay Houston
Lighting and Power Co. $58 million to settle a coal-transport
dispute.
   HL&P, and its fuel-supply affiliate, Utility Fuels Inc., sued
Seattle-based Burlington Northern and four other railroad companies
in July 1986 claiming they conspired to block construction of a coal
slurry pipeline from Wyoming to Texas and Arkansas.
   Energy Transportation Systems Inc. was to build the pipeline to
carry pulverized coal mixed with water from the Powder River Basin
in Wyoming and Montana primarily to HL&P's coal-fired plants in
Texas.
   But due to the alleged conspiracy, ETSI canceled the project.
   ETSI separately sued the five railway companies. Burlington
Northern said it agreed to pay ETSI a $100 million cash payment on
Dec. 1, and deferred payments of $25 million plus interest on Dec.
1, 1989, 1990 and 1991.
   Burlington Northern is the third defendant to settle with HL&P.
The utility had previously settled with Chicago and Northwestern
Railroad and Union Pacific Railway, but HL&P declined to give
separate settlement amounts.
   Meanwhile, the case is scheduled to go to trial in Janaury 1989
with the other two defendants, Atchinson, Topeka and Santa Fe
Railway Co. and Kansas City Southern Railway Co.
   Burlington Northern confirmed it agreed to adjust HL&P's rates on
the remaining 12 years of a long-term contract to transport coal
from the Powder River Basin to HL&P plants in Texas.
   HL&P spokesman Floyd LeBlanc said the settlement won't affect the
light company's application for a $432 million rate-hike request.
   HL&P is petitioning the state Public Utilities Commission for a
base-rate increase to recover the cost of building two generating
stations _ a coal-fired unit in Limestone County and the first unit
of the South Texas Nuclear Project near Bay City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881130-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1016EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     11-30 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0290</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices opened higher on Wall Street today in a
continuation of the rally that began Tuesday afternoon.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 4.62 to
2,106.15 as of 10 a.m. EST.
   Advancing issues had a margin of about 4-to-3 over decliners,
with 490 stocks rising, 371 declining and 504 unchanged on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Big Board volume was a light 16.99 million shares after the first
30 minutes of trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed stocks was up 0.26
to 152.69. On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index
was up 0.51 to 292.71.
   Hildegarde Zagorski, a market analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc., said traders were buying in a follow-through from
gains on Tuesday, when the Dow Jones industrial average rose 20.09
to 2,101.53.
   Continued strength in the dollar also supported prices today, she
said.
   The market was quiet _ as it has been in recent sessions _ while
many investors awaited Friday's scheduled release of the Labor
Department's unemployment figures for November.
   The most actively traded issue in the early going today was Texas
Utilities, which was unchanged at 28].
