<1ST_LINE>d f BC-FujitsuMove     11-30 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fujitsu Move,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Firm To Put Offices In Richardson, Sources Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHARDSON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fujitsu America Inc. will build a major
office, research and manufacturing facility in this Dallas suburb,
the Dallas Morning News reported Wednesday, citing unidentified
sources.
   ``It involves 5,000 to 6,000 people and a huge new corporate
complex,'' a source familiar with the negotiations who asked not to
be identified said. ``This is something they have been looking at
for several months.''
   Fujitsu America spokesman David Gould of the firm's San Jose,
Calif., headquarters Tuesday would neither confirm nor deny the
report.
   Sources in real estate told the newspaper that Fujitsu has
contracted to buy about 100 acres just north of the Dallas County
line in Collin County and plans to construct a 1 million-square-foot
office, research and manufacturing complex. The firm already has an
office and manufacturing facility in Richardson that employs about
300 people.
   The announcement of the plan will be made next month, sources
said. The newspaper did not say whether Fujitsu's headquarters would
be moved from San Jose or how many employees would remain there.
   Fujitsu America is the U.S. subsidiary of Fujitsu Ltd., based in
Tokyo, is a worldwide electronics company that had revenues of $16.4
billion in 1987.
   The Fujitsu consolidation and relocation would be the third big
economic development for the Dallas area in the past 30 days.
   Two weeks ago, GTE Corp. announced it was moving its national
telephone headquarters from Stamford, Conn., to Irving in a move
that would bring about 3,000 people to the area and create about
1,000 new jobs.
   It was only about three weeks ago that federal officials
announced plans to build the Superconducting Super Collider research
complex to Waxahachie, about 30 miles south of Dallas. That project
would create several thousand jobs.
  
</TEXT>
