<HEAD>Wheat Opens Lower; Corn, Soybeans Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices were mostly lower while corn
and soybeans were mostly higher in early trading today on the
Chicago Board of Trade but the price changes were slight due to a
lack of significant news.
   Analysts said the light trading and marginal price movement that
characterized this morning's activity probably would continue for
the next couple of weeks, barring any unforeseen changes in supply
and demand.
   ``I don't think we're going have any real excitement in these
markets for a while,'' said Cathy Leow, an assistant vice president
of research with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York. ``The
factors that cause extreme strength or weakness just aren't in
place.''
   She said exports would be the key to the grain markets, while
soybean traders were keeping a close watch on weather conditions in
Argentina and Brazil.
   The weather has been unusually dry for soybean planting in South
America and if the dry conditions persist into the growing season,
U.S. soybean prices are likely to rise, Ms. Leow said.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to { cent lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.23{ a bushel; corn was }
cent to 1} cents higher with December at $2.58{ a bushel; oats were
{ cent to 1{ cents higher with December at $1.96 a bushel; soybeans
were 2} cents lower to 3 cents higher with January at $7.56 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .23 cent lower to .18 cent higher with December
at 72.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .30
cent higher with January at 82.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .10
cent lower to .25 cent higher with December at 39.45 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .73 cent to 1.40 cents higher with February
at 43.85 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures closed mixed on Tuesday while pork futures were
mostly higher.
