<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf White House comment after 3rd graf pvs, It was;
Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<HEAD>Personal Income Up 1.8 Percent In October</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large increase in farm subsidy payments and
bonuses to auto workers pushed Americans' personal income up 1.8
percent in October, the steepest rise in a year, the government said
today.
   The Commerce Department said income rose $72.1 billion to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $4.18 trillion last mont,
following modest increases of 0.5 percent in September and 0.4
percent in August.
   It was the largest increase since October 1987 when income shot
up 2.0 percent, also on the strength of farm subsidies.
   ``It's continuing good news,'' said White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater. ``The economy is proceeding on an even keel.''
   The department attributed about half of last month's increase to
farm and auto payments. Excluding those factors, income would have
risen a still hefty 0.9 percent.
   Today's report is the latest in a series of indicators showing
the economy boomed in October. The unemployment rate was at a
14-year low of 5.3 percent, factories were operating at the highest
rate in 8{ years, and retailers enjoyed the strongest sales gain in
seven months.
   Personal consumption spending, which includes everything except
interest payments on debt, was up a robust 0.8 percent to an annual
rate of $3.30 trillion following a weak 0.1 percent rise in
September.
   The biggest spending increase last month was for services, up 1.4
percent, followed by a 0.6 percent increase for nondurable goods.
Spending on durable goods, ``big ticket'' items expected to last
three or more years, fell 0.6 percent.
   With income rising faster than spending, Americans saved more
than in any month since October 1987. The personal savings rate _
savings as a percentage of after-tax income _ was 5.2 percent, up
from 4.2 percent in September.
   Disposable, or after-tax income, was up 1.9 percent last month,
also the largest increase in a year, after rising 0.6 percent a
month earlier.
   Wages and salaries, a key component of personal income, were up a
strong 1.5 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $2.51
trillion, bolstered by a 2.1 percent increase in manufacturing
salaries. The auto bonuses accounted for about 60 percent of the
manufacturing increase.
   Farm income rose a huge 76.2 percent to an annual rate of $46.7
billion, largely because of government payments for corn harvested
in 1987.
</TEXT>
