<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1339EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Sun-TimesTalks     11-30 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sun-Times Talks,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last-Minute Snag Imperils Sun-Times Contract Ratification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the Chicago Sun-Times and its
newsroom employees today scheduled another round of contract
negotiations after a clause on pension-fund contributions
jeopardized their tentative labor pact.
   A bargaining session was set for Thursday morning, officials said.
   ``It's progress,'' said newspaper spokesman Michael Soll. ``It
means sitting down and reasoning again.''
   ``We hope it can be resolved,'' said Linda Lenz, a union
spokeswoman and an education writer for the Sun-Times. ``Things will
not drag on. We are determined not to let them drag on.''
   The dispute revived the chance of a strike at the city's
second-largest newspaper.
   When informed of the last-minute snag, members of Newspaper Guild
Local 71 postponed a vote on the tentative contract late Tuesday and
told union bargainers to seek new talks.
   ``We are disappointed that the guild did not unanimously
recommend approval of the company's offer as it had agreed to do,''
Soll said today.
   ``The company's offer included two separate pension alternatives
with the guild having the option to select one or the other. ...
Apparently the guild selected an alternative which it did not fully
understand,'' he said, reading a company statement.
   Ratification by the local's 250 members seemed little more than a
formality until union leaders studied specific language on pensions
in an outline provided earlier Tuesday by Sun-Times management.
   The Sun-Times said the new pension formula, which has increased
contributions from the company, takes effect Jan. 1. Union
bargainers, though, said they believed it would be retroactive to an
earlier date.
   ``Neither I nor the unit chairman, Tom Gibbons, recall any
indication made by the company about that since you don't take notes
... on things that aren't said,'' guild official Gerry Minkkinen
said.
   Soll said: ``Management has full notes describing the agreement.
And the (federal) mediator agrees with the management.''
   But Ms. Lenz said the federal mediator's notes ``were silent on
the issue. Similarly, our (Guild) notes do not reflect what the
company claims they said.''
   A strike was planned for Nov. 21, but was postponed as bargainers
tried to get a contract.
   The next day, bargainers reached agreement on a three-year pact
that offered a $500 payment in the first year, followed by 3 percent
wage increases in each of the remaining two years.
   The proposed contract also included improvements in sick leave,
hospitalization, maternity leave, indemnification from libel
lawsuits and minority hiring and training programs.
   As a result of the new development, guild spokesman Daniel
Lehmann, the newspaper's religion reporter, said another strike date
could be set.
   After Tuesday night's meeting, many newsroom employees were angry.
   ``We have to have an acceptable contract,'' said Shane Gericke, a
member of the negotiating committee, who described the guild
bargainers as being ``on a very short leash.''
   Lehmann called the pension language ``one of the major elements
of the new contract.''
   Newsroom employees have been working without a contract since
June 1.
   The Sun-Times has an estimated circulation of 605,000 daily and
614,000 on Sundays. The Chicago Tribune's circulation is estimated
at 765,000 daily and 1.11 million on Sundays.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
