<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     11-30 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0315</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices advanced on Wall Street today as activity
in takeover stocks sparked interest in other issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 12.98 to
2,114.51 as of 2 p.m. EST.
   Advancing issues had a nearly 2-to-1 edge over decliners, with
885 stocks rising, 480 declining and 510 unchanged on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Among broader measures, the NYSE's composite index of all its
listed stocks was up 1.30 to 153.73. On the American Stock Exchange,
the market value index was up 1.21 to 293.41.
   Big Board volume totaled 104.16 million shares with two hours of
trading to go.
   Michael Metz, a market analyst with Oppenheimer & Co., said
activity in takeover targets such as RJR Nabisco and Pillsbury led
to buying of other stocks.
   RJR Nabisco managers, who are among the three bidders for the
food and tobacco giant, today boosted their offer to more than $24.3
billion, or $108 a share. The company's stock shot up 2| to 93{
after the new bid was announced.
   Metz said investors also believed that Pillsbury _ which again
rejected Grand Metropolitan PLC's $5.23 billion, or $60-a-share, bid
_ would receive a higher offer. Pillsbury was up | to 58{ today.
   The developments piqued the interest of speculators, Metz said.
   ``People are looking for the next game to play,'' he said.
   Some traders were still on the sidelines, awaiting Friday's Labor
Department report on unemployment in November and fearing it could
prompt the Federal Reserve Board to tighten credit further.
   The most actively traded issue today was Ohio Edison, up [ at 18~.
   Among the other gainers, Digital Equipment was up 1[ to 93|, UAL
rose 1{ to 109 and Dow Chemical was up 1\ to 85\.
