<HEAD>British Shares Stronger in Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices strengthened Wednesday on the London
Stock Exchange but a lack of news kept the market almost static.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended the day
up 5.5 points, or 0.30 percent, at 1,792.4, the lowest point of the
session. The index reached a high of 1,801.3 at mid-morning and then
drifted lower for the rest of the day.
   At the close, the narrower Financial Times 30-share index was up
2.6 points at 1,458.0.
   Volume totaled 444.8 million shares, up from 408.4 million on
Tuesday.
   Dealers said market players seemed to be more interested in the
currency markets after the key British interest rate was raised
Friday to 13 percent, the highest among the leading Western nations.
   The stock market was also holding back to see the response to the
flotation of state-run British Steel. The offer for shares closes
Friday. If there is only a lukewarm response it won't do much good
for share prices in general because of the uncertainty created by
the interest rate hike, rising inflation and the widening British
trade deficit.
   The Financial Times index of 500 shares closed at 1,013.38, up
3.46.
