<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0324</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices moved higher on Wall Street today as
strength in the Treasury bond market eased some interest rate
worries.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 15.65 to
2,117.18 as of 3 p.m. EST.
   Advancing issues had a nearly 2-to-1 edge over decliners, with
975 stocks rising, 475 declining and 465 unchanged on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Among broader measures, the NYSE's composite index of all its
listed stocks was up 1.55 to 153.98. On the American Stock Exchange,
the market value index was up 1.51 to 293.71.
   Big Board volume totaled a moderate 130.18 million shares with
one hour of trading remaining.
   Robert Colby, a market analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &
Co., said continued strength in Treasury bond prices _ and a
resulting drop in interest rates _ helped improve the tone of the
stock market.
   By late afternoon, the government's bellwether 30-year bond was
up more than $6 per $1,000 in face value.
   Analysts said traders also took some comfort from a Federal
Reserve report that economic growth had slowed. The report raised
hopes that the Fed would not nudge interest rates higher.
   Michael Metz, an analyst with Oppenheimer & Co., said activity in
takeover targets such as RJR Nabisco and Pillsbury led to buying of
other stocks.
   RJR Nabisco managers, who are among the three bidders for the
food and tobacco giant, today boosted their offer to more than $24.3
billion, or $108 a share. The company's stock _ the most actively
traded on the NYSE _ shot up 2{ to 93] after the new bid was
announced.
   Metz said investors also believed that Pillsbury _ which again
rejected Grand Metropolitan PLC's $5.23 billion, or $60-a-share, bid
_ would receive a higher offer. Pillsbury was up ~ to 58} today.
</TEXT>
