<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Higher On First Notice Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mostly
higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, with substantial
gains in soybean and near-month corn futures partially linked to
first-notice day for the December contracts.
   Wednesday was the first day on which traders could formally
announce their intention to deliver wheat, corn, oats, soybean oil
and soybean meal against the contracts for delivery in December.
   First-notice days frequently are characterized by sharp price
movements because most traders play the market with no intention of
making or taking physical delivery of commodities, analysts said.
   There is no contract for December delivery of soybeans but the
rally in the soybean meal and oil pits helped boost soybean futures,
said Cathy Leow, an assistant vice president of research with
Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   Dry weather in the South American soybean belt also contributed
to the rise in soybean futures prices, she said.
   At the close of trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1 cent higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.24{ a bushel; corn
was 1{ cents to 4} cents higher with December at $2.61{ a bushel;
oats were unchanged to 5 cents higher with December at $1.95{ a
bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 9} cents higher with January at
$7.63{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
