<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1918EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Centel     11-30 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Centel,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Centel Seeks Buyer For Cable TV Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centel Corp. put its cable television unit on the
auction block Wednesday, two months after buying out a group of
dissident shareholders for $92.5 million and seven months after
declaring it was not selling any of its businesses.
   Chairman John P. Frazee Jr. said divestment of the Centel Cable
Television Co. would allow Centel to concentrate on its telephone
operations, which include local exchange service in nine states and
a fast-growing mobile cellular communications business that operates
in 13 states.
   Analysts estimated the value of Centel Cable at $1.4 billion.
Centel said in a statement that proceeds from the sale would be used
to repurchase shares and reduce indebtedness.
   But Frazee denied any connection between the decision to sell
Centel Cable and the more than $850 million that Centel paid out in
the past year to extend the reach of its cellular division and fight
a takeover battle.
   ``We can't be all things; we can't be as large in each one of
these three businesses as we would like to be,'' Frazee said in a
telephone interview from his Chicago office.
   ``We believe this decision will allow our shareholders to receive
full value from our cable television investment,'' Frazee said.
``More importantly, it will enable us to refocus our attention on
those businesses that have tremendous potential for enhancing
sharehoulder value.''
   Frazee would not speculate on the potential sale price of Centel
Cable, which serves more than 550,000 subscribers in Florida,
Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Michigan and Ohio.
   Centel Cable ranks 22nd among the top 50 U.S. cable operators and
should fetch about $25 per subscriber, or about $1.4 billion, said
Paula Greer, an industry analyst with Paul Kagan Associates Inc. of
Carmel, Calif.
   Ms. Greer said in an interview from her office in Mount Clemens,
Mich., that federal regulations prohibit companies from owning both
cable and telephone services in the same market, ``so it does make
sense that they would sell off the cable and concentrate on their
core business, which is telephone operations.''
   Centel Cable, accounted for $130 million of Centel's $1.48
billion in revenues last year and has been an industry leader in
deploying new technologies such as pay-per-view and fiber optics,
Centel said.
   Local telephone service provides the bulk of Centel's revenues,
accounting for nearly $825 million in sales last year.
   Last spring, Centel purchased United Telespectrum Inc., the
cellular subsidiary of Kansas City, Mo.-based United
Telecommunications, for $763 million plus $9.5 million in United
Telespectrum debt.
   Centel spent much of this year waging a proxy battle against its
largest shareholders, New York-based investors Asher B. Edelman and
George Lindemann, who sought to break up the company and sell the
pieces. Frazee had said in April that none of Centel's businesses
were for sale.
   Shareholders rejected the dissidents' takeover bid and in
September, Edelman and Lindemann sold their 5.5 percent stake back
to Centel.
   Centel still is seeking a buyer for its business telephone
systems business, which has been on the block since late May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
