<DOCNO> AP881130-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-88 1716EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-30 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Declines; Gold Stronger</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell slightly Wednesday after bearish
sentiment pulled it down from gains posted earlier in trading in
Europe. Gold prices rose.
   ``It was a war between the bulls and the bears,'' said Zlatko
Glamuzina, chief currency dealer of Banco di Sicilia in New York.
   The early rise in the dollar was based partly on expectations
that the Federal Reserve would push up U.S. interest rates to
control inflation. But a report to the Federal Reserve on Wednesday
said there was no indication that inflation was getting out of hand,
Glamuzina said.
   In addition to the report to the Fed, the dollar was hurt by a
big sell order and by action by the Bank of England, whose attempts
to keep the British pound from rising against the West German mark
had the effect of pressuring the dollar, Glamuzina said.
   Foreign-exchange dealers said trading was light and traders were
reluctant to take big positions ahead of new U.S. economic
statistics due Thursday and Friday.
   The Commerce Department is scheduled to report Thursday on the
index of leading economic indicators for October, and the Labor
Department is scheduled to report Friday on the November
unemployment rate.
   The Canadian dollar strengthened against the dollar, prompting
the Bank of Canada to sell the currency.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 121.85 Japanese yen, down from
122.15. In London late Wednesday the dollar traded at 122.05 yen. In
New York, the dollar fell to 121.48 yen from 121.83 on Tuesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8480 late Wednesday, more
expensive for buyers than Tuesday's late $1.8425. Later in New York,
the pound rose to $1.8535 from $1.8443 Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.7318 West German marks, down from 1.7348; 1.4498
Swiss francs, down from 1.4500; 1.1834 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1913; 5.9195 French francs, down from 5.9310; and 1,279.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,282.50.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Tuesday's late rates, included: 1.7375 West German marks, up from
1.7285; 1.4548 Swiss francs, up from 1.4481; 5.9327 French francs,
up from 5.9125; 1.9590 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9530; 1,284.97
Italian lire, up from 1,281.25; and 1.1872 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1930.
   Dealers said trading in gold was light and the improvement was
due to a rise in the price of platinum.
   Gold in Hong Kong closed at a bid of $422.62 a troy ounce, up
from $421.93.
   Gold closed in London at a bid of $423.25 a troy ounce, up from
$422.75 late Tuesday. The closing price in Zurich, Switzerland, was
$422.30 bid, up from $422.25.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $424.80 a troy ounce from $421.90.
   Later, Republic National Bank of New York said gold rose to
$424.10 a troy ounce from $421.50.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.14 bid a troy ounce,
up from $6.09. On New York's Comex, silver rose to $6.136 a troy
ounce from $6.030.
</TEXT>
