<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise Despite OPEC Skepticism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices surged in moderate trading
Wednesday amid encouraging signs about the latest OPEC agreement.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, settled 40
cents higher at $15.32 a barrel, near its high for the day of
$15.35. The contract price had fallen 11 cents a barrel on Tuesday.
Other contract months also rose, though not as sharply.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
December contract for unleaded gasoline soared 2.18 cents to finish
at 49.05 cents a gallon. The December contract for wholesale home
heating oil rose 0.53 cent to 48.32 cents a gallon. Other contract
months for both products also advanced.
   Analysts said two encouraging developments helped strengthen
prices.
   Non-OPEC oil-producing countries are showing signs of wanting to
cooperate with OPEC countries to help reduce the glut of oil on
world markets, said Bob Baker, an analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   ``That's very important psychologically,'' Baker said. ``It's not
that non-OPEC countries are going to cut back much, but it could
show some positive response.''
   In addition, the oil minister from the United Arab Emirates
continued to make efforts to soften remarks he made on Monday that
his country did not consider its new OPEC production quota the
``official'' quota.
   On Monday, the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
signed a new agreement to limit the cartel's production to 18.5
million barrels a day from the present level of around 22.5 million.
The cartel also maintained its benchmark price of $18 a barrel,
which it hopes to achieve in the first half of 1989.
   Analysts said Wednesday's oil futures prices also were helped by
bullish weekly statistics on U.S. inventories from the American
Petroleum Institute and the expiration of the December contracts on
the Mercantile Exchange.
   Late Tuesday, new weekly API data showed declines in crude and
gasoline inventories. Gasoline stocks dropped 2.5 million barrels
last week and crude stocks fell 2.6 million.
</TEXT>
