<1ST_LINE>u f AM-United-Labor     11-30 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-United-Labor,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flight Attendants Surprised by United's Call for Talks Mediator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Association of Flight Attendants said
Wednesday it was surprised by United Airlines' call for a mediator
in contract talks with the union.
   ``We would say it was premature. The company has been unwilling
to meet very many times this year. We aren't against it, we are just
surprised by it,'' said Cindy Yeast, spokeswoman for the flight
attendants union.
   Chicago-based United requested the mediation in an application
filed with the National Mediation Board on Tuesday.
   ``A mediator has to be selected and dates for new talks agreed
upon. All this takes time,'' said Ms. Yeast.
   United refused comment on the matter.
   ``We never have any comment concerning contract negotiations,''
said United spokeswoman Sara Dornacker.
   United's 13,000 flight attendants rejected a tentative agreement
almost a year ago. New negotiations began in January and employees
continued to work under their old labor pact.
   ``There is no threat of a strike. Airlines are governed by the
Railway Labor Act, which stipulates a number of cooling off periods
and contract extensions,'' Ms. Yeast said.
   Since April, the carrier also has been involved in contract talks
with the Air Line Pilots Association.
</TEXT>
