<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FTC-Kraft     11-30 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC-Kraft,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Closes Probe of Philip Morris-Kraft Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission ended its
antitrust probe of the proposed $12.6 billion merger of Philip
Morris Cos. Inc. and Kraft Inc. on Wednesday, after news reports
that it was still investigating the deal generated widespread
investor concern.
   The commission formally ended its probe a day after the mandatory
waiting period for the takeover ended.
   Normally, closing an antitrust investigation is a routine matter
attracting little public attention. The two companies had issued a
statement Tuesday that the legal waiting period had ended without
the government challenging their merger plans.
   But, at a routine press briefing on Wednesday, FTC Chairman
Daniel Oliver and agency officials declined to discuss details of
the case, stating that they could not comment because the matter
remained open.
   That sparked speculation that the agency might be preparing to
take action against the planned takeover and prompted officials to
call news media to clarify their position. And the full commission
met by the end of the day and voted to close the matter.
   ``It's fairly routine to keep investigations open beyond
the...waiting period, ending the waiting period doesn't mean the
investigation is auotmatically closed,'' said Patrick M. Sheller, an
aide to Oliver.
   But Sheller and FTC spokeswoman Anna Davis stressed that keeping
the investigation open did not indicate any action was pending.
   When large companies plan to merge they must inform the
commission and Justice Department and then wait 30 days before
completing the action to give the government time to act if it deems
the marger anticompetitive.
   But even after a merger is completed the commission still can
take legal action to undo the combination.
   Sheller said the normal procedure is for the staff to come to the
five-member commission at some point with a recommendation on
whether to approve the merger. Then the commission itself votes on
that recommendation and either commences lagal action or sends the
companies a formal notice closing the investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
