<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Tyson-HollyFarms 2ndLd-Writethru f0295 11-30 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tyson-Holly Farms, 2nd Ld - Writethru, f0295,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tyson Conditionally Sweetens Holly Farms Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 new grafs to CORRECT that invalidation of merger
agreement not a condition of sweetened tender offer. Picks up 4th
graf, Tyson also...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc. on Wednesday sweetened
its buyout offer for Holly Farms Corp., but made completion of the
deal contingent on the elimination of key terms of Holly Farms'
merger with ConAgra Inc.
   The nation's biggest poultry processor boosted its cash tender
offer to $54 a share, or about $1.1 billion for Holly Farms' 20.4
million outstanding common shares and equivalents, from $52 a share,
or about $1.06 billion.
   Tyson stated in a letter to the board of Memphis, Tenn.-based
Holly Farms that the offer was subject to termination or
invalidation of Holly Farms' agreement to sell ConAgra some of its
prize assets if acquired by a third company, such as Tyson, and to
pay ConAgra a ``bustup fee'' if their deal fell through.
   Tyson also offered to pay cash and stock it valued at $57 a share
for control of Holly Farms under a two-step buyout if the company
terminated its merger with ConAgra and negotiated a new agreement
with Tyson.
   The company said it remained willing to revise its new proposals
and threatened to put the latest offers directly before shareholders
if Holly Farms continued its refusal to negotiate.
   A Holly Farms spokesman at the company's headquarters was said to
be unavailable for comment. ConAgra spokesman Walt Casey said the
latest Tyson offer ``doesn't change our expectations of being able
to acquire'' Holly Farms. ConAgra has valued its proposal for Holly
Farms at about $1 billion.
   Holly Farms has rejected Tyson's previous takeover offers and on
Nov. 16 agreed to a stock swap merger with Omaha, Neb.-based ConAgra
that the Holly Farms board valued at $59.25 a share. That merger
with Holly Farms, the nation's second-largest poultry processor,
would make ConAgra the nation's biggest poultry concern.
   In agreeing to the merger, Holly Farms granted ConAgra a
so-called ``lockup option'' to buy key Holly Farms assets in the
event a third company acquires Holly Farms. It also agreed to pay
ConAgra a $15 million ``bustup fee'' if their merger falls through.
   Tyson is challenging those provision in Delaware Chancery Court,
and in Wednesday's letter again attacked them as reflecting a
bidding process that ``was a sham calculated to deliver Holly Farms
at any price to the bidder favored by management.''
   ``We ask that you consider our increased tender offer price and
our merger proposal...in light of certain undeniable facts _ namely
that the lock-up option and the termination fee provisions resulted
from a process which was neither fair nor an auction and clearly was
not intended to maximize value for Holly Farms stockholders,''
Chairman Don Tyson said in the letter.
   Holly Farms stock closed at $53.50 a share, up $1 in New York
Stock Exchange trading. Tyson dipped 50 cents a share to $15.50 in
national over-the-counter trading.
   Under the two-step transaction Tyson proposed, it would pay $53
cash and one-quarter share of Tyson stock, worth about $3.87{ at
Wednesday's price, for 93 percent of Holly Farms' outstanding
shares, or about 18.98 million shares. The remaining shares would be
converted into 3.56 shares of Tyson stock, worth $55.18 based on
Wednesday's price, in a subsequent merger.
   If its amended tender offer is accepted, Tyson said it could be
in position to close the deal as early as Dec. 16, when the offer is
scheduled to expire. The second step could be completed early next
year, Tyson said.
   Tyson also demanded that it be furnished all written information
furnished to ConAgra.
</TEXT>
