<2ND_LINE>BC-Philippines-Westinghouse, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0294,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippine Lawsuit Expected As Smokescreen, Westinghouse Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 new grafs to UPDATE with government saying it
will file suit Thursday. Picks up 3rd graf, The government...
DELETES 6th graf pvs, Officials of...as outdated.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp., bracing for an
expected lawsuit by the Philippines, said Wednesday the dispute
stems from politically motivated opposition to the nuclear power
plant it built under former President Ferdinand Marcos.
   The government of President Corazon Aquino has said it plans to
sue Westinghouse for damages and breach of contract regarding the
$2.3 billion plant, which never went into operation because of
alleged safety defects.
   A formal announcement of the suit was scheduled in Manila for
2:30 p.m. local time (1:30 a.m. EST) at the presidential palace.
   The government says the plant, 60 miles northwest of Manila in
Bataan province, is unsafe partly because of its design and its
location on an earthquake fault and near a volcano.
   The reactor's opponents also allege that bribes were paid over
the awarding of the prime contract for the plant.
   ``What we're finding here are the results of a political policy
that came to life when they were running for office,'' said
Nathaniel D. Woodson, general manager of the Westinghouse nuclear
fuels unit. ``They now feel they have a political albatross around
their neck and they're trying to blame us.''
   President Aquino's legal adviser, Adolfo Azcuna, said in late
October that the suit was ready and likely would be filed within a
month in the United States.
   In addition, a standstill agreement barring either the government
or the company from taking legal action, was to expire Thursday.
   Woodson and Deputy General Counsel Louis J. Briskman said
Philippines officials have acknowledged during private talks that no
matter how safe the plant is, they don't intend to allow nuclear
power production in the country.
   With all but $20 million to $30 million still due from Manila for
the power plant, Westinghouse could walk away from the 10-year-old
controversy, said Woodson. The bigger risk could be damage to the
company's international standing as a designer and builder of
nuclear power plants.
   ``All over the world we have built plants, and we haven't had
this problem. If they don't want to operate this plant, that's their
decision, but don't make Westinghouse a scapegoat,'' he said.
``Westinghouse will not be a scapegoat.''
   The company cites investigations by the U.S. Justice Department
and the Securities and Exchange Commission, which produced no
evidence to warrant charges.
   A safety study commissioned by the Aquino government _ a draft of
which was published by a trade journal _ concluded that the plant is
safe, Westinghouse said. But the government says the final report
concludes otherwise, although officials have refused to release the
document.
   The 620-megawatt plant, powered by a Westinghouse pressurized
water reactor, was completed three years ago.
   The project early on was shaken by allegations of kickbacks to
officials of the Marcos regime and by safety concerns.
   Communist rebels have bombed the transmission towers leading from
the plant, and people have cut and sold the copper lines as scrap.
The plant's corps of operators has largely disbanded, and
Westinghouse has only a handful of employees still in the
Philippines, Woodson said.
   Furthermore, the cost of the plant continues rising, Westinghouse
said. Interest on the loans the Philippines government took to build
the plant cost an estimated $300,000 per day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
