<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pillsbury 1stLd-Writethru f0218 11-30 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0218,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Top Executive Rejects Meeting With Unfriendly Suitor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBs 4th graf pvs Grand Met... with 2 new grafs to UPDATE with
response from Sheppard. Picks up 5th graf, Grand Met...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. said Wednesday it has sent a
letter to Grand Metropolitan PLC Chairman Allen Sheppard saying that
a $60-a-share takeover offer is inadequate and a meeting between
officials of the two companies would, therefore, ``serve no
purpose.''
   ``Following many hours of study, with the advice and assistance
of four respected financial advisers, the board has unanimously
determined that your $60-per-share offer is financially inadequate
and not in the best interests of Pillsbury and its shareholders,''
Philip L. Smith, Pillsbury's chairman and chief executive officer,
said in the letter.
   ``This conclusion is confirmed not only by Pillsbury's own
internal analysis and the advice of its financial advisors, but also
by the advice of your advisers who have put values in the high $60s
to low $70s on Pillsbury in documents that were disclosed publicly
in open court by your counsel,'' Smith wrote.
   Sheppard responded, in a letter Wednesday to Smith, by
reiterating his desire for a meeting and contending that Pillsbury's
characterization of Grand Met's offer as inadequate was flawed.
   Sheppard called the offer ``at the high end of the range of fair
values for Pillsbury'' based on analysis by Grand Met's investment
advisers, and noted that Pillsbury's advisers variously have valued
the company in the $50 a share range.
   Grand Met, a British liquor, gambling and speciality products
conglomerate, launched its $5.23 billion hostile takeover bid Oct.
4. Pillsbury's board of directors has rejected it as inadequate and
has refused to meet with Sheppard.
   In a Nov. 22 letter to Smith, Sheppard said Grand Met would like
a ``full and frank discussion'' with Pillsbury executives of Grand
Met's all-cash offer.
   Sheppard told Smith that although he has ``no reason to believe
that our $60-per-share offer is not fair and fully priced, I remain
prepared to negotiate all aspects of the proposal, including price.''
   In his response, Smith told Sheppard, ``Your reluctance to
provide a higher offer cannot be excused by saying you won't bid
against yourself. The Pillsbury board will only endorse an offer for
Pillsbury which reflects the values inherent in the company. Your
current offer does not.''
   On Monday, Hennepin County District Judge Thomas Carey took under
advisement renewed arguments from a Pillsbury shareholders group on
its request to have Pillsbury's ``poison pill'' defense invalidated,
force Pillsbury to negotiate with Grand Met and block the
Minneapolis-based food and restaurant company's planned spinoff of
its Burger King fast-food subsidiary.
   In his letter, Smith said, ``Our board's review of Pillsbury's
and Burger King's potential has confirmed that now is not an
appropriate time to sell Pillsbury, and that if the company were to
be sold in the future as two separate companies, substantially
greater values could be realized.''
   Smith concluded, ``The Pillsbury board remains committed to
value. Simply put, your $60-per-share offer does not represent the
values which the Pillsbury shareholders deserve. As long as the
framework for a meeting between ourselves is an inadequate offer
which you persist in claiming is fair and fully priced, a meeting
would serve no purpose.''
   Grand Met has said a separate Burger King would create a huge tax
liability for Grand Met if the takeover is successful. In addition,
Burger King franchisees have announced opposition to the plan,
saying it would add too much debt to the already troubled fast-food
chain.
   Grand Met on Monday extended its offer for a fifth time. The
tender offer now will expire at midnight EST Friday unless extended
again. By last Saturday, 85.3 percent of Pillsbury's outstanding
shares had been tendered and not withdrawn, Grand Met said.
</TEXT>
