<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0291 11-30 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0291,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Stocks Higher In Tokyo Morning Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei closing, later
dollar trading. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar declined against the Japanese yen in
Thursday morning trading, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main
market indicator rose to new highs.
   In midmorning trading, the dollar was changing hands at 121.52
yen after opening at 121.28 yen, down 0.57 yen from Wednesday's
close.
   The dollar fell Wednesday in New York after the Bank of England
put in a large sell order in an attempt to prevent the British pound
from rising against the West German mark, dealers said, effectively
pushing the dollar down.
   In Tokyo, market players were inclined to remain on the sidelines
ahead of the release of U.S. November unemployment figures,
scheduled for Friday in Washington, said a dealer with the Bank of
Tokyo.
   ``The dollar rose slightly after some trading companies bought
the currency for their payments, but the dollar-yen rate was not
moving very much,'' said the dealer, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which rose
260.60 points to a record close on Wednesday, gained another 94.26
points to finish morning trading at 29,673.16.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, share prices rose after an overnight
gain by the Dow Jones' industrial average in New York, dealers said.
   Market participants' buying interest helped boost share prices
despite some selling by traders attempting to cash in gains made
over the last two days, said a dealer with a major securities firm
in Tokyo.
   He said many investors believed there was less likelihood that
the U.S. Federal Reserve Board would raise its interest rates and
that in turn contributed to the stock-buying interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
